<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Confers with Crown Prince of Saudi Arabia (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Premier Zhu Rongji said here
today that China is satisfied with the noticeable growth of
Sino-Saudi Arabian relations in political, economic, cultural and
judicial fields.
</P>
<P>
He made the remark during his talks with Crown Prince Abdullah
Ibn Abdul Aziz Al Saud, deputy prime minister and head of the
National Guard of Saudi Arabia, here this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said the crown prince is the first leader of Saudi Arabia
to visit China since the establishment of the diplomatic ties
between the two countries in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The visit, a major event in Sino-Saudi Arabian relations, will
go down as a new chapter of friendship and cooperation between the
two countries, Zhu noted.
</P>
<P>
Crown Prince Adbullah first conveyed greeting from King Fahd to
the Chinese people, and said China is the closest friend of Saudi
Arabia, whose people have been following closely China's
contributions to world peace and the progressive cause of humanity.
</P>
<P>
Fairly big advances have been made in Sino-Saudi Arabian trade
relations after the forging of diplomatic ties between the two
countries and Saudi Arabia has become China's largest trade
partner in the West Asia-Africa region.
</P>
<P>
According to Zhu, the two economies are compatible with each
other with great potential to be tapped in the future. He
expressed the belief that the Crown Prince's China visit will
boost the economic and trade development between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Noting that China and Saudi Arabia are two major nations
respectively in East and West Asia and have adopted independent
foreign policy for peace, Zhu said that the two nations, sharing
similar and identical views on major international affairs, are
also making efforts to develop their national economy and improve
the living standards of their people. "We two have vast prospects
for cooperation in all fields," he acknowledged.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981015.0003 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Confers with Crown Prince of Saudi Arabia (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Crown Prince Abdullah agreed on Zhu's views on bilateral ties,
saying that his country attached importance to its relations with
China and hoped that his visit can enhanced such ties.
</P>
<P>
On Middle-east issue, Zhu said China is concerned with the
recent stalemate of Palestinian-Israeli peace talks. "The key to
end the stalemate hinges on the effective implementation of the
relative UN resolutions reached by all parties based on the
principle of 'Land for Peace' as it stipulated in Madrid
Conference," Zhu stressed.
</P>
<P>
Zhu noted that China appreciates Saudi Arabia's important
contributions to safeguarding the just rights and interests of the
Arab states and supporting the Palestinian people in their
struggle to recover its just national rights.
</P>
<P>
Zhu went on to say that China, as a permanent member of the UN
Security Council, will join efforts with international community
and urge relevant parties to adopt flexible and practical stance
in a bid to realize the thorough and just settlement of the Middle
East issue.
</P>
<P>
Crown Prince Abdullah said that Middle East peace process meet
with difficulties but he thought this situation "can not last
long." He expressed his belief that the just cause of the Arab
people will surely win the final victory. "As an influential
country in the world, China wins the respect of Arab countries,"
he said, adding that he hoped that China will continue to play a
still more important role in Middle East issue.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also had an exchange of views on Asian financial
crisis and other issues of common concern.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the talks, Zhu hosted a welcoming ceremony in honor of
Crown Prince Abdullah.
</P>
<P>
The crown prince and his party arrived here this afternoon for
an eight-day China visit at the invitation of Zhu.  
</P>
</TEXT>
