<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Official Defends Stability of HK Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, October 14 (Xinhua) --- Joseph Yam, chief executive
of Hong Kong Monetary Authority (HKMA) Wednesday expressed his
resolve to defend the stability of Hong Kong currency, brushing
aside accusations against HKMA's intervention in August to ward
off speculations on Hong Kong stock and contract market.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a luncheon jointly hosted by the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region Government and the Hong Kong Trade
Development Council, Yam said free markets do not mean that
markets can be freely manipulated.
</P>
<P>
"They need to be fair markets as well," he said. "We have a
responsibility to tackle market manipulation and avoid serious
market dislocation developing."
</P>
<P>
Turning to accusations that Hong Kong was trying to jack up the
market against trends dictated by fundamentals, Yam detailed on
the cause and effects of HKMA's move, saying the aim had been to
deter market manipulation, not to jack the market.
</P>
<P>
The HKMA's actions had been successful and there has been no
indication of further market manipulation since the end of August,
he noted.
</P>
<P>
"This (manipulation) can be highly damaging to the stability of
the whole financial system of Hong Kong," he said. "It also
presents the serious risk of undermining general confidence in our
currency."
</P>
<P>
He also repudiated the accusation that Hong Kong had
dangerously departed from the currency board discipline and
ventured into discretionary monetary management.
</P>
<P>
Joseph is in Singapore to attend the Seventh East Asia Economic
Summit which is organized by the Switzerland-based World Economic
Forum and the Economic Development Board of Singapore. The summit
ended this evening. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
