<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Primakov Sets Forward Anti-Crisis Measures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny
Primakov Wednesday outlined the concept of a government-proposed
anti-crisis program and the main problems confronting the country,
Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the Federal Council (upper house of parliament),
Primakov said it is important to pool efforts of the government
and regions to bring Russia out of the current difficult stage of
development.
</P>
<P>
He said the main problems in Russia now are wage and pension
arrears, which are the top question to be addressed, and the
paralysis of the banking system.
</P>
<P>
A considerable part of Russia's economy was not
functioning. The imports dropped by 75 percent, with those of
foodstuffs registering an even greater fall, Primakov said.
</P>
<P>
Primakov said taxes revenues sharply dwindled because of lack
of customs duties, the gross domestic products dropped by 16
percent, real incomes by 11 percent, and the ruble has devaluated.
</P>
<P>
Calling for a cooperation among regions in overcoming those
problems, Primakov said, "the country needs further privatization
programs to develop the real economy and improve living standards."
</P>
<P>
He suggested that regional leaders should cooperate with the
cabinet on this matter.
</P>
<P>
The next step is to disentangle non-payments between
enterprises, and that move will help revitalize the economy,
Primakov said.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister reported that the government-defined order
of debt repayment by organizations will be financed through the
federal budget.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of reorganization of the banking system, Primakov
said, "banks which survived the crisis will operate in the future,
too. Banks which are not viable at all will not survive in the
future either."
</P>
<P>
Primakov said Russia's taxes will be cut, including the
value-added tax and the income tax. The present system is being
streamlined to receive "sufficient" taxes from commodity
monopolies without damaging export, he said.
</P>
<P>
Primakov's address received support from the Federation
Council. Yegor Stroyev, Chairman of the Federation Council, said
the upper house supports Primakov's proposals on measures to
overcome the recent problems. The Federation Council will also put
forward its own proposals.
</P>
<P>
Stroyev said the cooperation between the government and the
heads of inter-regional associations will make it possible to find
the best way to make state decisions.
</P>
<P>
Russian Communist Party leader Gennady Zyuganov said Primakov
"demonstrated a pragmatic approach to the current situation."
</P>
<P>
He told reporters that the Communist Party will support
economic recovery measures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
