<HEADLINE> Plants May Help Extract Gold From Soil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Christopher Anderson of
Massey University in New Zealand and his colleagues said they have
found a way to sharply increase the amount of gold plants can
extract from the soil, reported the Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
Scientists have long known that plants can pull gold and other
metals out of the soil. But this "phytomining" typically occurs in
extremely low levels.
</P>
<P>
Anderson and his colleagues conducted a series of experiments
in which they added the chemical ammonium thiocyanate to the soil
of potted Indian mustard plants and found it sharply boosted the
amount of gold extracted. They said that the same way could work
for other plants as well.
</P>
<P>
They said that induced hyperaccumulation of gold appears to be
relatively independent of plant species, so it should be possible
to use plants that might be easy to grow on mine tailings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981015.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Beat China in Women's Basketball </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, China, October 14 (Xinhua)-- New Zealand upset hosts
China at the opening match of the four-team international women's
basketball tournament which kicks off Wednesday at the first leg
of Fengyang, An'hui.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese players exposed their shortfall of experience to
the visiting New Zealand opponents although they held a 44-39
into the second half.
</P>
<P>
The host, aged 22 on average, has kept their lead all the way
through the first half by exploring their speed to their
advantage, which is countered by the visitors with frequent
substitutes trying to keep themselves in the game.
</P>
<P>
The poor inside attacking cost the hosts greatly when the
visitors final took over the lead and snatched a 77-79 win.
</P>
<P>
In the other match on Wednesday, Chinese Taipei kept their
dominance to the final whistle with a 87-63 victory without
allowing any chance to the United States, represented by a ABL
professional club.
</P>
<P>
The United States boasted a repertoire of experience and
overshadowed their opponents with bigger sizes, only to be
outwitted by the winner with their well-ploted organization and
high shooting percentage.
</P>
<P>
The competition at this leg will span three days with two
games each day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
