<HEADLINE> APPCED Urged to Discuss Nuclear Waste Disposal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUILIN, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The Mexican and Iraqi delegates
suggested here today to add the issue of nuclear waste disposal to
the agenda of the next annual conference of a regional
environmental conference.
</P>
<P>
They made the remark in the Sixth Annual Meeting of the
Asia-Pacific Parliamentarians Conference on Environment and
Development (APPCED), to be opened tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
Armando Galvan Gazcon, a member of the Mexican delegation,
criticized the recent resolution passed by the U.S. Congress on the
disposal of nuclear waste along the U.S.-Mexican border.
</P>
<P>
Informed sources revealed the United States has allocated a
site to dump and treat nuclear established a nuclear waste dumping
facility a mere 20 miles to the U.S.-Mexican border. He cited the
American claim of the lack of any danger to Mexicans as simply
preposterous. He also mentioned an investigation conducted by
Mexicans living in the area which revealed that the facility does
threaten their health.
</P>
<P>
"If the facility is indeed safe, why did the U.S. Congress
refrain from approving the burial of nuclear waste in inland
areas, rather than on the U.S.-Mexican border?" Gazcon asked.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi delegates also addressed the issue, and suggested that
the next assembly in Thailand should discuss effective solutions
to problems related to nuclear pollution. More importantly,
according to the Iraqi delegation, discussion should center on how
to prevent the reoccurrence of a similar situation.
</P>
<P>
Peter Hodgson, acting president of the APPCED Executive
Committee and a member of the New Zealand House of
Representatives, said that the valuable suggestions are indeed
worthy of further discussion.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
