<HEADLINE> China on Nuclear Disarmament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 14 (Xinhua) -- China Wednesday called
on the two countries with the largest nuclear arsenals to
implement their bilateral agreements on nuclear disarmament as
soon as possible and further reduce their nuclear arsenals.
</P>
<P>
"This will not only have positive impact on international peace
and security, but also create favorable conditions for other
nuclear-weapon states to participate in the nuclear disarmament
process at an early date," said Chinese representative Li Changhe.
</P>
<P>
Li, China's ambassador for disarmament affairs, told the First
Committee of the 53rd Session of the U.N. General Assembly that as
a nuclear-weapon state, China never participates in nuclear arms
race, nor has it ever evaded its responsibility on nuclear
disarmament.
</P>
<P>
"We have all along stood for the complete prohibition and
thorough destruction of nuclear weapons, and has unilaterally and
unconditionally undertaken not to be the first to use nuclear
weapons, and not to use or threaten to use nuclear weapons against
non-nuclear weapon states or nuclear-weapons-free zones," he said.
</P>
<P>
Ambassador Li said, "We also call for the early conclusion of a
convention banning nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
"Through appropriate steps and phases, the reductions will be
achieved gradually from the larger arsenals to the smaller ones
until the ultimate objective of nuclear disarmament is
accomplished, freeing mankind from the menace of nuclear war," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981015.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1999 Employment Guidelines Adopted by Commission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Reforms on tax and benefit
systems, more open access to job market and better exploitation
of services sector job potential were the key points in the
employment guidelines adopted on Wednesday by the European
Commission for next year.
</P>
<P>
The commission, the executive body of the 15-nation European
Union, also stressed the importance of life-long learning and
reconciling work and family life in an effort to create more jobs
union-wide.
</P>
<P>
It proposed, as limited adjustments for next year's employment
policy, such active measures as to render jobs and job-related
education more attractive, to prepare a skilled and adaptable
workforce, to open labor market to all, to create more jobs in the
services sector and to pay more attention to affordable and
accessible high-quality care services to relieve workforce of its
family life concerns.
</P>
<P>
Commission officials said that though 800,000 new jobs were
added to the EU labor market in 1997, overall employment rate in
the union was still on the decline, compared with 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
In the late 1970s, the European Union employment rate was 64
percent whereas now the rate dropped to 60.5 percent. Employment
for the old and young people declined even more.
</P>
<P>
The European Union has taken employment as one of the crucial
tasks alongside the single currency and internal market.
</P>
<P>
The EU member states have worked out their individual
employment action plans and have to report to the commission on
their implementation of the national action plans on a yearly
basis.
</P>
<P>
European Employment Commissioner Padraig Flynn said that the
success of improving long-term employment union-wide depends on
the implementation of the measures agreed upon among member
states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
