<HEADLINE> Massive Funding Set for Controlling Huaihe River Pollution (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUILIN, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government plans to
allocate 15 billion yuan (1.8 billion US dollars) for the
construction of 57 water treatment plants along the seriously
polluted Huaihe River, according to Qu Geping, director of the
National People's Congress (NPC) Environment and Resources
Committee.
</P>
<P>
The massive plan calls for elimination pollution in the river
valley by the year 2000, Qu made the remarks just prior to the
opening of the Sixth Annual Assembly of the Asia-Pacific
Parliamentarians Conference on Environment and Development
(APPCED) on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He said the project will represent one of the major
environmental protection measures adopted by the Chinese
government.
</P>
<P>
Qu, an outstanding environmental worker in the ranks of
government, stressed that environmental protection is one of two
basic national policies.
</P>
<P>
"The government has adopted resolute measures in the regard,"
said Qu. China closed 63,000 polluting ventures over the past
three years, including more than 5,700 factories along the Huaihe
River.
</P>
<P>
China completed the first phase project to curb pollution along
the Huaihe river between 1994 and 1997. The second phase project
was launched last year. "All polluted water and sewage waste must
now meet drainage standards before release into the river,"
according to a local official.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981015.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Massive Funding Set for Controlling Huaihe River Pollution (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Qu noted that similar clean-up projects are being carried on
Taihu, Chaohu and Dianchi lakes, as well as along the Haihe and
Liaohe river and in Beijing area. Total government funding for the
period from 1996 to 2000 is expected to hit 450 billion yuan, or
1.3 percent of the nation's GDP. The investment scale basically
equals levels in most developed countries. "Central and local
government investments in environmental protection, combined with
bank loans, are expected to reach 100 billion yuan in 1998 alone,"
according to Qu.
</P>
<P>
Rapid economic growth and certain policies in effect at one
point seriously threatened China's environment and resource
protection efforts. Various localities witnessed deteriorating
water and air pollution, as well as serious soil
erosion. Pollution along the Huaihe River formerly adversely
affected the quality of potable water.
</P>
<P>
The National People's Congress and central government attach
great importance to the protection of the environment and
resources, and continuously improve supervision to ensure
implementation of related laws. The NPC has promulgated 15 laws
which have established a comprehensive legal system to guarantee
protection, said Qu.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, government at all levels have attached equal
priority to environmental protection and economic development. All
projects are subject to environmental appraisals and approval,
said Qu, adding that funding to curb pollution has been increased
on annual basis.  
</P>
</TEXT>
