<HEADLINE> Violators of Park Rules to Be Fined in S.Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The Kruger National Park, the
biggest nature reserve in South Africa, will fine visitors who
disobeyed rules of the partk up to 1,500 Rand (about 250 U.S. dollars)
per offence, South African Press Association (SAPA) reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The park said in a statement:"Reckless behavior endangers the
animals and has a negative impact on the environment and to our other
visitors' enjoyment of the wilderness qualities that the Kruger
National Park offers."
</P>
<P>
The park will no longer tolerate such abnormal behaviors, like
speeding, feeding of animals, littering, reckless driving, and
visitors alighting from their vehicles, the statement said, noting the
park does not want to undermine the safety of both visitors and
animals.
</P>
<P>
The managing authorities has instructed traffic officers, game
rangers and plain-clothed security personnel to be on the lookout for
such offenders, who would be fined up to 1,500 Rand or face a prison
sentence, SAPA said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
