<HEADLINE> Annan Urges More Preventive Efforts for Less </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 14 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan Wednesday called for more preventive strategies in
reducing natural disasters.
</P>
<P>
In a message to the International Day for Natural Disaster
Reduction, which falls on October 14 this year, the U.N. chief
said, "Preparedness measures for more efficient rescue operations
will remain necessary, but we must first turn much greater
attention to the introduction of preventive strategies aimed at
saving lives and protecting assets before they are lost."
</P>
<P>
"Science and technology play a central role in reducing the
economic and social consequences of natural hazards," he said.
"This year's observance of the International Day highlights the
importance of information in communicating these technical
abilities and in sharing practical experiences to make communities
safer."
</P>
<P>
"Almost daily, we are reminded of the threat of natural
disasters," Annan said, adding that since the beginning of the
year, "we have endured catastrophic floods in Asia, deadly
hurricanes in the Americas and the serious consequences of EL Nino
on several continents."
</P>
<P>
"While we cannot stop the forces of nature, we can and must
prevent them from turning into major social and economic
disasters," he said.
</P>
<P>
Natural disasters "profoundly affect our efforts to achieve
sustainable development," he said.
</P>
<P>
The theme of the International Day of Natural Disaster
Reduction this year is "Prevention and Media -- Prevention begins
with information." The International Day falls on the second
Wednesday of October each year.
</P>
<P>
This is the ninth year in the program for the International
Decade for Natural Disasters, adopted by the General Assembly in
1989 and refined at the World Conference on Disaster Reduction in
Yokohoma, Japan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
