<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Profile: Amartya Sen, "Conscience Keeper" of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Professor Amartya Sen, the
first Asian to win the Nobel Prize for economics Wednesday, has
won acclaim as "conscience keeper" of the world of economics by
probing into ethical and philosophical questions relating to
inequality and causes of poverty and famine.
</P>
<P>
Sen, 64, became a professor at the Jadhavpur University at just
24 and was a strong votary of social development and felt market
reforms had no meaning without it.
</P>
<P>
Sen, now in New York, was candid about India's economic reforms
and felt that despite overall economic growth, there was evidence
that economic expansion was not reaching the least fortunate in
the society.
</P>
<P>
Born on November 3, 1933, at Santiniketan, India's east state
of West Gengal, which was founded by another Indian Nobel laureate
Rabindranath Tagore, Sen has retained Indian citizenship despite
his long stay abroad as a professor.
</P>
<P>
Educated at Presidency College in Calcutta, 1,460 kilometers
Southeast of here, Sen went to Trinity College, Cambridge
University, where he acquired his bachelor and masters degrees and
doctorate.
</P>
<P>
He won the prestigious Adam Smith Prize, Wrenbury Scholarship
and Stevenson Prize at Trinity and later became master of the
college.
</P>
<P>
Sen, the sixth Indian to get Nobel Prize, has taught in his
motherland and various universities abroad including Harvard,
Oxford and London School of Economics.
</P>
<P>
As a versatile economist, Sen's writings ranged from choice of
technique, poverty, famine and inequality.
</P>
<P>
Sen returned to India in 1963 to teach at the Delhi School of
Economics for about nine years.
</P>
<P>
In his three decades of illustrious career, Sen held several
prestigious posts including presidentship of the American Economic
Association and International Economic Association.
</P>
<P>
He was also member of editorial boards of reputed journals like
Economica, Economics and Philosophy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981015.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lesotho Multi-Party Talks Seem to Be in Trouble </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Talks between Lesotho's
rival parties seem to be heading for trouble as the opposition
parties push for a transitional council while the ruling party is
firmly opposed to it.
</P>
<P>
The opposition alliance Wednesday called for the establishment
of the structure by an act of parliament before October 31, South
African Press Association (SAPA) reported.
</P>
<P>
The ruling Lesotho Congress for Democracy (LCD), however, said
it did not agree to such a structure because it is
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of the transitional council was proposed by
the Southern African Development Community (SADC) as the LCD and
its opposition rivals failed to agree on who should govern the
country before fresh general elections in 15 to 18 months.
</P>
<P>
The proposed council will have access to information held by
the government that is relevant to the elections. It will also
take decisions on all electoral matters including the role of the
police, the military, the intelligence, finance, foreign affairs,
and media and publications. It will review Lesotho's electoral
system and appoint a new Independent Electoral Commission.
</P>
<P>
In a document to be presented at the Lesotho multi-party talks
under way in Maseru Wednesday, the opposition alliance said the
council should have executive and other powers as agreed to by
the parties and conferred upon it by the act of parliament,
according to SAPA.
</P>
<P>
The document said the objectives of the council would include
to facilitate and promote the preparation and holding of new
elections not later than March 31, 2000.
</P>
<P>
It should also create and promote conditions conducive to free
and fair elections, ensure equal opportunities for all parties
seeking participation in the elections and eliminate any
impediment to political activities, including victimization of
employees on political grounds.
</P>
<P>
According to the opposition's proposal, the council should be
constituted by every party which fielded 40 or more candidates in
the May 23 elections. Each party should have three representatives.
</P>
<P>
The opposition also proposed that members of the council
should be paid a rate equivalent to that of government ministers.
</P>
<P>
In the document, the opposition alliance called for the review
and amendment of the country's constitution to provide for certain
measures including intervention by the head of state (the king)
in national crises such as the present one without reference
to any second party.
</P>
<P>
The parties also want the head of state to be declared the
commander-in-chief of the armed forces.
</P>
<P>
In its document presented to Wednesday's talks, the LCD said
the establishment of a transitional council would be tantamount
to overthrowing the country's constitution.
</P>
<P>
It argued that such a structure is irrelevant as Lesotho is
not in transition. Lesotho has an elected parliament and
government, it added.
</P>
<P>
The LCD also argued that nowhere in the would are political
parties empowered to conduct general elections.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's talks are chaired by South African Safety and
Security Minister Sydney Mufamadi. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981015.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
