<HEADLINE> First Trans-Asia-Europe Optical Fiber Cable in Operation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The first trans-Asia-Europe optical
fibre telecom cable directly linking Frankfurt of Germany with
Shanghai of China went into operation on Wednesday, the Germany
telecom group, Deutsche Telekom, announced.
</P>
<P>
According to a spokesman of the Deutsche Telekom, the
state-of-the-art optical fiber link, called Trans-Asia-Europe Optical
Fiber Cable System (TAE), is the longest terrestrial cable system in
the world with a total span of 17,000 kilometers, running from Shanghai
through Kazakhstan, Uzbekistan, Turkmenistan, Iran, Turkey, Ukraine,
Poland, Romania, Hungary, Austria to Germany.
</P>
<P>
Combined with national networks along the stretch, the cable will
be finally developed into a huge intercontinental network covering 20
countries in Asia and Europe.
</P>
<P>
Built by a consortium of telecom companies, including the Deutsche
Telekom and China Telecom, the cable is able to carry voice telephony
and data traffic with a capacity of twice 155-megabit per second,
equivalent to around 4,000 telephone calls made simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
The Deutsche Telecom said that the system could also be upgraded to
deal with the surge in telecom traffic in the future.
</P>
<P>
The investment on the TAE, including the final expansion, would run
up to about 600 million U.S. dollars, the company said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981015.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> General Assembly Meets on U.S. Embargo Against Cuba </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The 53rd General
Assembly (GA) session Wednesday convened a plenary meeting to
discuss the necessity of ending the economic, commercial and
financial embargo imposed by the United States on Cuba.
</P>
<P>
The meeting considered a report by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan, who submitted the report on September 3 at the request of a
GA resolution, adopted on November 5, 1997, which demanded an end
to the U.S. embargo against Cuba.
</P>
<P>
In the report, Annan listed replies he received from
governments on the issue, and most of the governments called for
an immediate end to such an embargo under the principle of the
U.N. Charter.
</P>
<P>
Yu Qingtai, member of the Chinese delegation, took the floor at
the plenary meeting to express the views of the Chinese government
on the issue, saying that "with the cold war behind us for quite a
few years, this situation should not be permitted to continue."
</P>
<P>
The General Assembly has repeatedly adopted resolutions calling
on all countries not to continue implementation of laws that are
contrary to the principles contained in the U.N. Charter and basic
norms of international relations, or detrimental to the legitimate
economic interests of third countries.
</P>
<P>
"It is regrettable that the government of the United States of
America has not responded positively to this appeal from the
international community, and has persisted in refusing to
implement the relevant U.N.G.A. resolutions," Yu said.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions and embargoes by the United States over the years
have created great difficulties to the Cuban people's endeavors to
achieve economic and social development, as well as their
restructuring process, he said.
</P>
<P>
"As a consequence, improvements in the living standards of the
Cuban people have been hampered, with particularly harmful effects
on the health and wellbeing of women and children," he said. "This
is clear violation of the human rights of the people of another
country."
</P>
<P>
"Furthermore, the unilateral actions by the U.S. have also
obstructed normal economic and trade relations between Cuba and
many other countries, causing damage to their legitimate rights
and interests," he said.
</P>
<P>
"With the cold war behind us for quite a few years, this
situation should not be permitted to continue. History has shown
us that differences among nations can be settled effectively only
through dialogue and negotiations on the basis of equality and
respect for each other's independent choices," he said.
</P>
<P>
"It is our hope that the United States would take constructive
action in line with the prevailing trend of our era," he added.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is expected to adopt a resolution, U.N. officials
said.
</P>
<P>
Washington has been maintaining the economic, commercial and
financial embargo against Cuba for nearly 40 years. The impact of
the entire policy, together with the Helms-Burton Act against
interested companies, has already cost the Cuban economy more than
60 billion U.S. dollars, representing about three times the value
of the country's gross domestic product. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981015.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
