<HEADLINE> U.S. Says Russians May Fly With NATO Over Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 14 (Xinhua) -- U.S. special envoy Richard
Holbrooke said Wednesday Russia had offered to fly reconnaissance
flights over Kosovo as part of the monitoring of a settlement of
the crisis.
</P>
<P>
"I might add, and say out here for the first time, that the
Russians have said they would like to fly with us, which would be
pretty amazing," said Holbrooke in an interview with the National
Broadcasting Company (NBC).
</P>
<P>
However, Holbrooke, who negotiated the settlement with Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic, gave no further details of Russia's
offer, or the U.S. response to such an offer.
</P>
<P>
Russia has strongly opposed military action against Yugoslavia.
It welcomed the Holbrooke-Milosevic agreement, under which the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) will provide aerial
verification of compliance on the ground.
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials say this will involve "unrestricted" NATO aerial
surveillance to quickly detect violations. Serb air defenses will
be removed from Kosovo or stored in cantonment areas to avoid any
threat to the surveillance flights.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Holbrooke-Milosevic agreement calls for a team
of 2,000 ground monitors to verify compliance, to be assembled by
the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE).
</P>
<P>
Russia, an OSCE member, will participate in the ground
inspection mission.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke said Milosevic was forced to make "enormous
concessions" in pledging to end Serbian attacks in Kosovo and
avoid NATO-sponsored air strikes.
</P>
<P>
"We came to the brink of war in the last few days in Europe --
the most serious crisis since the end of the Cold War. The planes
were on the runway and still are ready to go," he said.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke said that solutions to the violence in Kosovo lay in
the promises made by Milosevic buttressed by a future political
framework.
</P>
<P>
"I can see a way out of the crisis which is the fact that we
were about to go to war over Kosovo and now we've got something
better than war," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
