<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ARATS Official Reiterates One-China Principle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Tang Shubei, executive
vice-president of the Association for Relations Across the Taiwan
Strait (ARATS), said here today that the two sides across the
Taiwan Straits should first have mutual trust under the one-China
principle.
</P>
<P>
China's sovereignty and territorial integrity cannot be
separated, although the two sides have not yet got united, he
pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Both Wang Daohan, president of the ARATS, and Koo Chen-fu,
chairman of the Taiwan Straits Exchange Foundation (SEF), talked
about sincerity and mutual trust during their meeting today in
Shanghai, Tang said at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
There has been indeed disparity between the two sides on who
represents China since 1949, but there is a tacit agreement, or
mutual trust, between the two sides that there is only one China
in the world and Taiwan is part of China, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, the mutual trust was weakened somewhat in the 1990s,
especially since 1993, Tang noted, referring to the various
notions put forward by the Taiwan side, such as "one country, two
governments," "one country, two equal political entities," and so
on.
</P>
<P>
Tang noted we can't say there are "two Chinas" only because
China has not been reunified.
</P>
<P>
In referring to the interpretation of "one China," Tang said
his association had clarified it in a letter to the SEF on
November 16, 1992.
</P>
<P>
The ARATS held that "both sides of the Taiwan Straits adhere to
the one-China principle and seek peaceful reunification, but talks
on practical issues across the Taiwan Straits will not involve
political implication of one China," he said.
</P>
<P>
The SEF, however, said "in the course of seeking peaceful
reunification, both sides of the Taiwan Straits adhere to the one
China principle, but differ in the understanding of the one-China
concept."
</P>
<P>
The interpretations demonstrate that both sides are seeking
peaceful reunification and adhering to the one-China principle, he
emphasized.
</P>
<P>
Tang also quoted Wang as saying that both sides should make
joint efforts and hold negotiations on an equal footing on the
reunification under the one-China principle and that Taiwan's
political status can be discussed only under the one-China
principle.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
