<DOCNO> XIE19981015.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oil Search Resumed in Nigeria's Deep Offshore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Two joint oil companies in
Nigeria have resumed their drilling operation in the nation's
deep offshore after a year's break and are scheduled to drill two
more exploration wells in the next three months.
</P>
<P>
Under an exploration program, British Petroleum (Nigeria)
Limited (BP) and Norwegian Statoil Nigeria Limited will drill
three wells at a cost of 150 million U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
This is expected to raise their total investment in
exploration activities in deep offshore in 1994-1998, to 300
million U.S. Dollars, The Guardian newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Managing Director of BP Nigeria, Mark Eames, said that the
outcome of the current drilling operation, started last month,
will determine the fate of the eight-year-old alliance of the two
companies to hold on the two blocks assigned to the alliance by
the Nigerian government in 1991.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that results of the seismic data acquired by
them on the two blocks were believed to show that the two blocks
may contain hydrocarbon resources.
</P>
<P>
BP/Statoi drilling operations are coming in the wake of
similar efforts by another deep offshore operations of ELF
Petroleum in conjunction with Chevron, Exxon and Canadian
Petrolem.
</P>
<P>
In the past few years, about 22 exploration wells had been
drilled by some eight companies in Nigeria's deep water basin
estimated to boost the nation's oil production capability of 3
million barrels per day (bpd) by about 500,000 bpd.
</P>
<P>
But only eight out of the 22 wells, which cost between 30
million and 50 million Dollars each, have signs of oil stock in
commercial quantities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
