<HEADLINE> hke101481 -Taliban Agree to Free All Iranian Prisoners: UN Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The Afghan Taliban militia
Wednesday agreed to release all Iranian prisoners following
assurances from a special U.N. envoy that Iran would also free all
Taliban prisoners.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached during a four-and-a-half hour meeting
between visiting U.N. Special Envoy on Afghanistan Lakhdar Brahimi
and Taliban supreme leader Mohammad Omar in the militia's
headquarters of Kandahar.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a news conference at Islamabad Airport Wednesday
evening on his return from one-day long visit to Kandahar, Brahimi
said arrangements will be made to bring the Iranian prisoners from
Kandahar Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Brahimi said Omar expressed regret over the killing of Iranian
diplomats and condemned the incident and expressed readiness to
hold international inquiry into the killing of Iranian diplomats.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban leader also said that no Taliban commander was
involved in the murder of the Iranian diplomats and the Taliban
have already initiated probe to apprehend the killers.
</P>
<P>
Brahimi told Omar that the United Nations would back direct
contact between Iran and the Taliban to sort out their disputes.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a report reaching here from Kandahar quoted Taliban
spokesman Abdul Hae Mutmaen as saying that the Taliban had also
agreed to hold a face-to-face meeting with Iranian officials in
Jeddah, Saudi Arabia in a bid to normalize bilateral relations,
which have sharply deteriorated in recent months.
</P>
<P>
The meeting in Jeddah will be held soon under the auspices of
the 52-nation Organization of the Islamic Conference (OIC), the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Brahimi, who was accompanied by OIC Assistant Secretary General
Ibrahim Baker, described his talks with the Taliban's supreme
leader as "very promising."
</P>
<P>
"I am very, very hopeful," said Brahimi, who arrived in
Islamabad Thursday night from Tehran in a bid to defuse the
current tension between Iran and the Afghan Taliban.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. envoy, who flew into Kandahar Wednesday morning from
Islamabad, described his talks with Omar as "useful and
constructive" and said the talks would help reduce tension between
Iran and the Taliban.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of Osama Bin Laden, a Saudi dissident, Brahimi
said "we raised the issue of terrorism with the Taliban side and
Omar said that the Taliban condemn all types of terrorism
throughout the world."
</P>
<P>
"If the Taliban receive any substantial evidence about Osama's
involvement in terrorist activities, then the Taliban are ready to
put him on trial," Omar told Brahimi.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the two sides discussed U.N. difficulties in
Taliban- controlled areas and the investigation into the murder of
a U.N. official in Kabul in August.
</P>
<P>
According to the envoy, Omar reiterated the Taliban's stand to
put complete ban on poppy cultivation in Afghanistan if the
Taliban are recognized.
</P>
<P>
In this regard, Brahimi said he assured the Taliban leader that
the U.N. is ready to help Afghan growers in substitution of poppy
crops with others. 
</P>
</TEXT>
