<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AIDS Threatens S. Africa's Demography: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The spiraling rate of HIV
infection and AIDS among South African women of child-bearing age
had dire implications for the country's demography, a survey
released Wednesday warned.
</P>
<P>
The highest incidence of HIV infection (20 percent) was found
in women in the 20 to 24 age group in 1997. An estimated 18
percent of women in the 25-29 age group were infected, according
to the survey conducted by the South African Institute of Race
Relations.
</P>
<P>
The high HIV infection rate among child-bearing women
threatens the country's demography because about a third of
children born to HIV-positive mothers would be infected at birth,
while more will be infected through breast-feeding, which is
common in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
In KwaZulu-Natal Province, which has the worst HIV-AIDS
situation, an estimated 26.9 percent of women attending antenatal
clinics were HIV-positive in 1997, against a national average of
16.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
The survey quoted a senior life insurance manager, Janina
Slawski, as saying that by 2010, South Africa's average life
expectancy could be reduced from 62 to 40 years.
</P>
<P>
She said when the epidemic peaked, between 2005 and 2010, an
estimated six million people would be HIV-positive, and 600,000
would have developed full-blown AIDS over that period.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
