<DOCNO> XIE19981015.0039 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mixed Reaction in Yugoslavia on Kosovo Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The agreement struck Tuesday
by Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic and U.S. envoy Richard
Holbrooke on the Kosovo crisis has received mixed reaction in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Emerging from his final meeting with Holbrooke, Milosevic told
the nation in a televised address that the agreement removed the
threat of military intervention against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The Serbian government endorsed the agreement the same day at a
special cabinet session, saying it provided a basis for a lasting
political solution to the autonomy of Kosovo within Serbia.
</P>
<P>
The ruling Socialist Party of Serbia and the Yugoslav Left
hailed the agreement as "a victory of a principled and
well-founded policy" pursued by President Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
The deal averted a possible NATO air strike and protected the
country's territorial integrity and independence.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the Kosovo provisional executive council Zoran
Andjelkovic said Wednesday in the Kosovo capital Pristina that the
council would fully comply with the agreement to reach a peaceful
resolution to the crisis in the southern Serbian province.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia's official Tanjug news agency quoted Andjelkovic as
saying he was confident that "the majority of citizens -- ethnic
Albanians, Serbs and members of all other ethnic groups --
welcomed the agreement" which, he said, was in the interest of
peace and security in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Dragan Tomic, Serbia's parliament speaker, congratulated
Milosevic and said, "We are satisfied and happy that what we
wanted has been achieved... Sovereignty of the state, territorial
integrity and national dignity has been preserved."
</P>
<P>
But opposition parties, although supporting a peaceful
solution, criticized Milosevic for being irresponsible in the
negotiation that led to the agreement for the Organization for
Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) mission to be deployed
in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"With bad leadership of the country, he (Milosevic) brought us
to the brink of war and was forced to give huge concessions," the
Democratic Party said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In Kosovo, the ethnic Albanians who are ready to die for the
independence of the province were against the agreement. They
still insisted on a full independence from Serbia or at least a
three-year transition that will allow them to have a full control
over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Veton Surroi, an editor of the ethnic Albanian newspaper Koha
Ditore, said, "The deal is not linked to a serious political
negotiating process. It reinforces Milosevic's authority on the
ground."
</P>
<P>
While in Belgrade, some people said Milosevic had saved the
nation's integrity and averted NATO air strikes while others
thought he had sold out the country, for with the agreement Kosovo
will eventually be governed by the ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
"I am satisfied with the agreement because I don't need to go
to Kosovo to fight for the integrity of Serbia," a student at
Belgrade University said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
