<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda, Rwanda Reiterate Joint Stance on DRC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Uganda and Rwanda, who have
been accused by Congolese President Laurent Kabila of fomenting
and backing the armed rebellion in the Democratic Republic of
Congo (DRC), have reaffirmed their stance on this ten-week-long
conflict.
</P>
<P>
The two neighbors made a statement Wednesday evening after
Rwandan Vice-president Paul Kagame paid a one-day working visit
to Uganda, a press release from the President's Office said.
</P>
<P>
During talks with President Yoweri Museveni, Kagame explained
his concern about the continuing insecurity in his country caused
by former Rwanda Armed Forces (ex-FAR) and Interahamwe militia
based in the DRC, as well as state-inspired acts of genocide and
ethnic cleaning of targeted groups of people in the DRC.
</P>
<P>
Museveni reiterated that Uganda's military presence in eastern
part of the DRC is based on a mutually agreed arrangement between
the two governments and is aimed at flushing out Ugandan rebels
having rear bases there.
</P>
<P>
Both parties strongly condemned the involvement of the
terrorist regime of Sudan in the conflict and questioned the
wisdom of any continued support for the Kabila-Sudan alliance.
</P>
<P>
They also dismissed with contempt the "baseless" theories and
"falsehoods" propagated by Kabila and some of his allies to cover
up the real issues underlying the conflict.
</P>
<P>
They agreed that it was the two issues of supporting terrorist
groups and planning to commit genocide that had caused the two
countries to be in conflict with the Mobutu regime in 1996/1997.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the two leaders also exchanged views on
issues concerning closer bilateral relations and how to
streamline methods of work to make cooperation in all fields more
co-ordinated.
</P>
<P>
The statement added that Uganda will maintain its military
presence in eastern DRC until a government of the DRC accepted by
all the belligerent parties and opposition groups is in place or
the Organization of Africa Unity puts in place an alternative
arrangement.
</P>
<P>
Two weeks after the rebellion, foreign troops from Zimbabwe,
Angola, Namibia, Chad and Sudan were invited to fight for Kabila
government. Now there are more than 8,000 foreign troops fighting
alongside Kabila forces.
</P>
<P>
Uganda and Rwanda strongly oppose foreign intervention in the
DRC crisis. The latest report said that the Tutsi rebels, who
have reportedly been supported by these two neighbors of DRC, had
retaken Kindu, a big city in eastern DRC which had been used by
government forces to fight rebels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981015.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Agency to Double Fund in Helping Ugandan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The International Fund for
Agricultural Development (IFAD) has decided to extend and double
fund for another four years to save Ugandan orphans.
</P>
<P>
A press release issued Wednesday evening by the Ugandan
Presidential Office said the decision was made by IFAD President
Fawzi Al-Sultan when he paid a courtesy call on Ugandan First
Lady Janet Museveni here.
</P>
<P>
The IFAD president is on a five-day official visit to the east
African country.
</P>
<P>
IFAD acts as an intermediary for the administration of the
Belgian funding to Third World countries. Through IFAD, the
Belgians have funded the Uganda Women's Efforts to Save Orphans
(UWESO) to implement the UWESO Development Project for the last
four years.
</P>
<P>
The project has assisted rural women in Uganda who take care
of orphans to acquire skills to generate income for their
households.
</P>
<P>
The official thanked the first lady for initiating and
sustaining the project, and said his organization has much
confidence in the work carried out by Ugandan women.
</P>
<P>
Janet Museveni, who is the founder and patron of UWESO,
thanked the Belgians and IFAD for their strong faith in the
project and their generous assistance which has enabled UWESO to
reach out to the needy in Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Fawzi Al-Sultan, who arrived Tuesday, will also launch a
vegetable oil development project in Uganda during his stay in
the country.
</P>
<P>
IFAD is a specialized agency of the United Nations based in
Rome, Italy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
