<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mubarak Says Openness Characterizes His Reign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
Wednesday said that openness, freedom of the press, strengthening
democracy and supporting low-income people have always been the
key basis of his 17-year rule.
</P>
<P>
Talking to reporters at an airbase west of Cairo, Mubarak said
that had it not been for the principle of openness, Egypt could
not have had got what it has now.
</P>
<P>
He said that some of his associates were of the view that he
should paint hope in his political speeches. "But I have kept
wondering how to give the people hope while the true picture was
bad. Had we painted to the people a beautiful picture they would
have blamed the state for embarking on reform or raising prices,"
said Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
For years, only the government, political parties and
government-approved companies had been allowed to run newspapers
in Egypt. But in 1996, as Egypt pushed to open its economy to
foreign investment, the government eased control and allowed
independent newspapers to publish.
</P>
<P>
That led to a boom, with 107 newspapers, most small and local,
hitting the stands. And some began to take up previously taboo
subjects such as government corruption and Muslim-Christian
tensions.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak said Egypt maintains the freedom of the press, and the
public opinion has come to learn how to "differentiate between the
poor and good quality of things."
</P>
<P>
The president, who is also supreme commander of the Armed
Forces, made the remarks after inspecting the shooting ground of
the Air Force as part of the celebrations of the Air Forces Day
which fell on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak has one year to go before his third-term six-year
presidency ends. He assumed the post in 1981 immediately after his
predecessor Anwar Sadat was assassinated.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has since started a vigorous economic reform program to
attract foreign investors and privatize state-owned
companies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
