<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Find Giant Iceberg Born in Antarctica </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 14 (Xinhua) -- British scientists have found a
giant iceberg which has broken off an Antarctic ice shelf.
</P>
<P>
Researchers from the British Antarctic Survey (BAS) said that
they identified the iceberg, about 150 km by 30 km, Tuesday after
reviewing image collected by the U.S. NOAA weather satellite.
</P>
<P>
The iceberg, which has broken off Ronne Ice Shelf, in the
Weddell Sea, is four times the size of the last large iceberg to
calve in the region which came from Larsen Ice Shelf.
</P>
<P>
The break is a "normal event" in the Antarctic region and the
iceberg is probably the largest one discovered in the local region
in the past few years, Dr Lachlan-Cope, from the BAS's Cambridge
headquarters said Wednesday in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
The newly-born iceberg is grounded right now, Dr Lachlan-Cope
said, eventually it may drift into the south Atlantic in two or
three seasons and break up there in a very short time.
</P>
<P>
Ice shelves are found retreating on the Antarctic peninsula.
Researchers from the BAS predicted in 1996 that the region of
Ronne Ice Shelf was at risk and was likely to calve within a
decade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
