<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Against Proliferation of Mass Destruction Weapons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 14 (Xinhua) -- China Wednesday
reiterated its position of supporting international efforts to
prevent the proliferation of weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
Ambassador for Disarmament Affairs Li Changhe told the First
Committee of the 53rd Session of the U.N. General Assembly that
China has improved its export control system through new
regulations.
</P>
<P>
As a state party to the Treaty on the Non-Proliferation of
Nuclear Weapons, the Biological Weapons Convention and the
Chemical Weapons Convention, China has faithfully honored its
obligations and imposed strict control on the export of sensitive
items and their production technologies and equipment, he said.
</P>
<P>
In the past two years, the Chinese government has promulgated
the Regulations on the Supervision and Control of Chemicals, the
Regulations on Nuclear Export Control, and the Regulations on the
Control of the Export of Duel-Use Nuclear Materials and Related
Technology.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Li said, China applies strict control to the transfer
of conventional military equipment and related technologies, and
has issued the Regulations on the Control of the Export of
Military Products in October 1997.
</P>
<P>
"Preventing the proliferation of weapons of mass destruction
and promoting international cooperation in the peaceful use of
sciences and technologies are just two sides of one coin," Li
said, noting that they should complement rather than exclude each
other.
</P>
<P>
The international non-proliferation efforts should be fair and
rational, and should not apply double standards whereby
non-proliferation is used as a pretext to infringe upon the
legitimate rights and interests of other nations, Li added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
