<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Mixed Tones on Coming U.S. Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Hours before Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu leaves for Washington for talks with
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, officials and parties here were
expressing various views on the U.S.-brokered summit.
</P>
<P>
While U.S. officials said it is time for a settlement over the
second Israeli withdrawal from the West Bank, members of the
Israeli delegation were cautioning against pressure on Israel.
</P>
<P>
As hardliners stepped up pressure on Netanyahu not to make
concessions to the Palestinians, the main opposition Labor Party
declared that it will support Netanyahu if he reaches an agreement.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Ariel Sharon stressed that people should not
expect quick results in the U.S. talks, saying although Israel
wants peace, the negotiations will take time. "It is not a short
procedure," he said.
</P>
<P>
He was echoed by Trade and Industry Minister Natan Sharansky,
who, like Sharon, is also a member of Netanyahu's inner cabinet.
Sharansky described as "unhealthy" the great expectation for the
summit all over the world, saying it would result in pressure on
Israel.
</P>
<P>
"It's not our obligation to get back with an agreement. If we
are not able to get cooperation of the Palestinians on security
issues...there will be no agreement," he said.
</P>
<P>
Both Sharon and Sharansky will accompany Netanyahu to the
U.S. and take part in the negotiations, due to begin Thursday at
Wye Plantation near Washington and last into next week.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the U.S. Embassy in Israel, however, said
while the Clinton administration understands Israel's concerns
over the high expectation, it hopes the two sides will take "hard
decisions" in the talks in order to clinch a deal.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton is trying to persuade Netanyahu and
Arafat to conclude an agreement over a 13 percent Israeli
withdrawal from the West Bank during the U.S. summit.
</P>
<P>
"We can't expect everything to be resolved in a short meeting,
but in the other hand, we can't expect the existing situation to
continue forever," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
In the Knesset (parliament), nine lawmakers from the ruling
coalition signed a petition Wednesday to Netanyahu asking him not
to hand over land to the Palestinians unless they fulfill their
commitments under signed agreements.
</P>
<P>
This move added to the pressure already put on Netanyahu by his
right-wing partners.
</P>
<P>
The National Religious Party, the extreme rightist in the
coalition, has threatened to topple the government if Netanyahu
signs an agreement without meeting their conditions. The party
asked Netanyahu to make sure that the Palestinians extradite
suspects in attacks on Israelis and abolish the clauses in the
Palestinian Covenant calling for Israel's destruction.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Land of Israel Front, a group of rightist
legislators crossing party lines, has announced that from the
moment the government decides on withdrawal, it will take every
opportunity to bring down the government.
</P>
<P>
But Labor leader Ehud Barak promised Wednesday that Netanyahu
can count on the support of his party if he returns from
Washington with a redeployment deal.
</P>
<P>
The Labor party will provide Netanyahu with a "safety net" if
the Knesset turns a vote on the agreement to a no-confidence vote
on the government, although this does not mean the Labor supports
the policy of Netanyahu's government, Barak said.
</P>
<P>
With the support of the Labor, which has 34 seats in the
Knesset, Netanyahu will be secured a parliamentary majority in the
120-seat parliament if he presents an agreement for
approval. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
