<HEADLINE> China for Landmine Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 14 (Xinhua) -- China said Wednesday
that it is in favor of imposing proper and reasonable control on
landmines to protect innocent civilians from injuries by these
weapons.
</P>
<P>
Ambassador for Disarmament Affairs Li Changhe told a U.N.
session here that the most pressing issue at present is to assist
mine-affected countries to remove remaining mines that still
threaten civilian lives.
</P>
<P>
He recalled that President Jiang Zemin declared during his
visit to Canada last November that China will actively participate
in international mine clearance efforts.
</P>
<P>
Despite additional spending on flood fighting and disaster
relief this year, China still decides to contribute 100,000 U.S.
dollars to the U.N. Voluntary Trust Fund for Assistance in Mine
Clearance, which will be earmarked for demining activities in
Bosnia and Herzegovina, Li said.
</P>
<P>
In cooperation with relevant U.N. departments, China will host
two training courses on mine clearance in the next two years when
Chinese experts will provide technical training to students from
mine-affected countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
China will also provide mine-detection and mine-clearance
equipment to those countries, Li added.
</P>
<P>
He told the session that China ratified the amended Landmine
Protocol and the newly annexed Protocol on Blinding Laser Weapons
to the Convention on Certain Conventional Weapons on 29 August
1998.
</P>
<P>
"China will formally deposit its instruments of ratification of
the above-mentioned two protocols with the secretary-general of
the United Nations," Ambassador Li declared. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
