<HEADLINE> Ambassador: U.S. Investors Have Growing Interest in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 14 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Ambassador to Egypt Daniel
Kurtzer said Wednesday the American companies and investors have
a growing interest in employing their funds in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
He was speaking at a joint news conference here with the
director of the U.S. Agency for International Development (USAID)
Joseph Grandmaison.
</P>
<P>
Referring to related American studies, the ambassador said the
findings show that Egypt is increasingly attracting American
investments as its economy keeps improving.
</P>
<P>
He estimated American investments in Egypt at 2.2 billion dollars,
maintaining that expectations are high that the investments volume
will jump to a worth of 3 billion dollars in the near future.
</P>
<P>
Within this framework, five American companies had sent
delegations to see the possibility of launching projects in Toshka
in Upper Egypt, an area which is witnessing implementation of a
giant Egyptian development project.
</P>
<P>
He said the number of American companies operation in Egypt
increased from 220 to 229 in the past nine months only.
</P>
<P>
The director of the USAID, at the news conference, said up to
52 investment projects at a worth of 10 billion dollars were
submitted for study for the Egyptian and American investors
participating in a conference which opened earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
The conference, which followed a U.S. government decision to
cut economic assistance to Egypt, is designed to encourage
American private sector to increase investment in the country.
</P>
<P>
U.S. assistance to Egypt and Israel will be reduced by five
percent as of 1999. The drop in the annual U.S. aid to Egypt
from 815 million dollars to 775 million dollars is a move the
U.S. Congress is undertaking in view of skinny U.S. budget
resources.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. foreign aid budget has been including 815 million
dollars for Cairo, and 1.2 billion for Tel Aviv, in addition to
the aid earmarked for international organizations. Cairo also gets
an 1.3 billion dollars in military aid from Washington every year.
</P>
<P>
Egypt and the U.S. have hold an array of talks in both Cairo
and Washington since July on establishing a new system of
cooperation that puts emphasis on enhancing economic and trade
cooperation and rescheduling the aid program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
