<HEADLINE> Eritrea Pledges to Comply with Arbitration Decision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANAA, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Eritrean President Issayas
Aferwerki has reiterated that Asmara will comply with the results
of the international arbitration over its disputed Red Sea islands
with Yemen.
</P>
<P>
Aferwerki expressed the stance in a message to Yemeni President
Ali Abdullah Saleh, the Yemeni News Agency said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The message was conveyed to Saleh Wednesday by visiting
Eritrean Minister of Trade and Industry Ali Sayed and Minister of
Foreign Affairs Wald Telmisani.
</P>
<P>
Yemen clashed with Eritrea in December 1995 when Eritrean
troops took over most of the Red Sea Hanish Archipegalo. In May
1996, Eritrea accepted a France-brokered accord to seek
international arbitration on the issue.
</P>
<P>
Last Friday, both sides said that they accepted the decision of
a London-based International Arbitration Panel, which awarded the
bulk of the islands to Yemen.
</P>
<P>
In the message, Aferwerki voiced keenness on establishing
close, cooperative ties of good neighborliness with Yemen that not
only benefit the two countries but also regional peace, security
and stability.
</P>
<P>
Aferwerki also invited Saleh to visit Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Saleh echoed Aferwerki's words in his meeting
with Eritrean officials, saying Yemen is willing to open a new
page in relationship with Eritrea for a more prosperous future.
</P>
<P>
Saleh expressed thanks for Aferwerki's invitation, saying he
will visit Eritrea at an appropriate time.
</P>
<P>
Aferwerki met a high-ranking Yemeni delegation led by Deputy
Prime Minister and Foreign Minister Abdel-Kadir Bagmal Tuesday.
This was the first visit by a ministerial Yemeni official since
December l995.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that the two countries are taking concrete steps
to improve bilateral relations, such as resuming their diplomatic
ties to the ambassadorial level and reopen air link. 
</P>
</TEXT>
