<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Welcomes Kosovo Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
welcomed the current turn in the Kosovo event, Prime Minister
Yevgeny Primakov said Wednesday after meeting with the president
in the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
Primakov told reporters that Yeltsin praised the civil action
of the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE)
in Kosovo and instructed Russian officials to continue working in
the same direction.
</P>
<P>
He said Russia's position is effective now and lessening
tension around Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Recalling the stand taken by Russia in the settlement of the
Iraqi crisis and during the developments in Kosovo, Primakov said,
"We have stated point-blank that if an air strike is dealt at
Yugoslavia, our attitude to NATO will be dramatically changed, and
there will be many changes in our orientation."
</P>
<P>
Primakov said that he also reported to the president the main
issues of the government's performance.
</P>
<P>
The president paid special attention to the fulfillment by the
government of its obligations concerning the current payouts to
public-sector workers, the army, and pensioners, according to
Primakov.
</P>
<P>
Asked about the health of Yeltsin, Primakov said, "The
president feels well." He "waved aside our remarks when we
reminded him of the need of stay in bed and have a thorough rest,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
The meeting with Yeltsin was also attended by Foreign Minister
Igor Ivanov, who has now left for Paris to attend a session of the
Contact Group on Yugoslavia, and Defense Minister Igor Sergiyev.
</P>
</TEXT>
