<DOCNO> XIE19981015.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> General Assembly Urges U.S. to End Embargo Against Cuba </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The 53rd General
Assembly (GA) session Wednesday voted 157-2 to adopt a resolution
calling for an end to Washington's nearly four-decade economic
embargo against Cuba.
</P>
<P>
The United States and Israel voted against the resolution, with
12 countries abstaining.
</P>
<P>
The resolution reiterated its call for all nations to "refrain
from promulgating and applying laws and measures" on the embargo
against Cuba.
</P>
<P>
The resolution once again urged "states that have and continue
to apply such laws and measures to take the necessary steps to
repeal or invalidate them as soon as possible in accordance with
their legal regime."
</P>
<P>
The resolution requested the U.N. secretary-general, in
consultation with the appropriate organs and agencies of the
United Nations system, to prepare a report on the implementation
of the present resolution in the light of the purposes and
principles of the U.N. Charter and international law, and to
submit it to the General Assembly at its fifty-fourth session.
</P>
<P>
The resolution voiced the GA decision to include in the
provisional agenda of its fifty-fourth session in the item
entitled "Necessity of ending economic, commercial and financial
embargo imposed by the United States against Cuba."
</P>
<P>
Before voting, the Cuban foreign minister took the floor at the
plenary meeting of the 53rd GA session.
</P>
<P>
The General Assembly has made the embargo-ending appeal for
seven years in a row, but Washington, citing Cuba's alleged
violation of human rights, insisted on maintaining the embargo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
