<HEADLINE> Russian FM leaves for Paris Contact Group Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign Minister Igor
Ivanov left for Paris Wednesday to attend a meeting of the Contact
Group on the Kosovo crisis, according to the Itar-Tass news
agency.
</P>
<P>
The meeting attended by the foreign ministers of the six-nation
Contact Group, the United States, Britain, Italy, France, Germany
and Russia, will hear U.S. special envoy Richard Holbrooke's
report on the results of his talks with Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic and a report by Polish Foreign Minister
Bronislaw Geremek, who is now the chairman in office of the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE).
</P>
<P>
The ministers are expected to discuss the details of the
agreement on Kosovo reached by Holbrooke and Milosevic, the
implementation of the agreement and the role to be played in this
process by the United Nations, the OSCE and NATO.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that one of the main goals of the meeting is to
work out a mechanism of "verification and control" over the
implementation of the Kosovo accords.
</P>
<P>
Before his departure to Paris, Ivanov told reporters that
President Boris Yeltsin insists that Russian diplomats remain
vigilant and keep all attention on Kosovo because "there are signs
of a positive turn towards political settlement."
</P>
<P>
However, the president noted, the ultimate threat of combat
operation is still there. "Therefore, our task is to firm up this
positive trend and make sure that the political dialogue
continues," Invav quoted Yeltsin as saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
