<DOCNO> XIE19981015.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House Panel May Streamline Impeachment Investigation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The chairman of the
Judiciary Committee of the U.S. House of Representatives said
Thursday that he will try to streamline the panel's impeachment
inquiry by focusing on the "core charges" against President Bill
Clinton: lying under oath, obstruction of justice and witness
tampering.
</P>
<P>
Representative Henry Hyde, a Republican, said his goal is to
finish the inquiry by the end of the year -- a goal he has
expressed before, even while opposing Democratic attempts to set
strict time limits on the investigation.
</P>
<P>
The White House suggested Hyde is floating a trial balloon for
political reasons.
</P>
<P>
The House voted 258-176 last week to authorize the inquiry
without limits by time or subject.
</P>
<P>
"The committee is attempting in this initial phase of the
impeachment inquiry to establish a process for completing the
inquiry by the end of the year," Hyde said Thursday in a written
statement. "This requires streamlining its work to focus on the
core charges against the president of lying under oath,
obstruction of justice and witness tampering."
</P>
<P>
But Hyde said the year-end goal could not be met without
cooperation from the White House and committee Democrats.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the chairman said in an interview with The Washington
Post Tuesday that the 15 potential grounds for impeachment --
detailed by the committee's chief investigator last week -- may be
pared down to meet the voluntary deadline.
</P>
<P>
White House press secretary Joe Lockhart said Thursday,
"Expansion of charges last week probably was done with politics in
mind on the House floor. And floating the idea of reducing them
probably has something to do with politics this week."
</P>
<P>
Lockhart said any serious process must first look at setting
the standards of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
David P. Schippers, the Judiciary Committee's chief counsel,
outlined the 15 separate allegations last week, adopting 10 of the
11 grounds for impeachment recommended by Independent Counsel
Kenneth Starr and offering four from the panel's Republican staff
for the committee to consider. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981015.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SPD, Greens Agree to Liberalize German Citizenship Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Chancellor-elect Gerhard
Schroeder's Social Democratic Party (SPD) and the Greens party
agreed Wednesday to liberalize Germany's citizenship law to make
it easier for the nation's 7 million foreigners to integrate into
German society.
</P>
<P>
The agreement reached between the SPD and Greens would allow
third-generation foreigners who are born here to get German
passports automatically while keeping the nationality of their
parents at the same time.
</P>
<P>
In addition, foreign immigrants would be able to apply for
German citizenship after eight years instead of the current 15
years of waiting period.
</P>
<P>
Kerstin Mueller, a Greens leader, described the accord as a
clear signal for earlier integration of foreigners living in
Germany.
</P>
<P>
The children of immigrants from Turkey, Yugoslavia, Italy and
Greece who began arriving in the 1950s during the post-war
economic boom have largely transformed Germany into a
multicultural society in recent years.
</P>
<P>
There are currently about 7.4 million foreigners living in
Germany out of a total population of 82 million, more than any
other European nation.
</P>
<P>
The conservative party of Chancellor Helmut Kohl, who was
defeated by Schroeder's SPD in general elections on September 27,
has so far resisted efforts to alter the citizenship law dating
back to a 1913 imperial edict that bases nationality on bloodlines
rather than birthplace.
</P>
<P>
Both the SPD and Greens believe that loosening the citizenship
law would help ease social tensions given the booming foreign
population.
</P>
<P>
The two parties are currently in negotiations to form a
center-left coalition government in Bonn. If a deal could be
reached, the new government is due to be sworn in at the end of
October. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981015.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Humanitarian Work Resumes in Kosovo After Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, October 14 (Xinhua) -- International aid agencies
began massive relief efforts to save the lives of tens of
thousands of ethnic Albanian refugees in Kosovo, according to
reports from the Kosovo capital of Pristina Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The move came just hours after Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic and U.S. special envoy Richard Holbrooke struck a deal
to end Serbian military action in Kosovo and allow refugees to
return home.
</P>
<P>
Fernando Del Mundo, spokesman for the UNHCR, said, "Time is
running out for us, but some ethnic Albanian refugees are too
scared to come out of forests and into towns."
</P>
<P>
About 250,000 ethnic Albanians have left their homes since the
conflict flared up in March in Kosovo between Serb forces and the
Kosovo Liberation Army. Humanitarian work was severely hindered by
the seven-month-long conflict.
</P>
<P>
"It's crucial that we're able to help them. People are still
out in the open without proper clothes, some of them barefoot,"
Mundo said, adding the relief work became urgent as winter
approaches.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, the European Union's special envoy to
Kosovo, Wolfgang Petrisch, met Ibrahim Rugova, leader of the
Kosovo Albanians, and urged him to support the peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
"This is a big chance for the Kosovo Albanian side and they
should take this up," Petrisch said after talks with Rugova in
Pristina.
</P>
<P>
Petrisch was the first senior Western official to meet the
Albanian leadership since Tuesday's breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a spokesman of the U.N. Liaison Office in Belgrade
said Wednesday that to follow closely the agreement, U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan would send a mission to Yugoslavia in
the next few days for further discussion on the Kosovo issue.
</P>
<P>
Spokesman Jay Carter told a press conference in Belgrade that
the agreement reached Tuesday would mean much for a peaceful
solution to the problems in Kosovo, and would contribute to a
better future for Yugoslavia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
