<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poll: Voters Likely to Back Incumbents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Incumbents of the U.S. House
of Representatives are in good shape to win re-election in
November, said a poll released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The USA Today/CNN/Gallup Poll found that 68 percent of those
surveyed believe their House member deserves to be re-elected,
compared with 16 percent who do not believe that. It also found
that 47 percent approve of the way Congress is handling its job
and 46 percent disapprove.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, President Bill Clinton's job approval was at 65
percent, according to the poll.
</P>
<P>
Among likely voters, 47 percent said they would vote for a
Democratic candidate if the election were being held today, to 46
percent for a Republican candidate, says the poll.
</P>
<P>
The survey also found that among likely voters:
</P>
<P>
-- 54 percent say impeachment hearings should proceed as
planned;
</P>
<P>
-- 58 percent say Clinton should not be removed from office.
</P>
<P>
The survey of 1,004 adults was conducted Friday to Monday. It
has a margin of error of minus or plus 3 percentage points for the
full sample. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981015.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sit-in Staged to Urge Release of Jordanians Jailed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Hundreds of Jordanians staged a
sit-in outside the Parliament Wednesday to press for the release
of Jordanian prisoners held in Syria.
</P>
<P>
The sit-inners, most of them relatives of the prisoners, urged
the government, lawmakers and human rights organizations,
especially the Amnesty International, to work for the quick
release of the prisoners.
</P>
<P>
Emad Sharqawi, one of the sit-in organizers, said that
700-1,000 Jordanians are in jails in Syria, and most of them were
imprisoned without trials and ill-treated, the semi-official
Jordan Times said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, representatives from the demonstrators submitted a
memorandum to the Lower House of Parliament, containing the list
of the Jordanian inmates and describing the adverse conditions
they are facing in Syrian prisons.
</P>
<P>
In response, some lawmakers said that the issue has been top on
the agenda of the House and its affiliated Committee of Public
Freedom is making efforts to secure the release of the prisoners.
</P>
<P>
Sharqawi said another two sit-ins will be held near the Prime
Minister's Office and the Syrian Embassy respectively later if the
current one achieves no success.
</P>
<P>
Sharqawi said that many of Jordanians have been detained since
1970s on charges with having links with Palestinian organizations
or Jordan's major opposition the Muslim Brotherhood.
</P>
<P>
And some others were members of the National Command of the
ruling Baath Party in Syria, who were put into prisons following
the coup in 1971 which brought the incumbent Hafez Assad to power.
</P>
<P>
A report issued by the Amnesty International said that most of
the Jordanian prisoners were jailed without trials and some of them
are in poor health and suffering from diseases.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian Minister of Information Nasir Judeh Tuesday said that
the government is making efforts to secure the release of the
Jordanian prisoners in Syria. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
