<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Says Monitors See Some Compliance in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 14 (Xinhua) -- International monitoring
teams in the Yugoslav province of Kosovo Wednesday saw signs that
Serbian forces are starting to comply with U.N. demands, the State
Department said.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Rubin said two U.S. teams and
one European team went into the Kosovo countryside Wednesday to
see what was happening on the ground.
</P>
<P>
"They encountered no denial of access. They regarded the access
as excellent, the Serb police presence is much smaller in the
countryside than on Sunday, and the Serb police are generally
departing the countryside," he told a briefing.
</P>
<P>
The monitors reported that many checkpoints have gone and there
are signs of people returning to villages on the east-west highway
south of Malisevo, once an Albanian separatist stronghold, he
added.
</P>
<P>
"Some of the local Kosovars that they met with indicated that
they were pleased with the changed circumstances in which they
were going to be provided greater security through this agreement
and its verification system," he said.
</P>
<P>
But the U.S. spokesman said these were only preliminary
impressions and agreements were still needed on aerial monitoring
and on a 2,000-strong ground monitoring force.
</P>
<P>
"NATO authorities will have to make a judgment at the end of
the week whether there is substantial and serious compliance on
the part of President Milosevic," he said.
</P>
<P>
The current monitors are part of a diplomatic observer mission
and Rubin said he expected this to evolve into the 2,000-strong
mission which Milosevic negotiated with U.S. special envoy Richard
Holbrooke Monday.
</P>
<P>
The full-scale mission will be under the auspices of the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE), which
is chaired by Polish Foreign Minister Bronislaw Geremek.
</P>
<P>
"As Foreign Minister Geremek gets approval from his governing
board in Vienna to launch this, contributions need to be obtained.
A headquarters needs to be set up in Pristina. A leader and chief
of the mission needs to be selected. I would expect that to take
some time," Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
"The key to this agreement, if it's going to work, is going to
be the on-site verification system on the ground and the aerial
verification system in the air that we are trying very hard to
stand up in the coming days," said Rubin.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said he expected Serbia would sign an agreement with NATO
to implement the aerial verification system, and an agreement with
the OSCE to implement the ground verification system.
</P>
<P>
"So this combined air-ground verification system will give us
greater and greater confidence of the kind of preliminary
indications that I just gave you," the spokesman added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981015.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU to Lift Sanctions on Nigeria Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) has
assured Nigeria that it will lift virtually all sanctions on the
west African country soon, a press release from the presidency in
Abuja said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to the release, visiting Spanish Secretary of State
for European Union and External Affairs, Ramon de Miguel, made
the assurance while meeting with Nigerian leader General
Abdulsalami Abubakar Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The release did not mention any specific date when the
sanctions will be lifted, but the official News Agency of Nigeria
(NAN) quoted de Miguel as saying after the meeting that the date
would be on October 26.
</P>
<P>
NAN also quoted the minister as saying that the EU convened on
the issue in Brussels Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
De Miguel told Abubakar that the EU will lift all sanctions on
Nigeria after the forthcoming review except the arms embargo and
ban on military training, the presidency said.
</P>
<P>
However, he said military training which would enhance
Nigeria's capability to engage in humanitarian operations might
be allowed pending the lift of the arms embargo and restrictions
on military relations.
</P>
<P>
The total lift of the sanctions will be after the successful
conclusion of the transition program which is scheduled to end in
May next year, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
De Miguel commended the efforts of the Abubakar government to
entrench democracy and liberalize the political and economic
environment in Nigeria, saying that Spain and the EU would do
their best to support the on-going regeneration process in
Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Responding, General Abubakar thanked de Miguel for his visit
and assured him that the transition program was very much on
course and that his government was taking steps to address all
identified problems which might hinder its successful
implementation.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar said his government welcomed offers by friendly
nations to help in ensuring the success of its political program
and expressed the hope that more Spanish investors will seize
the opportunity of the on-going privatization exercise to come to
Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
The EU and other Western countries imposed wide sanctions on
Nigeria in 1995 after the then government of late General Sani
Abacha hanged author Ken Saro-Wiwa and eight other minority
activists on murder charges.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's relations with the West have improved greatly after
Abubakar took office in June following the sudden death of
Abacha.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar has won wide support both at home and abroad for his
aggressive measures in promoting democratization and economic
reform, including the release of all political detainees,
announcement of a new democratization program and massive
privatization of badly-run public enterprises. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
