<DOCNO> XIE19981015.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Good Prospects for Cyprus Economy: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Prospects for Cyprus' economy
are encouraging despite the turmoil in the global economy, Finance
Minister Christodoulos Christodoulou said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the annual meeting of the island's stock brokers,
Christodoulou said economic growth rate this year would reach 4.5
percent, compared with 2.5 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, unemployment rate would be around 3 percent
and inflation would fall to 2.5 percent, he said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to government's policies, Christodoulou said the
liberalization and modernization of the financial system and the
capital market was one of its top priorities.
</P>
<P>
He spoke highly of the progress of the Cyprus Stock Exchange
(CSE) and the incentives the government introduced to help boost
the island's stock market.
</P>
<P>
Cooperation between the government and stockbrokers was
"valuable," he said, it "is perhaps the best example of harmonious
cooperation between the public and private sectors."
</P>
<P>
He said the incentives have already delivered, because a number
of companies are seeking listing in the CSE.
</P>
<P>
In January, Cypriot government announced a series of incentives
to boost the stock market, including allowing offshore companies
to invest in listed companies' stocks without lossing their
special tax status, 50-percent cut of tax rate of companies which
seek listing within the coming five years, and exemption of the
cost of acquisition of new-listed shares from tax for four years
instead of two years.
</P>
<P>
The CSE was launched in March 1996 after years of operation in
an unofficial capacity under the auspices of the Cyprus Chamber of
Commerce and Industry.
</P>
<P>
Its total market capitalization reached 1.83 billion Cyprus
pounds (about 3.66 billion U.S. dollars) in June this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
