<DOCNO> XIE19981015.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Retail Sales Up 0.3 Pct in September </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. retail sales moved
up by a modest 0.3 percent in September thanks to a rebound in
auto sales, the Commerce Department reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Overall, sales rose to a seasonally adjusted 224.9 billion U.S.
dollars after flat sales in August, according to the department.
</P>
<P>
Auto sales shot up 0.9 percent in September, the best gain in
four months, following decreases of 0.1 percent in August and 4.3
percent in July.
</P>
<P>
However, excluding autos, sales inched up just 0.1 percent
higher in September, the same as the increase in the month before.
</P>
<P>
The report suggests consumers may have turned a bit cautious
following the sharp late-August drop in the stock market. Besides,
analysts believed, Hurricane Georges temporarily battered sales in
parts of the South and unseasonable warmth curbed spending on fall
merchandise.
</P>
<P>
Sales at clothing and accessory stores dropped 1.3 percent, the
worst decline in a year and a half. Spending at furniture stores
edged down by 0.2 percent, the weakest performance in five months.
</P>
<P>
Due to falling gasoline prices, sales at service stations
decreased 0.8 percent. For the third quarter, they're off 5.7
percent from a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
Drugstore sales were down 0.1 percent in September. On the
positive side, spending increased 0.7 percent at department stores
and other general merchandisers, 0.8 percent at restaurants and
bars, 0.4 percent at building-supply and hardware stores and 0.3
percent at food stores.
</P>
<P>
A boom in home sales, fueled by low mortgage rates, has
supported sales of building materials and hardware. The
third-quarter sales level was 9.7 percent higher than last year.
</P>
<P>
Overall, retail sales, which account for roughly a third of the
nation's economic output, were 4.1 percent higher in the third
quarter than a year earlier. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981015.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trade Ties With Asia Must Be Reviewed: Mozambican </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Mozambican Minister of Planning
and Finance Tomaz Salomao said here Wednesday that Mozambique
must review its trade ties with the Asian countries in serious
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Mozambican government must evaluate its relations with
those countries inflicted by serious financial turmoil, the Asian
countries in particular, so as to defuse the negative influence
of the crisis, Salomao said at a press conference in Maputo.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that with right evaluation of the trade
ties, the Mozambican government may take realistic measures to
keep away from the Asian flu.
</P>
<P>
However, Salomao noted that the efforts made by Mozambique
should be concerted with those by the Southern African
Development Community (SADC) members.
</P>
<P>
He added that "collective action" can help SADC member states
to avoid the Asian financial crisis which has influenced many
markets around the world.
</P>
<P>
The Mozambican finance minister stressed that his government
would keep up its efforts to curb the inflation.
</P>
<P>
The Mozambican government is aiming to keep the inflation
within 10 percent in 1998, said Salomao.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique's inflation rate was 17 percent in 1996 and 5.6
percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Influenced by the overwhelming financial crisis in Asia,
Mozambique is facing great pressure in curbing the inflation.
</P>
</TEXT>
