<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Link Infertility to Bacterial Infection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Some men may have low fertility
because of bacterial infections in their sperm, researchers in
Hungary said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Bela Molnar and colleagues of Albert Szent-Gysrgyi Medical
University in Szeged, Hungary, reported in the New Scientist
magazine that they have shown bacteria can prevent sperm from
swimming well enough to reach an egg.
</P>
<P>
The reproductive systems of up to two-thirds of men are
infected with anaerobic bacteria such as Fusobacterium nucleatum
and Bacteroides fragilis.
</P>
<P>
These infections usually go unnoticed unless extremely large
numbers of the bacteria are present, when they can cause pain and
discharge.
</P>
<P>
Wondering if these bacteria could be one factor in some men's
fertility problems, the researchers isolated F. nucleatum and B.
fragilis from 43 infected men and incubated sperm of normal
motility with various concentrations of the bacteria.
</P>
<P>
Sperm usually swim in a culture medium for a day or more. But
even in the samples with low concentrations of bacteria, only 1
percent of the sperm were still moving after 18 hours. At the
highest dose, they all stopped moving after three hours.
</P>
<P>
Bacteria may inhibit sperm motility by either competing for
fructose, a sugar that sperm need for energy or producing products
that are toxic to sperm, or physically interfering with the
lashing of sperm tails, explained the researchers.
</P>
<P>
The study suggested that infertile men with infections should
be given broad-spectrum antibiotics for three months to eliminate
the bacteria, before beginning In Vitro Fertilization (IVF).
</P>
<P>
"We should first treat them and let them try to conceive the
normal way," Molnar said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981015.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Duma Adopts Document on Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The Russian State Duma, the
lower house of parliament, Wednesday passed a statement on the
situation in the Balkans, which welcomes "the progress on a
peaceful resolution to the conflict in Kosovo."
</P>
<P>
According to the Interfax news agency, the document endorsed by
307 votes with six votes against said that the State Duma
unconditionally denounces any forms of aggression against the
Union Republic of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
It declared that in the event of unleashing military operations
by NATO member states against that country, considerable damage
will be caused to their relations with Russia, which will flare up
tension in Europe and the whole world.
</P>
<P>
Praising Russian diplomats for the international efforts to
settle the Kosovo problem, the Duma stressed, "NATO's decision to
implement a military action against Yugoslavia should be abolished
immediately."
</P>
<P>
The State Duma sent its delegation to Belgrade Wednesday to
coordinate the position of the conflicting sides. Yugoslavia
should also develop links with the Russia-Belarus Union, the Duma
said.
</P>
<P>
The Duma also recommended that the Russian government "correct
the program for cooperation between Russia and NATO, while taking
into account NATO's position in Yugoslavia."
</P>
<P>
It is necessary to continue to make energetic efforts for
reaching a compromise on the Kosovo problem, the lower house
believed. Such a compromise may be based on an end to violence,
implementation of U.N. Security Council resolutions, and the start
of constructive talks on the status of Kosovo with respect for the
territorial integrity of the Union Republic of Yugoslavia, it
said. 
</P>
