<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Firms of the United States and France are competing
over a gas pipeline project that would carry Syrian gas to
Lebanon, the Arabic daily An Nahar reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The report said Elf-Aquitain of France has gone a long way in
its negotiations with the Lebanese government and the Ministry of
Electricity on the project, details of which have not been
disclosed yet.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the report quoted the director of the
U.S. Trade and Development Agency Joseph Grandmaison, who has
been visiting here, as saying that his agency had approved a
500,000 U.S. dollars allocation for a feasibility study on the
project.
</P>
<P>
The paper said the party who offers to do a feasibility study
has a better chance of winning the project.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- The Lebanese cabinet has endorsed the launch of a new
550 million-U.S. dollar bond issue, local newspapers reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The move came only two days after a 100 million-dollar
Eurobonds was launched in London.
</P>
<P>
The 550-million-dollar bond issue will be the last in a plan
approved by the parliament early this year to borrow 2 billion
dollars to restructure part of the country's national debt of 14
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- A total of 76.1 percent of the Royal Jordanian (RJ)
flights started out and arrived safely as they were scheduled in
the first nine months of this year, compared with 75.5 percent in
the same period in 1997, Jordan's official news agency Petra said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the news agency reported that the RJ flights carried
911,975 passengers in the first nine months of this year,
making the occupancy rate of the RJ flights' seats reaching 65.7
percent.
</P>
<P>
The RJ flights also carried 46,219 tonnes of goods and
performed 40,879 flying hours during the same period, it added.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The Amman Financial Market (AFM), Jordan's sole stock
market, Wednesday suspended trading the shares of the Jordan
Cement Factories Company (JCFC) in preparation for privatizing the
state-owned company.
</P>
<P>
The suspension will keep valid until a formal governmental
decision about the privatization of the JCFC is made, said a
AFM statement.
</P>
<P>
The government now owns 49.3 percent of the kingdom's sole
cement producer's shares. The JCFC earned some 17 million
U.S. dollars in net profits in 1997.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- French travel agents and tour operators said here
Wednesday that the number of French tourists coming to Jordan can
reach 60,000 this year, if promotion efforts and regular flight
operation between the two countries are increased.
</P>
<P>
Jordan received a total of 30,000 French tourists in 1997,
Jordan's official news agency Petra quoted the agents and
operators as saying at a meeting held between the two sides'
tourism officials and representatives in Amman. 
</P>
