<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blood Donation May Lower Risk of Heart Attack: Magazine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Blood donors may have a lower
risk of heart attacks than those who chose not to give blood,
Finnish scientists said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The finding supports the hypothesis that people with more iron
in their bodies are at greater risk of heart attacks, Dr Jukka
Salonen, of the University of Kuopio, Finland, reported in the New
Scientist.
</P>
<P>
"We were extremely surprised to find such a strong relationship
between blood donation and protection against heart disease," Dr
Jukka Salonen told the magazine.
</P>
<P>
After studying the medical records of 2,862 men over a
nine-year period, the researcher found that of the 153 who were
blood donors, only one suffered a heart attack, while among the
non-donors the heart attack rate was 17 times higher.
</P>
<P>
Scientists believed that the reduction in heart disease may be
due to the loss of iron associated with blood donation.
</P>
<P>
An earlier study by the same group found that men with large
iron stores in the body were more than twice likely to have a
heart attack than those whose iron stores were low.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981015.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Central Bank Lowers Repo Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 14 (Xinhua) -- As a sign of an easing in
monetary policy, South African Reserve Bank Wednesday lowered its
repo rate by 0.25 percentage points to 21.60 percent, South
African television reported.
</P>
<P>
Business welcomed the small step taken by the reserve bank,
the central bank of South Africa, but said that it was too early
to be optimistic in view of the fact that the world financial
market is still highly volatile.
</P>
<P>
The repo rate, at which the central bank lends to commercial
banks, had been stuck at high levels after the financial crisis
began in late May this year.
</P>
<P>
The repo rate was below 15 percent before the crisis, said the
report. 
</P>
