<HEADLINE> Burundi Conflicting Parties Begin Face-to-Face </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Conflicting factions in
the Burundi peace talks opened their face-to-face discussions
Wednesday after more than two months of recess with a debate on
the issue of democracy and good governance.
</P>
<P>
An aide to peace talks mediator Julius Nyerere, the former
president of Tanzania, said that the talks started in a friendly
atmosphere with all parties showing concern for a peace deal.
</P>
<P>
The issue of democracy and governance is the first item on the
five-point agenda adopted late on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The other items on the agenda are endorsement of chairmen of
five committees proposed at the first round of talks in June this
year, start of the work of the committees, discussions of
procedures governing talks and debate on subject of peace and
security in Burundi.
</P>
<P>
The aide said four sides -- the National Assembly, Frolina,
Inkinzo and the former Burundian president Ntibuntanganya -- have
represented their views at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The third round of talks, which started on Tuesday, are aimed
at ending the five-year civil strife in the land-locked Burundi.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, reports reaching here said Nyerere attended a short
service in remembrance of Prince Louis Rwegasore on Monday
evening.
</P>
<P>
Nyerere praised the late prince, saying they had close contact
particularly during the independence struggles.
</P>
<P>
"If Prince Rwegasore has to rise from his tomb today, he'll be
shocked to see how tiny African republic has been divided on
ethnic lines," he told more than 40 Burundians who gathered at
the service at the Hotel 77 in Arusha.
</P>
<P>
Among the audience was the former President of Burundi,
Sylvestre Ntibantunganya, who was overthrown in 1993 by military
strongman Major Pierre Buyoya.
</P>
<P>
He urged Burundians to follow footsteps of the late prince who
had united the nation to bring prosperity and development for
all.
</P>
<P>
The remembrance service was organized by the government of
Buyoya, led by Burundi's Minister of Peace Process, Ambroise
Niyonsaba.
</P>
<P>
Nyerere said the lifting of economic embargo on Burundi by
Great Lakes states lies in the hands of Burundians themselves.
</P>
<P>
If various Burundian factions can agree on a peace deal, a
message will be delivered to leaders of the Great Lakes countries
so that they could lift the sanctions in a short time, he said.
</P>
<P>
He cautioned the warring parties not to deploy any dilatory
tactics in the peace process, otherwise the Great Lakes states
will play the same game.
</P>
<P>
East and central African nations, backed by the Organization
of African Unity, have imposed economic sanctions on Burundi
shortly after Buyoya toppled a civilian government led by
President Ntibantunganya in July of 1996.
</P>
<P>
More than 150,000 people, mostly civilians, have been killed
in Burundi since October 1993 in a series of massacres and in
armed conflict between Tutsis and Hutus.
</P>
<P>
Warring parties signed a ceasefire agreement in the first
round of talks in June and dwelt mainly on the genesis of the
Burundi conflict at the second round of talks in July. But
fightings have continued over the past months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
