<HEADLINE> European Stock Markets Sustain Rally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 14 (Xinhua) -- European stock markets, buoyed
by Wall Street's bounce back into positive territory, enjoyed an
end of session rally on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
London's FTSE 100 index staged a modest comeback despite a
morning in the doldrums, as index of top shares ended the day up
48.3 points at 5038.4, making up for Tuesday's 47.5 drop which
followed Monday's record gains. But at one point earlier it had
been down 54.4 at 4935.7.
</P>
<P>
The gains in London came even though Wall Street opened down
while in the morning dealers had bad news from the Far East to
contend with. In Japan the Nikkei was down 172.06 at 13070.73 and
in Hong Kong the Hang Seng slipped back 18.74 at 8990.09.
</P>
<P>
The outlook for interest rates remained mixed as unemployment
figures showed the claimant count at an 18 year low, while the
annual rise in average earnings fell back to 4.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, minutes from the Bank of England's Monetary Policy
Committee meeting showed hardline interest rate hawk Willem Buiter
switched his vote in September to back a cut for the first time.
</P>
<P>
The news had little effect on the markets, with analysts split
as to whether the inflationary implications of the jobless fall
outweighed the other indicators.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, the Dax index rallied strong towards the end of
trade, closing at 4371 points after a gain of 117.98. But
investors said that trade had remained subdued.
</P>
<P>
Achim Matzke at Commerzbank said the dollar's drop overnight
may have been keeping investors out of the market. The dollar
slipped to DM1.6336 from DM1.6522 late Tuesday in New York.
</P>
<P>
In Paris, the Cac 40 index closed at its session high, boosted
by Wall Street's late morning recovery, closing at 3,361, after a
gain of 82.19. Traders said it was underpinned both by the
greenback's turnaround and the boost in European markets.
</P>
<P>
"That's unusual, but it's symptomatic of the fact that European
markets have been underperforming," said one dealer. "There's hope
of stability in Europe next year; the U.S. will go into recession
before we will, which will create demand for European equities."
</P>
<P>
But he warned that CAC-40 trading volume would remain modest in
coming sessions with investors still cautious because of the
dollar's relative weakness. 
</P>
</TEXT>
