<HEADLINE> Israeli Right-Wingers Rally against Possible Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Hundreds of Israelis took to
the street Wednesday to protest against signing an agreement with
the Palestinians over the second redeployment of Israeli troops in
the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The rally, organized by the right-wingers, was held near the
residence of Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
"Prime Minister, stop the danger, don't surrender," says a
giant sign, giving the rally its theme.
</P>
<P>
Demonstrators also held posters reading: "Agreement on
withdrawal bad for Israel" and "Benjamin Netanyahu, you was wrong
on signing Hebron Accord, don't continue on singing agreements."
</P>
<P>
Hanan Porat, Knesset (parliament) member of the National
Religious Party, said in the rally that a withdrawal agreement
means Israel would hand over territory to the Palestinians in a
"silver plate."
</P>
<P>
He threatened that he will call for early elections if an
agreement is reached without the fulfillment of the Palestinian
commitments to fight terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu is due to fly to the United States Wednesday night
and take part in a three-way meeting with Palestinian National
Authority Chairman Yasser Arafat and the U.S. President Bill
Clinton to break the deadlock in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
A U.S. peace initiative calls on Israel to hand over 13 percent
more of the West Bank in the second redeployment in exchange for
Palestinian crackdown on terrorism. Israel has so far balked at
the proposal.
</P>
<P>
Israeli right-wing parties claimed this scope of would endanger
the security interests of the Jewish country, and threatened to
topple the government if Netanyahu agrees to cede that much.
</P>
