<HEADLINE> Thailand's Swine Breeders Import Expected to Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's imported swine
breeding stocks are expected to fall by 50 percent this year
because of the country's economic slump and demand squeeze, the
Thai News Agency (TNA) reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Pichai Hothongcum, senior general manager of Betagro Hybrid
International Co., one of the major importer of swine breeding
stocks, was quoted as saying the ongoing economic crunch has
reduced local pork consumption and consequently forced local
raisers to cut the capacity by 20 percent from estimated 10
million pigs raised last year.
</P>
<P>
Pichai noted that although discouraged by the falling local
consumption, most raisers remain willing to continue raising pigs,
as the prices of feed meal are now relatively cheap.
</P>
<P>
The number of local raisers also remain stable, as some jobless
workers have entered into the swine farming.
</P>
<P>
For the whole year, the number of raised pigs is estimated at
about 8 million heads worth about 30 billion baht (789 million
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Now, the price of live pigs is about 40 baht (1.05 dollar) per
kilogram, down from 42-43 baht (1.11-1.13 dollar) per kilogram
over the past two-three months. The price is expected to stand at
this level until the end of the year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
