<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Central Bank to Intervene Baht Currency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BANGKOK, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Thai Central Bank Governor
Chatumongkol Sonakul has said the bank may intervene to prevent
rapid changes in the value of the baht currency to ensure a stable
financial market.
</P>
<P>
"We don't want the baht to dramatically change in the
short-term period. The unit can go up and down but not at a fast
rate," the Thai News Agency on Thursday quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
"The BOT (Bank of Thailand) will slow the rate of change to
support the trade sector," he added.
</P>
<P>
The baht, he said, remained competitively valued against other
currencies although it had made strong gains recently.
</P>
<P>
He said the real effective exchange rate of the baht, as of
October 9, was 13.17 percent weaker than that of currencies of
some 22 other countries, excluding Japan.
</P>
<P>
The baht ended at 38.30 to the U.S. dollar on Thursday from
the level of 41 two weeks earlier.
</P>
<P>
Chatumongkol said the central bank would continue to monitor
the movement of the baht currency in order to ensure that it
remains at a competitive level.
</P>
<P>
He also said strengthening of the Japanese yen would likely
boost the country's foreign currency reserves to 28 billion
dollars by the middle of this month, up from 27.4 billion on
October 9. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
