<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Editorial Congratulates Congress of Disabled Persons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 15 (Xinhua) -- The Friday issue of People's
Daily, China's leading newspaper, carries an editorial hailing
the opening of the Third National Congress of the China Federation
of Disabled Persons.
</P>
<P>
The editorial expresses warm regards to the nation's 60 million
handicapped people and over 200 million relatives, as well as
people who work diligently to make life better for disabled people.
</P>
<P>
"The goal of the congress is to proceed under the guidance of
Deng Xiaoping Theory and the guidelines of 15th National Congress
of the Communist Part of China to provide a retrospective of the
road of development for nation's cause to assist disabled
people. The congress will also confirm the major tasks for the
next five years and development goals for the 21st century; unite
and assist handicapped people in their efforts to contribute to
the reform, opening and modernization drive; and provide
encouragement to increase the self-respect, self-confidence and
self-reliance of related individuals."
</P>
<P>
The editorial quoted the late Chinese leader Mao Zedong as
saying: "The blind suffer from one of the most debilitating
afflictions. You have joined the revolution for the cause of
liberating the oppressed and should also liberate those who suffer
most."
</P>
<P>
Over the past decade alone, China adopted the Law on Protecting
the Handicapped, three five-year plans offering related
assistance, and established a number of programs and institutions
to promote the cause.
</P>
<P>
More than four million handicapped people have been
rehabilitated over the past 10 years, with 64.3 percent of the
country's disabled school-age children receiving education,
compared with only six percent a decade ago. In additon, some 73
percent of handicapped people are employed, compared with the
previous rate of less than 50 percent, according to the editorial.
</P>
<P>
Fourteen million poverty-stricken disabled Chinese now have
adequate food and clothing thanks to poverty relief development
programs and the social security system.
</P>
<P>
The editorial urges governments at all levels and society as a
whole to offer greater support and care for the disabled. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
