<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 15:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. to Start Shuttle Talks in Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, October 15 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Resident Representative
in Cyprus, Dame Ann Hercus, will start from Friday shuttle talks
between Greek and Turkish Cypriot communities on the island in a
fresh bid to seek solution to the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
This was announced here Thursday by government spokesman
Chirstos Stylianides at his press briefing.
</P>
<P>
Stylianides said Hercus will first have a meeting with
president Glafcos Clerides on Friday, which aims at clarifying
several issues concerning shuttle talks.
</P>
<P>
"We have already said that after that we can enter a process
of proximity talks," he added.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the third stage of the process would be
direct talks, if a common ground was found.
</P>
<P>
"We are ready to participate in such a process which will aim
to solve issues such as reduction of tensions, security and
substance of the Cyprus problem," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Stylianides said the Cypriot government remained firm on the
implementation of the U.N. resolutions and the results of the
meetings with Secretary-General Kofi Annan in New York last
month.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Chief announced on September 30 that during his
separate meetings with Mr. Glafcos Clerides and Mr. Rauf Denktash
in New York, he proposed that his Deputy special Representative
for Cyprus, Ann Hercus, "develop a process for on-island contacts
with both parties, with the goal of reducing tensions and
promoting progress toward a just and lasting settlement".
</P>
<P>
Both leaders expressed their support for such a process and
have promised to cooperate with it in a constructive and
flexible manner, Annan added.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed
its troops and took over the northern third of the island in
the wake of a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus peace talks broke down last summer when Turkish
Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash walked out of a U.N.-sponsored
inter-communal talks in Switzerland to protest against an
European Union (EU) decision to start accession talks with the
Cypriot government.
</P>
<P>
Denktash put forward a proposal in August, calling for the
establishment of a confederation of two equal states in Cyprus
as the basis for resuming talks. The idea was rejected by
the Greek Cypriot-dominated government and U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
The U.N.-led international community has been trying for
decades to reunite the island through a bi-zonal, bi-communal
federation formula, but so far no tangible results have been
achieved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
