<HEADLINE> Taliban Team to Arrive in Pakistan for Talks With UN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 15 (Xinhua) -- A Taliban team will arrive
here Friday for talks with visiting envoys of the United Nations
and the Organization of the Islamic Conference (OIC) on the
present Iran-Afghan tension and the Afghan issue.
</P>
<P>
Taliban's chief representative in Islamabad Saeedur Rahman
Haqqani told Xinhua Thursday that Wakeel Ahmed, advisor to Taliban
supreme leader Mulla Mohammad Omar, will lead the three-member
delegation for talks with U.N. officials, prominently on the U.N.
difficulties in the Taliban-controlled areas.
</P>
<P>
This will be Wakeel's second visit to Pakistan in six days.
Earlier he delivered a letter to U.N. special envoy on Afghanistan
Lakhdar Brahimi from Omar inviting him to visit Afghanistan for
detailed talks in Kandahar.
</P>
<P>
Brahimi visited Kandahar Wednesday and held a meeting with Omar
which Brahimi described as "useful and constructive."
</P>
<P>
The Taliban and the U.N., in series of talks in Islamabad and
Kandahar, discussed U.N. difficulties in the Taliban-controlled
areas and the investigation into the murder of a U.N. official in
Kabul in August.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. had withdrawn its staff from Kabul a few days before
the U.S. cruise missile strikes on alleged terrorist bases in
Khost in August. One U.N. official was reported to be killed in
Kabul during an anti-U.S. demonstration following the strike.
</P>
<P>
Haqqani said that the Taliban will discuss with U.N. officials
their difficulties and ways and means to remove them so that they
could reopen its offices in Kabul. The Taliban officials will
apprise the U.N. officials of investigation into the murder of the
U.N. official.
</P>
<P>
Talking about the release of remaining Iranians held in custody
by the Taliban, Haqqani said he was informed by the U.N. officials
that they were making arrangements for an early evacuation of the
Iranians from Kandahar.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that airlifting of the Iranians would be completed by
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
During his talks with Brahimi Wednesday in Kandahar, Omar told
Brahimi and OIC Assistant Secretary General Ibrahim Saleh Baker
that all the remaining Iranian prisoners in their custody would be
released.
</P>
<P>
Haqqani said that the U.N.-OIC envoys assured the Taliban
leader that all Taliban prisoners in Iran would also be released.
According to Haqqani, Iran held 80 Taliban prisoners, which Tehran
has denied. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
