<DOCNO> XIE19981015.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Producer Prices Pick Up 0.3 Percent in September </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 15 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. producer's prices
jumped 0.3 percent in September, the largest rise in a year, the
U.S. Labor Department said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
However, the larger-than-expected seasonally adjusted increase
in the Producer Price Index (PPI) for finished goods still
followed a stretch of eight declines over 10 months.
</P>
<P>
For the first nine months of the year, producer prices declined
at an annual rate of 0.8 percent, compared with a drop of 1.2
percent for all of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Analysts believed that the September gain was influenced by a
shift in the usual pattern for discounting autos and light trucks
in September, the end of the 1998 model year. After adjustment,
car prices rose 2.2 percent, the largest increase in eight years.
Before adjustment, they fell 0.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Without seasonal adjustment, the overall index for finished
goods would have been unchanged.
</P>
<P>
In September, seasonally adjusted energy prices overall dipped
0.1 percent following August's 2.3 percent plummet. Gasoline fell
two percent and natural gas 1.1 percent. However, heating oil
jumped 6.6 percent, the most in 11 months, and electricity rose
0.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Energy has been one of the driving forces behind deflation,
with prices down 11.6 percent from a year earlier. But many
analysts believe they have about bottomed and will no longer be
contributing to deflation.
</P>
<P>
Food prices increased 0.4 percent. Though the prices of beef,
pork and fish all fell, vegetables shot up 12.4 percent and fresh
fruit, 0.8 percent. There were gains topping 30 percent for
squash, corn, grapefruit, potatoes and tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
Deflation remained at earlier stages of the production
process. Prices fell 0.2 percent for intermediate goods and 1.6
percent for crude goods. An example of the three processing stages
is clothing for finished, cloth for intermediate and cotton for
crude.
</P>
<P>
In a separate report today, the Labor Department said
first-time applications for unemployment benefits rose by 2,000 to
a seasonally adjusted 303,000 last week. That level suggests
demand for labor remains robust in the United States despite the
prospect for slower economic growth. Two weeks earlier, the number
of jobless claims hit a five-month low of 290,000.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Commerce Department said inventories of unsold
goods at the nation's businesses rose 0.3 percent in August. Sales
fell 0.2 percent after a 0.1 percent decline in July. They were
the first back-to-back drops since October and November of last
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
