<HEADLINE> Waldner Edges Samsonov in Table Tennis World Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANTOU, China, October 15 (Xinhua) -- World champion Jan-Ove
Waldner outfoxed European champion Vladimir Samsonov in a
three-set thriller at the World Cup table tennis tournament here
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The 33-year-old Swede, known for wickedly deceptive serve and
devastating follow-up attack, snatched a 14-21, 21-16, 21-19
victory over the 22-year-old Belarussian who is currently ranked
world number one.
</P>
<P>
Samsonov, who plays a simple game, but with exceptional
composure and ball control, used his trademark rallies to grab
the first set.
</P>
<P>
The setback jolted Waldner out of lethargy as he got in very
early with vicious loops and sudden, disguised changes of
direction, winning the following two sets in 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
Waldner has recorded two wins with Samsonov at 1-1.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, Samsonov overcame a tenacious challenge
from Kalinikos Kreanga of Greece in their opening group game,
while Waldner routed Australia's Oceania champion Mark Smythe in
straight sets.
</P>
<P>
Samsonov, who suffered a crushing defeat to Waldner in the
world championship final last year, had beaten the Swede twice
this year --in European Top 12 tournament in January and Croatian
Open in March --both in a score of 3-1.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Kong Linghui, former world champion and 1995 World Cup
winner, kept a clean book by humiliating France's 1993 world
champion Jean-Philippe Gatien in 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
The 23-year-old Kong, ranked second in the world, handed a
21-15,21-12 loss to the lefthanded attacker.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, Kong beat rising star Ma Lin in an
all-Chinese game.
</P>
<P>
Defending champion Zoran Primorac had a perfect sheet by
taking his second straight group victory Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
The 29-year-old Croatian, who beat Sweden's Peter Karlsson
earlier in the day, outlasted South Korean Kim Taek Soo 21-15,
12-21, 21-17.
</P>
<P>
China's Olympic champion Liu Guoliang remained unbeaten with a
21-19, 21-10 win over former world number one Jean-Michel Saive
of Belgium.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Liu crushed Germany's Jorg Rosskopf 21-17, 21-12.
</P>
</TEXT>
