<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU High-Tech Trade Deficit Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, October 15 (Xinhua) -- The European Union's (EU)
structural trade deficit in high-tech products stood at a little
under 10 billion ECU (11 billion U.S. dollars) in 1997, almost
half its 1995 level, Eurostat reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The regional bloc's imports of high-tech products in 1997 were
worth 72 billion ECU (79 billion dollars) while its exports were
worth 62 billion ECU (68 billion dollars), the Luxembourg-based
statistical bureau of the European community said.
</P>
<P>
In 1990, EU imports were worth 51 billion ECU (56.1 billion
dollars) and exports 32 billion ECU (35.2 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Britain, France and Germany combined accounted for three-fifths
of EU imports of high-tech products in 1997, and the three EU
member states accounted for three-quarters of EU's high-tech
exports.
</P>
<P>
The United States is the world's largest importer and exporter
of high-tech products. 
</P>
</TEXT>
