<DOCNO> XIE19981015.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korean Chaebols Challenge Government in Restructuring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 15 (Xinhua) -- South Korean family-owned
conglomerates, or chaebols, Thursday challenged the government to
stop its intervention in their corporate restructuring.
</P>
<P>
"We think our voluntary restructuring will be much more helpful
for enhancing the nation's international creditability than the
one attained under government pressure," said Sohn Byung-doo,
deputy executive chairman of the Federation of Korean Industries
(FKI) after a meeting of top leaders of the chaebol lobby group.
</P>
<P>
The government has upheld free market principles so the
federation hopes it would respect family conglomerates' voluntary
restructuring efforts, Sohn said.
</P>
<P>
Bosses from 16 chaebols, including FKI Chairman Kim Woo-choong,
decided at the meeting to urge the government to give up
intervention in the restructuring when they meet government
officials next week.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time that the chaebols openly challenged the
government's restructuring policy.
</P>
<P>
South Korean chaebols are blamed for devouring most banks loans
and shirking responsibility for causing the ongoing financial
crisis with their high debt build-up and over-expansion.
</P>
<P>
The subsidiaries of South Korea's top 30 chaebols were laden
with total debts of some 28 million U.S. dollars by the end of
1997, after the nation was gripped by the unprecedented financial
crisis caused by corporate bankruptcies and bad loans of financial
institutions late last year.
</P>
<P>
The chaebols, especially the top five -- Hyundai, Samsung,
Daewoo, LG and SK -- have recently been under mounting pressure
from the government and the public for dragging their feet in
merging their excessive investments and overlaps in seven key
industrial sectors, including semiconductor and power generation.
</P>
<P>
Calling an August agreement on business mergers reached among
the top five chaebols "half-baked and insufficient," the
government has threatened to cut off new loans to the companies
involved in the restructuring of semiconductor and power generator
sectors unless they complete their mergers by the end of November
this year.
</P>
<P>
In the semiconductor sector, Hyundai and LG have been
deadlocked over managerial control of their joint company.
</P>
<P>
Under the restructuring plan in power generator industry
announced by the federation on October 7, the chaebols agreed to
maintain a dual management system between Korea Heavy Industries &AMP;
Construction Corp. (Hanjung) and Hyundai, after Samsung hands over
its boiler facility business to Hanjung. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981015.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysian National Capital Fund to Issue Bonds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's Danamodal
National Bhd (National Capital Fund) Thursday announced it will
issue nominal value zero-coupon, unsecured redeemable bonds to
fund its banking institution recapitalization program.
</P>
<P>
Danamodal was set up on August 10 this year to undertake the
task of recapitalizing and restructuring the banking sector, to
restore public confidence in the safety and soundness of the
system, with its focus on private sector solutions within the
framework of government policies and actions.
</P>
<P>
Danamodal said in a statement that it will inaugurally issue 11
billion ringgit (about 2.894 billion U.S. dollars) of bonds
1998/2003 to raise about 7.7 billion ringgit (about 2.026 billion
dollars) for the purpose.
</P>
<P>
The bonds will be allotted to 57 banking institutions -- 35
commercial banks, 10 core finance companies and 12 merchant banks
-- on October 21 and will be offered a rate consistent with the
prevailing market rate, Danamodal said.
</P>
<P>
These bonds have been accorded special status as liquid asset,
Class One liquefiable asset under the new liquidity framework and
will be assigned zero risk-weight for capital requirement
purposes, it said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, these bonds are tradable in the secondary market
among corporations listed under the Companies Act 1965.
</P>
<P>
It said Bank Negara Malaysia (State Bank of Malaysia) would
provide a facility to discount the bonds as the lender of last
resort.
</P>
<P>
These zero-coupon bonds are structured to give Danamodal the
flexibility to manage its cash flow position.
</P>
<P>
The statement said Danamodal shall have the right to extend the
maturity date of the bonds upon maturity for a further period of
not less than one year or not exceeding five years.
</P>
<P>
It said that with the funding in place, Danamodal expects its
recapitalization operations to progress on schedule in accordance
with the plan set out by Bank Negara.
</P>
<P>
Danamodal said the recapitalization and the restructuring of
the banking institutions would enhance the resilience of the
financial sector and is a priority under the government's National
Economic Recovery Plan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981015.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Positive Impact Forecast for EU's Agricultural Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Housewives in the European
Union (EU) may expect to find cheaper foodstuffs once the reforms
of the Common Agricultural Policy (CAP) have been implemented.
</P>
<P>
The positive forecast, published on Thursday as a result of
independent studies on the overall impact of the reforms, said
consumer price index was expected to drop by 0.45 percent, while
household food bills to drop by 1.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
Farmers are also expected to benefit from the CAP reforms as
they were expected to see increased income, projected to be
between 22 percent and 34 percent per labor unit, compared to the
relatively high level of the 1992-1996 period.
</P>
<P>
The studies were carried out by the statistical bureau of the
European community, the University of Bonn and the University of
Amsterdam.
</P>
<P>
The studies also forecast an increase in agricultural
production and internal demand, a 0.4-percent increase in gross
domestic product (GDP) and a 0.2-percent increase in employment.
</P>
<P>
European Agriculture Commissioner Franz Fischler said the
studies gave incontrovertible proof that CAP reforms is beneficial
not only for the agricultural sector but for the economy of the
European Union.
</P>
<P>
It is, therefore, time for agriculture ministers of the EU
member states to enter into serious negotiations on the
implementation of the CAP reforms, Fischler said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981015.0116 </DOCNO>
