<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Plane Carrying British MP, Sick Iraqi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, October 15 (Xinhua) -- A special plane landed at the
Rasheed airport in Baghdad on Thursday, on board British MP
George Gallaway and Iraqi sick child Maryam Hamza who is
suffering from leukemia.
</P>
<P>
In a statement to reporters, Gallaway said that the
five-year-old Hamza is a symbol of the sufferings of Iraqi
children due to the continuation of the U.N. sanctions since 1990.
</P>
<P>
Gallaway said Hamza has been treated in a hospital in Glasgow,
Scotland, for six months.
</P>
<P>
Hamza underwent chemotherapy and radiotherapy in the hospital
and is now in a remission state, an Iraqi official told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Her treatment cost some 93,000 U.S. dollars, which was paid
through private donations.
</P>
<P>
The British MP, who has been critical of the British anti-Iraq
policy, called on all states in the world to work for lifting the
embargo which claimed lives of thousands of Iraqis.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations imposed punishing sanctions -- including a
ban on air travel and limits on sales of oil -- on Iraq following
its invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Gallaway said that Hamza sent a letter to British Prime
Minister Tony Blair on Tuesday calling upon him to work for
lifting the embargo off Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Gallaway visited Iraq last March and met a number of Iraqi
officials and got acquainted with the health situation in
Iraq. In April, he visited Iraq for the second time and returned
home taking with him Hamza for treatment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
