<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ben Johnson to Race against Horses and Car </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Canada's sprinter Ben Johnson
will set his foot on the track Thursday again, this time in
competition with two horses and a car.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time the 36-year-old sprinter runs on a track
meat for horses at a charity fund-raising event, Canada's leading
newspaper the Globe and Mail reported.
</P>
<P>
Once a dominant figure in men's 100-meter field, Johnson has
been suspended from track and field since 1993 when he was tested
positive for the second time in his career.
</P>
<P>
Thursday's sideshow presentation may be the start of Johnson's
new career -- as a curiosity, media magnet and pitchman, the
paper said.
</P>
<P>
His presence is expected to draw at least 5,000 people to the
oceanside track in Charlottetown, Prince of Edward Island. Money
from the tickets will go to a local children's wish foundation.
</P>
<P>
The man-beast-machine race is believed the first in Canada,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
Each contestant will race a different distance. Johnson will
be set 80 meters from the finish line. The two horses will start
from 100 meters and 120 meters from the finish, while the car 140
meters.
</P>
<P>
The race will begin with the crack of a starter's pistol. But
a start official will also wave a flag for the car driver, who
might not hear the report of the pistol over the noise of his
engine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
