<HEADLINE> Taiwan Investors Hold Hope for Wang-Koo Meeting (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Taiwan investors are placing
great hope in the landmark mainland visit of Koo Chen-fu, chairman
of the Taiwan-based Straits Exchange Foundation (SEF) and his
delegation.
</P>
<P>
The delegation arrived in Shanghai on Wednesday and Taiwan
business people have expressed great hope that Koo's
meetings with Wang Daohan, president of the Association for
Relations Across the Taiwan Straits (ARATS), will lead to the early
realization of direct mail, trade and shipping across the Taiwan
Straits.
</P>
<P>
"We sincerely hope that the visit will help promote
communications and mutual understanding between the parties on
both sides of the Taiwan Straits," said D.C. Yang, chairman of the
Shanghai Association of Taiwan-Funded Enterprises. Yang made the
remarks during a banquet welcoming the Taiwan delegation.
</P>
<P>
The over 3,200 Taiwan-funded enterprises in Shanghai, China'
major financial and commercial center, were established with a
total investment of 3.6 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
"Direct mail, trade and shipping across the Taiwan Straits
should be realized at the earliest possible date," said Yang
Liangfu, chairman of the board of the Taiwan-funded Fule Food
Company.
</P>
<P>
Yang, who is also an association council member, held that the
resumption of contacts and high-level talk between ARATS and SEF
offer great hope for the resolution of many issues.
</P>
<P>
Between 2-3 million people currently travel between the two
sides of the Straits on an annual basis. Nonetheless, the two
sides have not as yet ended lingering hostilities and various
obstacles originated by Taiwan authorities. The requirement for
people to travel through Hong Kong and Macao adds both costs and
time to the journey.
</P>
</TEXT>
