<HEADLINE> Ukraine Hails Political Solution to Kosovo Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Ukraine welcomes the efforts to
seek a political solution to the crisis in Kosovo and supports
U.S. special envoy Richard Holbrooke's mediation in the troubled
southern Serbian province, an official statement said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
While noting that the Ukrainian government is happy with the
latest development in Kosovo, the foreign ministry statement said
Ukraine is ready to send representatives to join the planned
international observation mission heading for Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
NATO on Tuesday night authorized air strikes on Yugoslavia at
any time but gave the Yugoslav government four days' grace to
comply with all United Nations demands, including allowing
international aid agencies to access freely to Kosovo and
thousands of refugees to go back home.
</P>
<P>
Following the NATO decision, Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic, in an agreement reached with Holbrooke, provided
guarantee on the withdrawal of Serbian security forces from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The Ukrainian government said in the statement that it
understood why NATO made such an air strike decision against
Yugoslavia. And it also hoped that the Yugoslav leadership would
take new steps to implement the U.N. Security Council resolution
1199, so as to avert a possible NATO military intervention.
</P>
<P>
To safeguard Yugoslavia's territorial integrity and provide
Kosovo an extensive autonomy should be the basis for a peaceful
end to the crisis there, the statement added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
