<HEADLINE> India to Launch New National Database on Agriculture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 15 (Xinhua) -- India has planned to launch a
nationwide knowledge system that would provide farmers with the
latest information on agriculture to help attain sustainable food
security, the Press Trust of India (PTI) reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The new system, to be launched in January next year, will
concentrate on information empowerment of the socially- and
economically-unprivileged sections of the country, the PTI quoted
agriculture scientist M. S. Swaminathan as saying.
</P>
<P>
The information would reach farmers via a network of computers,
public telephones and wireless services, said Swaminathan,
chairman of the M. S. Swaminathan Research Foundation based in
Chennai, formerly Madras, capital of the southeast state of Tamil
Nadu.
</P>
<P>
The ex-director general of the Indian Council of Agricultural
Research told the 49th Congress of International Federation of
Information and Documentation which is underway in New Delhi that
such a system, developed by his foundation, would help the nation
attain sustainable food security.
</P>
<P>
It will provide information on safe drinking water,
environmental hygiene and productivity increase through
eco-friendly technologies and improved distribution system, he
said. 
</P>
