<HEADLINE> Food Safety Campaign Underway in EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, October 15 (Xinhua) -- A special campaign began on
Thursday in all European Union countries to inform food producers,
processors, retailers and consumers about their respective
responsibilities and rights concerning food safety.
</P>
<P>
The campaign, launched by the European Commission and expected
to extend into next year, was expected to drive home the message
that food safety is a shared responsibility.
</P>
<P>
The campaign was launched in response to a specific demand from
consumers for more information on the subject. A survey carried
out in late 1997 found 68 percent of consumers were concerned
about food safety.
</P>
<P>
Officials on the European Commission, the executive body of the
15-nation European Union, said that it is difficult to accept that
a single link in the food chain is to blame for food poisoning
incidents.
</P>
<P>
A single link is as dangerous as all other links put together,
they added.
</P>
<P>
The approach of the ongoing campaign will be to highlight the
importance of following the instructions given on the labels on
food packages and abiding by the basic rules of hygiene.
</P>
<P>
The campaign intends to target not only consumers in general
but also specific population groups such as school pupils and
students, servicemen and women and enterprise employees.
</P>
<P>
European Consumer Policy Commissioner Emma Bonino said:
"Consumers are concerned about food safety, they are uncertain.
</P>
<P>
"But I want everyone to be aware that food safety does not
depend on just one link in the food chain but demands constant
effort on the part of all involved, from the producer to the
consumer." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
