<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Says Not to Act Under International Pressure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 15 (Xinhua) -- India asserted Thursday that
there was no question of New Delhi acting under international
pressure in dealing with outstanding bilateral issues with
Pakistan and again ruled out any third party involvement in
resolving them.
</P>
<P>
On the eve of crucial Indo-Pakistan foreign secretary-level
talks beginning Friday in Islamabad, a spokesman from the External
Affairs Ministry said Thursday that the international community
has strongly expressed its desire that India and Pakistan resolve
all outstanding issues peacefully and bilaterally.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here said that Washington was pressurizing
both India and Pakistan to agree to a nuclear restraint regime.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman reiterated that India has always desired
peaceful, friendly and cooperative relations with Pakistan and for
this purpose has urged Islamabad to engage in a broad-based and
comprehensive dialogue which would move the relationship forward
over a broad front.
</P>
<P>
The dialogue would provide for a discussion on all pending
issues including Jammu and Kashmir, he said, adding that all
Indian proposals for the composite dialogue process have included
discussions on Jammu and Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
After suspension of 13 months, India and Pakistan are set to
resume the talks Friday in Islamabad amid mutual suspicion and
with little hope for any breakthrough especially on Kashmir, the
most contentious issue between the two neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Relations between the two countries have been tense after the
nuclear tests first by India and then by Pakistan in May this
year, which Pakistan said have further internationalized the
Kashmir dispute India has insisted as a bilateral issue.
</P>
<P>
The strained relations further deteriorated following reports
days ago that India is going to stage a large-scale military
exercise near the Pakistan border which evoked strong reaction
from Islamabad accusing New Delhi of vitiating the atmosphere on
the eve of the foreign secretary-level talks.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of the Pakistani Foreign Ministry said Tuesday that
Islamabad was extremely disturbed by the reports (of Indian
military exercises), particularly by the reported nature, size and
timing of the exercises.
</P>
<P>
However, Indian Defense Minister George Fernandes said the
exercises pose no concern to any nation as such maneuvers are
routine with all countries.
</P>
<P>
Indian External Affairs Ministry said earlier that New Delhi
was looking forward to the resumption of the talks with an "open
mind", while Pakistani Foreign Minister Sartaj Aziz said frankly
that no major breakthrough was expected from these meetings.
</P>
<P>
Judging by the attitude of both sides on eve of the talks,
there is remote possibility of any major progress as the issue of
Kashmir, which had led to the breakdown of the talks 13 months
ago, continues to be the dividing point as was evident from the
strong statements issued from both New Delhi and Islamabad
recently.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan declared Tuesday that it would speak on behalf of the
Kashmir people while India dubbed the statement as "utterly
absurd" and stressed that Kashmir remains an integral part of
India.
</P>
<P>
Jammu and Kashmir is one of the two issues scheduled to be
taken up for discussions during the Islamabad round of the talks
between the two countries while the other identified issues will
be discussed during talks in New Delhi from November 5 to 13.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981015.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
