<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Down in Uneventful Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 15 (Xinhua) -- The Australian sharemarket
ended an uneventful day slightly lower Thursday, with traders
waiting for solid direction before hedging their bets in the
current volatile climate.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark all ordinaries index slipped 6.3 points to
2,459.3, just off the day's lows.
</P>
<P>
The market opened looking fairly strong but when the Japanese
market turned around it again followed.
</P>
<P>
On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei closed at 12,995.37
points, down 75.36 points, or 0.58 percent from Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Our market really traded nowhere and volumes are dead, no
one's getting enthusiastic about doing anything at the moment,"
Lucinda Chan from Macquarie Equities said.
</P>
<P>
"Everybody thinks there is more downturn than upturn in the
market, people are waiting for the recovery to happen before they
jump into the market," he added.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was a very light 310.37 million shares
traded, worth 875.22 million Australian dollars (555.76 million
U.S. dollars) with 415 rises, 501 falls and 364 steady trades.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index closed 10.0 points lower to 4,271.2
while the all resources index dropped 3.5 points to 1,007.6.
</P>
<P>
There were no great surprises in individual stocks. The banks
and insurance sectors tended to hold up reasonably well.
</P>
<P>
The banking index closed up 7.6 points to 5,179.5, while the
insurance sector added 8.5 to 6,430.4 points.
</P>
<P>
Market leader, the National Australia Bank rose 14.5 cents,
Commonwealth jumped five cents, Westpac climbed 6.7 cents and ANZ
closed 1.5 cents lower.
</P>
<P>
Topping the day's turnover was telecommunications giant Telstra
on a volume of 10.71 million shares. The installment receipts
ended five cents lower.
</P>
<P>
Rupert Murdoch's News Corp fell seven cents while the preferred
shares slipped 10.5 cents. Publishing and Broadcasting's share
price, which has recently taken a battering, turned around to add
13.4 cents.
</P>
<P>
In resource stocks, BHP climbed 10.7 cents, as BHP announced
its Ekati diamond mine at Yellowknife in the North West
Territories of Canada was in production.
</P>
<P>
The gold index ended 33.7 points lower at 1,118.3. The gold
bullion price in Sydney closed at 296.50 U.S. dollars an ounce,
compared to Wednesday's close of 296.45. 
</P>
</TEXT>
