<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Cruises Through 63 U.S. Cents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 15 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar shot to
levels not seen in three months Thursday, closing firmly above 63
U.S. cents, and looks set to rally further.
</P>
<P>
Solid hedge fund buying lifted the currency to a high of 63.65
U.S. cents before it closed at 63.61, more than half a U.S. cent
above Wednesday's finish of 62.88.
</P>
<P>
Since Friday last week, the local dollar has gained two U.S.
cents.
</P>
<P>
Craig James, chief economist with Colonial State Bank, said the
Australian dollar could be likened to "the great Houdini."
</P>
<P>
"Over the last seven trading days, the Australian dollar has
gained nine percent against the U.S. dollar," he said.
</P>
<P>
"It is driven by substantial demand from American accounts,"
Peter McGrath, chief foreign exchange dealer at Westpac Banking
Corp., said.
</P>
<P>
"It looks quite strong actually, very strong and there doesn't
look to be any fundamentals behind the move other than just supply
and demand.
</P>
<P>
"So it looks set to continue at this stage and couldn't rule
out a test of 64 (U.S. cents), and perhaps a little bit above
there in coming days," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, McGrath said the U.S. dollar would likely need to go
down below 115 Japanese yen and stay there for the Australian to
sustain the pace above 64 U.S. cents in the medium term.
</P>
<P>
"But that could happen and we may see the Aussie squeeze higher
over the coming months," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar closed at 75.26 Japanese yen from 75.20
and 1.0392 German marks from 1.0293. 
</P>
</TEXT>
