<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Govt Forms Team to Probe Soeharto's Wealth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's Attorney General's
Office has set up a team to look into former president Soeharto's
alleged hidden wealth in all parts of the country, an official
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"We have ordered the public prosecutor's offices in all
provinces to cooperate with relevant agencies in tracing former
president Soeharto's wealth in all parts of Indonesia," deputy
head of the Attorney General's Office Ismu Djoko said in Jambi,
capital of Jambi province in southern part of Sumatra island.
</P>
<P>
If there are reports that Soeharto has plants, houses or land
in the provinces, the Attorney General's Office will send its team
to trace the property, Djoko was quoted by Antara News Agency as
saying.
</P>
<P>
According to a report from the National Land Agency, Soeharto
has land in 10 of the country's 27 provinces.
</P>
<P>
"It is possible that he also has properties, including land, in
other provinces. Relevant agencies, especially the National Land
Agency, can cooperate with the public prosecutor's offices in
tracing the properties," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian government has set up two teams to investigate
Soeharto's alleged corruption and his wealth.
</P>
<P>
Home and foreign reports have accused Soeharto of amassing
wealth illegally during his 32-year reign and stashing the fortune
overseas.
</P>
<P>
But Soeharto, who stepped down amid mounting public pressure on
May 21, swore that he did not have any deposits abroad in a
statement broadcast by his daughter's television station early
September.
</P>
<P>
Asked if the Attorney General's Office is slow in tracing
Soeharto's wealth, Djoko said the team set up by the office is
working hard to collect as much evidence as possible.
</P>
<P>
The team needs members who are very serious in tracing
Soeharto's wealth, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
