<DOCNO> XIE19981015.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran not to Reschedule Foreign Debts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Iran announced on Thursday that
it would not reschedule its foreign debts despite of a serious
financial problem caused by the fall in oil price.
</P>
<P>
"Iran is not intent on rescheduling of its foreign debts,"
Mohammad Mojarad, deputy governor of the Central Bank of Iran
(CBI), told the official news agency IRNA.
</P>
<P>
Mojarad said that all the Iranian banks have been instructed
to fulfill their undertakings on time and in case of any delay,
the due fine should be paid to their foreign bank partners.
</P>
<P>
He put Iran's foreign debts at 12.3 billion U.S. dollars,
equivalent to one year's oil revenues at the price of 12 dollars
per barrel.
</P>
<P>
Mojarad, who is in charge of the CBI foreign exchange affairs,
said that Iran's arrears amounted to 4 billion dollars, which
should be paid by the end of the next Iranian year (March 20,
2000).
</P>
<P>
Iran was forced to reschedule its foreign debts in 1993
because of excessive imports in 1992 and a sharp fall in its oil
revenue caused by oil price slump.
</P>
<P>
Foreign diplomats here doubt if Iran would pay off its foreign
debts this year since oil price slump once again dealt a serious
blow to the government revenue this year.
</P>
<P>
Mojarad said that Iran's oil revenues in the first half of the
current Iranian year (started on March 21) amounted to 5 billion
dollars, some 3 billion dollars less than the figure anticipated
in the budget for the period.
</P>
<P>
He put the total hard currency expenditures in the first half
of the year at 9.4 billion dollars, which was met through
borrowing over 1.3 billion dollars from foreign exchange
reserves, 5 billion dollars from oil revenues and 3.1 billion
dollars through other means, including advance oil sales and
receiving credit facilities.
</P>
<P>
The CBI official said that Iran would receive foreign credits
of 3 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that the foreign credits to be received
in the second half of the year would compensate for the deficit in
oil revenues, so that the government would not be forced to make
major adjustments, especially in the production sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
