<HEADLINE> Singapore to Assist Indonesia with Food, Medicines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, October 15 (Xinhua ) -- Singapore is gearing up to
deliver 4,000 metric tons of rice and a supply of medicines to the
Riau province of Indonesia in implementation of its humanitarian
aid to Indonesia, according to a government press release.
</P>
<P>
These rice and medicines will be delivered in two ships in
October and December 1998 respectively.
</P>
<P>
On behalf of the Singapore government, Edward Lee, Singapore
ambassador to Indonesia, will officially present the aid to the
Governor of Riau Bapak Soeripto at a handover ceremony due to be
held on October 16 in Batam, an Indonesian island close to
Singapore.
</P>
<P>
The forthcoming delivery is the second phase of the 12 million
Singapore dollars (about 7.5 million U.S. dollars) worth of rice
and medicines the Singapore Government would extend to Indonesia
on humanitarian base.
</P>
<P>
On August 1998, Singapore Minister for Education and Second
Minister for Defense Teo Chee Hean traveled to Indonesia and
handed over the first phase of humanitarian assistance comprising
10,000 metric tons of rice and a supply of medicines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
