<DOCNO> XIE19981015.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Facing Pricing Pressure, Trade Restrictions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Increasing competition from
other supplier countries and regions whose currencies have
devalued in the course of the Asian financial crisis will continue
to pose pressure on prices of Hong Kong's exports in the coming
year, according to a report.
</P>
<P>
The report, released by the Hong Kong Trade Development Council
(TDC) Thursday, said Hong Kong companies should be vigilant on the
undercurrent of regionalism and restrictive trade measures
triggered by the crisis.
</P>
<P>
The report, based on a TDC study on Hong Kong's external trade,
found that merchandise exports, including offshore trade, managed
by Hong Kong traders and manufacturers, were able to hold on
despite the devaluation of other Asian currencies.
</P>
<P>
The report said a strong U.S. dollar, falling prices of raw
materials and components as well as intensified competition have
led to a continued decline in export prices.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's external performance so far this year has been
significantly affected by the Asian economic turmoil, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
"Given this most serious challenge currently faced by the world
economy in 50 years, the adjustment in Hong Kong's export
performance is not surprising," said TDC's chief economist Edward
Leung.
</P>
<P>
However, Leung still maintained a positive view on the longer
term outlook of Hong Kong's external economy, pointing to the
steady economic growth in the U.S. and in the European Union, two
of Hong Kong's major export markets.
</P>
<P>
Both the U.S. and the EU economies will continue to expand at a
moderate pace, providing Hong Kong exports with the much-needed
vitality, the report said.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, sales to the Chinese mainland, Hong Kong's
largest market, are expected to be stable given the steady
expansion of the mainland's economy, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
