<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Samsonov Struggles in Table Tennis World Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANTOU, China, October 15 (Xinhua) -- World top-ranked
Vladimir Samsonov overcame a tenacious challenge from Kalinikos
Kreanga in their opening group game at the World Cup table tennis
tournament here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The 22-year-old Belarussian, European champion and Top 12
winner, came from one set down to beat the 10th-ranked Greek
17-21, 21-19, 21-15 in Group A.
</P>
<P>
There were some brilliant forehand drive exchanges as Kreanga
nosed ahead 17-14.
</P>
<P>
Kreanga built on this cushion and pulled further clear until
he forced Samsonov into a wayward backhand to go one up.
</P>
<P>
Samsonov displayed excellent poise and balance in the second
set, employing consistent topsin strokes from both wings which
were to much for his rival.
</P>
<P>
The lanky Belarussian led all the way to nail the third set.
</P>
<P>
In the other Group A game, reigning world champion Jan-Ove
Waldner routed Oceania champion Mark Smythe of Australia 21-8,
21-10.
</P>
<P>
In an all-Chinese clash, world number two Kong Linghui shook
off mid-game setbacks to beat 11th-ranked Ma Lin 21-12, 16-21,
21-14 in Group B.
</P>
<P>
South Korean Kim Taek Soo and defending champion Zoran
Primorac of Croatia were winners in Group C.
</P>
<P>
Kim, hailed as the best penhold topspin player in the world,
nipped Argentina's Liu Song 22-20, 21-14, while the 29-year-old
Primorac downed Swede Peter Karlsson 21-16, 21-16.
</P>
<P>
In Group D, Chinese Olympic champion Liu Guoliang used his
superior fire power to carve out a 21-17, 21-12 victory over
Germany's Jorg Rosskopf.
</P>
<P>
Rosskopf wilted under the barrages and showed justifiable
signs of nerve.
</P>
<P>
Also in Group D, former world number one Jean-Michel Saive of
Belgium beat Canadian Johnny Huang 22-20, 21-18. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
