apparently warding off the impact of the Asian crisis, with new
figures showing an improvement in long-term unemployment and
painting an optimistic outlook for manufacturing industries and
business.
</P>
<P>
The authorized Australian Bureau of Statistics (ABS) said
Thursday the number of Australians out of work for more than a
year fell sharply in September, by 2.6 percent to 251,900, wiping
out a sharp rise in August.
</P>
<P>
However, the long-term unemployed still made up a third of all
Australia's jobless.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a survey by the Australian Industry Group, newly
formed from the merger of Australia's two peak industry bodies,
forecast a major improvement in the manufacturing sector in the
coming months.
</P>
<P>
The survey of more than 1,000 companies found 37 percent of
manufacturers had lifted their output, while 32 percent cut
production in the September quarter.
</P>
<P>
It found 40 percent of manufacturers reported a rise in sales,
marginally offsetting the 36 percent whose sales fell.
</P>
<P>
Despite continued job losses in the sector, manufacturers were
optimistic about the future.
</P>
<P>
The survey found the manufacturing sector forecast a profit in
the current December quarter for the first time in more than 12
months, resulting from a sharp rise in production, sales and
exports and a further improvement in investment in plant and
equipment.
</P>
<P>
However, the survey expressed caution over the impact of the
Asian crisis. "Given that expectations tend to overstate actual
outcomes, care should be taken when interpreting these results,
particularly given that the full impact of the Asian crisis is yet
to be felt," the survey warned.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the National Australia Bank quarterly business survey
found business conditions improved slightly in the September
quarter, although conditions contracted for the second consecutive
quarter.
</P>
<P>
But the survey highlighted a degree of variability across
industries.
</P>
<P>
Mining, manufacturing and wholesaling continued to experience
poor conditions while the business and property services sector
recorded the strongest results.
</P>
<P>
The only sector to report a significant deterioration in
business conditions was transport, storage and communications.
</P>
<P>
Firms anticipated business conditions would improve further in
the December quarter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
