<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Promotes Export to Uganda: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 15 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's official
export to Uganda have doubled over the past four years, rising
from 24.4 million U.S. Dollars in 1994 to 48.8 million, local
daily the Star reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Exports to Uganda mainly consist of industrial goods and raw
materials, construction and transport machinery, newsprint and
sugar.
</P>
<P>
Senior Ugandan Trade Ministry official Richard Kamajugo was
quoted as saying that the sharp rise in South African exports to
Uganda was the result of cooperation between the two countries
after the 1994 general election, and subsequent signing of trade
and double taxation agreements.
</P>
<P>
Before 1994 there was no recorded trade between Uganda and
South Africa and the little trade that did not exist had to go
through a third country because there was no cooperation between
the two governments.
</P>
<P>
According to Kamajugo, Uganda had remain a deficit exporter to
South Africa, with only 185,900 U.S. Dollars worth of goods
exported in 1996, and 2.4 million in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Local trade experts predicted that South African exports to
Uganda will rise further owing to promotional campaigns by South
African industrialists and the shorter period of goods delivery
from South Africa compared with Asia and Europe.
</P>
<P>
Freight costs from South Africa expected to fall drastically
once the country's railway network linking southern, eastern and
central Africa gets operational.
</P>
<P>
A South African trade delegation headed by Trade and Industry
Minister Alec Erwin visited Uganda in July in a bid to promote
its export to the eastern African country.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that an ever increasing number of South
African firms is establishing branches in Uganda with an eye on
the country's 20 million population strong market, as well as
those in the Democratic Republic of the Congo, Rwanda and
Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
According to Uganda Investment Authority figures, South Africa
has become a leading source of investments to Uganda, upstaging
traditional sources such as Kenya, India, and Canada. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
