<HEADLINE> S. Africa Welcomes Lesotho Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 15 (Xinhua) -- South Africa Thursday
welcomed the agreement between the Lesotho government and
opposition parties on the establishment of a transitional
structure to prepare for new elections.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Alfred Nzo said in a statement that he was
satisfied with the accord.
</P>
<P>
Nzo paid tribute to the responsible manner in which all the
parties had committed themselves to placing the interests of the
people of Lesotho above their own.
</P>
<P>
"The spirit of compromise by the Lesotho government and
opposition alliance needs to be commended and encouraged. This
now opens the way for the vital process of reconstruction to
start."
</P>
<P>
Nzo welcomed United Nations Secretary General Kofi Annan's
statement on Wednesday, in which he committed U.N. assistance to
Lesotho's process of transition. Nzo also asked the international
community to help with Lesotho's reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
The agreement of the transitional body was secured after 11
hours of talks on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In terms of the timetable agreed to, Lesotho's Independent
Electoral Commission would be restructured by the end of the year
and a new code of conduct for political parties would be reviewed
by the transitional body and the commission as from March 31,
1999. Lesotho's electoral system would be reviewed by October 31,
1999.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's agreement was a second major breakthrough in
resolving Lesotho's political dispute over the May 23 general
election.
</P>
<P>
The government and its opposition rivals agreed on October 2
to hold fresh elections in 15 to 18 months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
