<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 30 Lesotho Mutinous Soldiers Arrested </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Thirty of Lesotho's rebel
soldiers who participated in a mutiny in September were arrested
early Thursday morning, South African Press Association (SAPA)
reported.
</P>
<P>
Lesotho Defense Force (LDF) chief Makhule Mosakeng said in
Maseru that the group was selected from more than 1,500 soldiers
who returned to army headquarters after Southern African
Development Community (SADC) commanders requested the arrests.
</P>
<P>
SAPA quoted military sources as saying that the group tried to
resist arrest, saying SADC troops had no power to arrest them.
But they later agreed to be taken to Lesotho's maximum security
prison near Maseru.
</P>
<P>
Lesotho opposition parties immediately called on South African
High Commissioner Japhet Ndhlovu to question the arrests and
demanded the immediate release of the soldiers.
</P>
<P>
"Their arrest violates the spirit of agreements reached at
yesterday's (Wednesday) talks which are aimed at normalizing
things in Lesotho," said opposition alliance spokesman Vincent
Malebu.
</P>
<P>
"We want those people to be freed immediately. We can't want
to normalize things and at the same time arrest others..."
</P>
<P>
Malebu called on the signatories of Wednesday's agreement to
ensure that intervening forces were not in Lesotho to arrest
people, but to maintain law and order, peace and stability.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's agreement provided for the establishment of a
transitional structure to prepare the nation for new general
elections in 15 to 18 months.
</P>
<P>
Junior Lesotho soldiers launched a mutiny in early September,
accusing Mosakeng and 28 other senior army officers of being
puppets of the ruling Lesotho Congress for Democracy. Mosakeng
and the senior officers were forced to resign at gun point.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Pakalitha Mosisili's government called for SADC
intervention and on September 22, SADC troops arrived in Lesotho
to deal with what SADC officials described as a coup in the
making.
</P>
<P>
Skirmishes broke out between SADC troops and Lesotho soldiers
and more than 70 people died, including 18 LDF soldiers and eight
South African soldiers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
