<DOCNO> XIE19981015.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Current Account Surplus Reaches $8 Billion in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Japan's current account surplus
in August reached 1,157.6 billion yen (about 8.0 billion
U.S. dollars), or up 43.6 percent from the same period last year,
marking the 17th straight monthly increase, the Japanese Finance
Ministry said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Exports came to 3,842.9 billion yen (about 26.6 billion
dollars), up 0.7 percent largely due to brisk demand for aircraft
and automobile engines, and steel products, the ministry said in a
preliminary report.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, imports dropped by 5.5 percent to 2,752.2 billion
yen (about 19.0 billion dollars) because of the declining domestic
demand.
</P>
<P>
Although imports from the United States rose by 9.3 percent,
those from Japan's Asian neighbors and the 15-member European
Union slipped by 3.0 percent and 2.4 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
Fewer Japanese were traveling abroad due to the weak yen,
causing the services deficit to shrink by 50.2 billion yen (about
347 million dollars) to 544.0 billion yen (about 3.8 billion
dollars), the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The current account measures the flow of goods and services, as
well as investment income and other monetary transfers.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese yen averaged 144.67 to the U.S. dollar in August,
compared with 117.90 yen a year earlier. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
