<DOCNO> XIE19981015.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibetans Learning How To Protect Rights Via The Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, October 15 (Xinhua) -- The word 'lawyer' was largely met
with indifference by most Tibetans 20 years ago, but law firms
have become a fairly common part of their lives today.
</P>
<P>
Yangzomg, a Tibetan woman who lives near Lhasa, the capital of
Tibet Autonomous Region, turned to lawyers for help when she
discovered that her ex-husband had concealed his possessions when
they got divorced.
</P>
<P>
When she got the house back and got child-support payments, she
explained her actions by saying, "Quarreling with him was futile
and I knew that only the law and lawyers could help me defend my
rights."
</P>
<P>
A construction company in Rinbung County also benefited from
the law when it won a lawsuit involving more than 700,000 yuan in
unpaid debts. Tsering Qoipei, the manager of the company, said
they used to rely on administrative mediators, but that their
problem remained unsolved until they turned to the law. "The court
is more efficient and impartial than administrative offices," he
explains.
</P>
<P>
Tibet currently has 11 law offices with 48 professional
lawyers, 40 percent of whom are Tibetans. Since law firms opened
for business here in 1985, they have handled about 3,800 cases and
worked as advisers for more than 300 corporations and government
organizations.
</P>
<P>
Yangjim, head of the Hengfeng Law Office, which was the first
to open in Tibet, said that the law business is one of the most
significant changes in Tibet in the past two decades.
</P>
<P>
Dojie, a judicial official, said that, with social and economic
development, the demand for legal services has been on the rise,
and lawyers, instead of merely defending people in criminal cases,
have played an important role in economic and civil and
administrative affairs.
</P>
<P>
The law business is booming in Tibet these days, and 48 lawyers
is hardly enough to cope with the increasing number of lawsuits,
he noted.
</P>
<P>
With the support of the central government, the Autonomous
Regional Judicial Department has drafted a development plan for
the business to increase the number of the lawyers here to 100 by
the end of the century.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981015.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korea's Hyundai Company Develops High-Speed Flash Memory </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 15 (Xinhua) -- South Korean Hyundai Electronics
has developed a high-speed 8-mega flash memory which is the
fastest in this sector of the same degree.
</P>
<P>
The newly developed flash memory chip has the processing speed
of 45 nanoseconds, which means that in one second, 22 million
Korean characters can be transmitted, said a spokesman of the
company Thursday.
</P>
<P>
It has circuit width of 0.35 micrometer and the user voltage is
five volts.
</P>
<P>
Flash memory, which can retain memory even after the power is
turned off unlike S-RAM or D-RAM, is used mainly in mobile PC,
network system and set top box.
</P>
<P>
Hyundai Electronics is expected to put one million units of the
new chip into market next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
