<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lesotho Govt, Opposition Agree on Transitional </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Lesotho government and
opposition parties have reached an agreement on setting up a
transitional structure to oversee the upcoming elections, local
media reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The deal was struck after 11 hours of talks between the ruling
Lesotho Congress for Democracy (LCD) and the opposition alliance
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
South African Safety and Security Minister Sydney Mufamadi,
who chaired the multi-party talks in Maseru, said the composition
of the structure would be decided at a later stage following
moves to legislate the formation of the body in the Lesotho
parliament this month.
</P>
<P>
In terms of the timetable agreed to, Lesotho's electoral
system would be reviewed by October 31, 1999. Its Independent
Electoral Commission would be restructured by December 31 this
year and a new code of conduct for political parties would be
reviewed by the transitional structure and the electoral
commission by March 31, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Mufamadi said the transitional structure would seek to create
and promote a climate in Lesotho that would be conducive to free
and fair elections.
</P>
<P>
The transitional body was proposed by the Southern African
Development Community (SADC) during the second round of
multi-party talks last week as the LCD and its opposition rivals
failed to agree on who should govern the country in the run-up to
fresh elections.
</P>
<P>
The opposition insisted on a government of national unity,
which the LCD firmly rejected.
</P>
<P>
Under the SADC proposal, the transitional structure would be
powerful as it would have access to information held by the
government that was relevant to the elections. It would also take
decisions on all electoral matters including the role of the
police, the military, the intelligence, finance, foreign affairs,
and media.
</P>
<P>
However, it is not clear whether all the terms were agreed to
by both sides. Mufamadi only said a task team would be set up to
define the finer workings of the body.
</P>
<P>
The LCD earlier Wednesday rejected the idea of the
transitional body, arguing that it would be unconstitutional
since its functions coincided with those of the government.
</P>
<P>
The multi-party talks came after political turmoil paralyzed
the mountain kingdom, resulting in military intervention by the
SADC last month.
</P>
<P>
Opposition parties refused to accept the results of the May 23
general election, claiming that it was rigged in favor of the
LCD, which won 79 of 80 seats in the National Assembly.
</P>
<P>
In the first round of talks on October 2, the government and
the opposition agreed to hold fresh elections in 15 to 18 months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981015.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda's GDP Too Dependent on Foreign Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Some 60 percent of Uganda's
Gross Domestic Product (GDP) is dependent on foreign aid inflows,
a situation that irks parliament members here.
</P>
<P>
Gabrel Opio, chairman of the parliamentary sessional committee
on finance and economic planning, told parliament in a recent
session of the committee that while the economy has continued to
register an overall positive trend, there is need to address
over-dependence on foreign aid, the New Vision paper reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The report said external aid inflows account for 60 percent of
the GDP while exports make only 30 percent. About 60 percent of
the exports is dependent on export of coffee which is faced with
fluctuation of prices on the world market.
</P>
<P>
The committee recommended that the government divest "healthy"
companies directly to the public through the stock exchange.
</P>
<P>
It also suggested that the government and core investors in
privatized healthy enterprises should float shares on the stock
exchange.
</P>
<P>
The MPs blamed the recent crisis in the local banking industry
on the laxity of top managers of the Bank of Uganda and asked the
central bank to step up its supervision role.
</P>
<P>
Absolom Ongom, a member of the committee, said the government
should persuade the majority share-holders in British-American
Tobacco to give up their preemptive rights and to cede 10
percent of their 70 percent shares to Ugandans as stipulated in
the law.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, some other MPs said measures should be instituted
to ensure the quality of Ugandan coffee and that the Finance
Ministry should desist from allocating itself a lion's share of
the budget at the detriment of other government departments.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
