<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hainan Sees Speedy Industrial Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, October 15 (Xinhua) -- China's southernmost province of
Hainan recorded nearly 3.74 billion yuan in industrial added value
in the first three quarters of this year, a 7.6-percent rise from
the same 1997 period.
</P>
<P>
Provincial government officials attribute the rapid growth to
the great local effort made in recent years to restructure the
industrial framework for building the province into a new national
industrial giant.
</P>
<P>
Big changes have taken place in Hainan's industrial sector
since 1988, when the province was established and industry lagged
far behind agriculture.
</P>
<P>
The output value of the local industrial sector caught up with
that of agriculture in 1993, and topped 10 billion yuan in
1994. And local industrial added value has grown at an annual rate
of 11.3 percent in the past five years.
</P>
<P>
A group of new industries producing automobiles, motorcycles,
chemicals, textiles, pharmaceuticals and beverages are mushrooming
in the province.
</P>
<P>
Hainan has built a plant to produce 60,000 tons of polyester
chips, a mill capable of printing and dying 15 million meters of
silk, and a factory producing 1.4 million woollen blankets, all on
an annual basis.
</P>
<P>
In the past five years, the output value of the local
automotive industry has soared 27 percent annually, while the
cement sector has risen 15.6 percent and canned foods 10.3 percent
annually.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981015.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 08:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon's Budget Deficit Up in September </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon's budget deficit
increased from 39 percent in August to 46 percent in September,
the Arabic daily Al Anwar reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Finance said in a statement Wednesday that
expenditure in September amounted to 443.12 million U.S. dollars,
while revenues were 240 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Fouad Sinyoura, Minister of State for Financial Affairs,
explained that there were expenses which the government had to
bear last month such as the end-of-service benefits for retired
public employees.
</P>
<P>
He said that debt servicing and payments for contractors and
hospitals were also among the reasons for the growth in
government expenditure.
</P>
<P>
The government has pledged to reduce the budget deficit to 42
percent by the end of this year after over-spending by 59 percent
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
But the huge debt of 16 billion dollars has been a heavy burden
for government's efforts to achieve its goal.
</P>
<P>
The government has issued 1.45 billion dollars in eurobonds
this year as part of its plan to restructure the national debt
which is predominated by the high-interest-rate local currency.
</P>
<P>
Another 550 billion dollars in eurobonds has been approved by
the Cabinet and is expected to be issued in the next few months.
</P>
<P>
Sinyoura stressed that despite the rise in expenditures in
September, the government managed to reduce the deficit from 51
percent in the first nine months of 1997 to 39 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
The total revenues in the first nine months this year stood at
2.24 billion dollars and expenditures were 3.67 billion dollars,
of which 1.52 billion dollars went to debt servicing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
