<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Officials On Single European Currency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Thai officials Thursday called
on the European Central Bank (ECB) to delicately balance the
priority of price stability to avoid contributing to the global
economic turmoil.
</P>
<P>
The call was made at a seminar on "Implications of the Single
European Currency on International Trade and Banking".
</P>
<P>
With the European single currency ready for introduction on
January 1 next year, there have been concerns that if the ECB sets
interest rates too high with an aim to curb inflation, it will
risk deepening the global recession and lead to further bank
failures.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, if the rates are set too low, the ECB will
risk breaching the goal of maintaining price stability.
</P>
<P>
Thai Deputy Prime Minister Supachai Panitchpakdi said at the
seminar that the dilemma the ECB is facing at this moment is the
formulation of a monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
He said financial shocks that started in 1997 represent higher
risks to the European economies and the world as a whole.
</P>
<P>
The United States recently responded to such risks by cutting
interest rates.
</P>
<P>
Supachai said that with Japan being mired in an economic
recession, the EU is the only remaining pillar that still has
breathing room to support the global economic and financial
systems. If the development taking shape outside the "economic
fortress" is ignored, knock-on effects of any global economic
slowdown may later prove to be significant.
</P>
<P>
Supachai said that as the arrival of the European single
currency draws near, Thai banks need to solve their problems
before getting ready to face a drastic change in the international
financial system.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that Thai banks have already studied the euro, but
the next step is that the banks must explain to their customers
any upcoming effects of the changes," he noted.
</P>
<P>
More trading among EU member countries would not severely
effect Thailand's exports, he added.
</P>
<P>
A common currency, he said, will facilitate the broadening of
European financial markets, given that bond and equity markets
will become comparable and competitive to the U.S. market.
</P>
<P>
Peter Bekx, the European Commission's head of the unit for
monetary affairs, noted at the seminar that the ECB would try to
introduce the economic and financial stability both for the
European countries as well as the world.
</P>
<P>
"However, we have to realize that the main objective for the
introduction of a single currency in Europe is to facilitate the
economy among member countries in Europe," he said.
</P>
<P>
Michel Caillouet, head of the Delegation of the European
Commission to Thailand, said that given the economic importance of
the euro zone, the euro is likely to become an international
currency in the global trade system.
</P>
<P>
The global banking industry would face a drastic change after
the euro is put into place. Not only will it have to forego a
permanent loss of fee income and earnings from foreign exchange
dealings, but it will also face a huge one-time transaction cost
for the change-over.
</P>
<P>
According to Supachai, the negative effects from the euro
arrival would not be substantial as trading between European
countries and Thailand accounts for only 15 percent of Thailand's
total trading. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981015.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Official: Li Peng Pays Great Attention to Environmental Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUILIN, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Li Peng, chairman of the
Standing Committee of the National People's Congress (NPC), has
paid great attention to the Asian-Pacific environment and
development in the region, said a top Chinese environment official
here today.
</P>
<P>
Qu Geping, president of the Sixth General Assembly of the
Asia-Pacific Parliamentarians Conference on Environment and
Development (APPCED) which opened here today, spoke highly of Li
Peng's effort in helping formulate and implement Chinese policies
on environmental protection during the past decade and more.
</P>
<P>
Li, elected to his present position early this year, was the
premier of China from 1988 to 1998, and before that vice-premier
and acting premier partly in charge of environment issues.
</P>
<P>
Li has been awarded the United Nations Environment Award for
his contributions to environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
In 1992 he participated in the U.N. Summit on Environment and
Development in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil, and signed the "Framework
Convention on Climate Change" and the "Convention of Biological
Diversity" on behalf of the Chinese government.
</P>
<P>
The assembly will meet through October 18. 
</P>
</TEXT>
