<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Gold Mine Commissioned in Ghana </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Ghanaian President Jerry John
Rawlings has commissioned a new gold mine at Damang, the ninth to
be opened in the Western Region since 1986, the Ghana News Agency
(GNA) reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
An investment of 135 million U.S. Dollars has been injected
into the Damang Gold Mine, which is 90 percent owned by the
Perth-based Ranger Minerals and 10 percent by the Ghanaian
government over the last 10 years.
</P>
<P>
Exploration activities started in 1989 and were initially
focused on the feasibility of retreating the tailings from the
old Abosso underground mine which was closed in 1956.
</P>
<P>
With adequate funding by public listing in 1993, drilling
continued until 1996.
</P>
<P>
Studies for a surface mining operation were carried out in
1996 and it showed that about 280,000 ounces of gold could be
produced annually which was economically viable.
</P>
<P>
Actual mining started in November 1997 and production at the
end of September, 1998 was 200,000 ounces. It is projected the
mine would produce about 300,000 ounces for 1998/99.
</P>
<P>
Rawlings expressed the hope during the commissioning ceremony
Wednesday that "great harmony and cooperation would be enforced
among the work force and management of the mine and the
communities."
</P>
<P>
"We on our part would like to assure investors, both local and
foreign, that we would persist our efforts to provide a stable
environment for their operation," he added.
</P>
<P>
The president said while mining could cause damage to the
environment, proper management could significantly reduce the
degradation.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Ghanaian government has decided that no new
mines would be licensed without the approval of the Environmental
Protection Agency.
</P>
<P>
Prospective mining companies would be required to produce the
appropriate Environmental Impact Assessment and Environmental
Management Plan.
</P>
<P>
Mines and Energy Minister Ohene Kena said as of December 1997,
over three billion Dollars of private investment capital had been
put into the mining sector.
</P>
<P>
He said the government's focus now is to ensure that these
investments attain the maximum possible beneficial impact on the
country's economy as a whole and to sustain them "in an orderly
manner."
</P>
<P>
The government is committed to the development of all other
mineral potentials and has in line with this policy sponsored
airborne geophysical survey in some unexplored areas of the
country, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
It is the government's hope that the result of the survey
would spark investors' interest in minerals other than the
traditional ones.
</P>
<P>
Ghana is the second largest gold-producing country in Africa
after South Africa. It is also rich in other minerals such as
diamond, bauxite and manganese ore. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981015.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-Zambia Trade Increases Drastically </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Trade between China and Zambia
has been growing steadily in recently years with 1997 witnessing
a 140 percent increase in bilateral trade, from 15.47 million
U.S. Dollars in 1996 to 37.19 million Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The annual trade had hovered around 10 million Dollars in the
early 1990s and increased steadily since.
</P>
<P>
Professor He Xiankai, Economic and Commercial Counselor of
the Chinese embassy in Zambia, told Xinhua that China attaches
great importance to African market and African resources in its
bid to open more markets and to secure more resources worldwide.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, 23 teams of Chinese entrepreneurs came to Zambia for
feasibility studies on business and investment. And the number
of teams increased to 33 in 1997 and this year 44 teams have
flocked to the country.
</P>
<P>
Referring to unfavorable conditions for the bilateral trade,
He said Zambia is an inland country and far from China, therefore
the cost for Chinese goods is higher than those from Zambia's
neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
Countries in southern and eastern Africa offer each other
favored trade conditions because they have formed regional trade
blocs.
</P>
<P>
Since China does not enjoy these favored conditions, Chinese
goods is less competitive than those of Zambia's neighbors.
</P>
<P>
However, Zambia's opening and privatization policies offers a
lot of opportunities and it needs funds and technologies.
</P>
<P>
He urged Chinese companies to promote trade by injecting more
investments into Zambia, producing and processing products and
assembling machines before selling them locally or for export.
</P>
<P>
Chinese companies running factories and mines in Zambia can
import production equipment from China free of import duty, thus
enhancing trade with Zambia.
</P>
<P>
Zambia has abundant agricultural resources such as land and
water and its climate is suitable for a variety of crops. To
encourage agricultural production the government imposes no tax.
Some Chinese farms perform very well in the country.
</P>
<P>
Chinese firms can undertake projects such as building or
rehabilitating schools, clinics and paving roads. The projects
undertaken by the Chinese firms will exceed 20 million Dollars
this year alone.
</P>
<P>
There is great room for Chinese firms to give a full play, He
concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
