<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, October 15 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Lawyers from the White House and the Judiciary
Committee of the U.S. House of Representatives will meet next week
for the first time to discuss the impeachment inquiry regarding
President Bill Clinton's conduct.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile Committee Chairman Henry Hyde is reportedly
considering trimming back the allegations. Paul McNulty, a
spokesman for the committee, said Wednesday the panel's lawyers
would invite White House counsel Charles F.C. Ruff to provide
"exculpatory information." The session next Tuesday will cover how
the House and the White House could "work together to expedite the
process." (US-Clinton-Inquiry)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
HAVANA -- The United States isolation in pursuing its policy to
Cuba has grown as 157 members of the U.N. General Assembly voted
for a resolution calling for Washington to repeal its embargo,
Cuba said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In a telephone interview with Xinhua, Foreign Ministry
spokesman Alejandro Gonzalez noted that only two countries, the
United States and Israel, voted in favor of the sanctions imposed
by the United States in 1959 and 12 others abstained. The
U.S. policy violates human rights and the basic rule of respecting
other independent states, he said. (Cuba-U.S. Blockade)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BUDAPEST -- The Hungarian National Assembly Wednesday approved
the government's proposal to allow the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization's (NATO) aircraft to fly over its territory in the
event of military action against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The proposal was passed by most parliament members from six
parties during a special meeting. (Hungary-NATO-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- In a major decision, India agreed to abide by the
Paris convention for the protection of industrial property and the
patent cooperation treaty, a financial daily reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Financial Express said both treaties, considered as main
records regarding international protection of intellectual
property, would be binding on India as of December 7. The decision
was welcomed by patent lawyers, India's trading partners and the
United Nations alike Tuesday. (India-Patent Treaties) 
</P>
