<HEADLINE> Lebanon Forms Fire Fighting Ministerial Committee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, October 15 (Xinhua) -- After hundreds of forest fires
broke out across Lebanon this week, the government decided to form
a ministerial committee to handle the situation.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Star newspaper reported Thursday that the cabinet
made the decision on Wednesday and appointed Deputy Prime Minister
and Interior Minister Michel Al-Murr to head the committee which
comprises ministers of defense, agriculture and environment.
</P>
<P>
The committee will report fires to the cabinet and study
fire-fighting mechanism, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The government's decision came when the country's northern,
central and southern mountainous and coastal areas have been hit
by blazes.
</P>
<P>
Civil defense figures have shown that 68 fires broke out on
Sunday, 87 on Monday and 125 on Tuesday, leaving at least 11 civil
defense personnel wounded and 1.75 million square meters of
orchards and forest damaged.
</P>
<P>
The meteorological department said the dry and windy weather
was the main reason behind the fires.
</P>
<P>
But politicians and farmers blamed the quickly spreading fires
on the government's negligence and severe shortage of fire
fighting equipment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
