<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Forestry Project to Be Launched in Eastern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NINGBO, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Ningbo, a port city in east
China's Zhejiang Province, will spend 180 million yuan (about 22
million U.S. dollars) on 260,000 hectares of forests over the next
four years.
</P>
<P>
The city's forests already cover a 380,000-hectare area. The
planned forestry project includes a six-hectare forest nursery,
which will provide trees for forest centers, reservoirs, and tree
belts along highways and rivers.
</P>
<P>
Three million trees will be planted on the city's farmland,
providing each 20-hectare farm with a protective tree belt.
</P>
<P>
Most of the trees will be evergreens or broad-leaved trees and
a strict distinction will be made, with different types of trees
in different forest zones.
</P>
<P>
The project is expected to improve the city's environment and
benefit soil and water resources and the marine environment, a
city government official says.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981015.0241 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ghana Receives $18m Loan From China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Ghana will receive a loan of
18 million U.S. Dollars from China to further promote economic
and technical cooperation between the two countries, the Ghana
News Agency (GNA) reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement signed in Accra Wednesday by Victor
Selormey, a Deputy Minister of Finance and Yang Zhengchi, chief
representative of Eximbank, the loan will be used to finance
joint venture projects and would be administered by Eximbank of
China.
</P>
<P>
Ghana, according to the pact, will have 15 years to pay back
the loan, which attracts an interest of three point five per cent
per annum, including three years grace period.
</P>
<P>
Two supplementary loan accords of six million Dollars for gold
mining and 8.7 million Dollars for cocoa processing were also
sealed.
</P>
<P>
Selormey described the loan as concessional because the
Chinese government has subsidized the "generally high interest"
of such Eximbank loans.
</P>
<P>
He said bilateral relations with the Chinese date back to the
pre-independence era and that "these relations have been cordial
since then."
</P>
<P>
Eximbank, which was established in 1994, will continue to
offer support to Ghana in its efforts to achieve economic
prosperity, Yang said.
</P>
<P>
Ghana has received about 30 million Dollars interest-free
loans from the Chinese government since 1972.
</P>
<P>
Some of the projects that have benefited from the loans
include the National Theater, Juapong Cotton and Textile Factory
and Afife Irrigation Project. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
