<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ghana to Hold Int'l Tourism Fair in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Ghana is to hold the second
Ghana International Tourism Fair from September 24 to October 3,
1999, the Ghana News Agency (GNA) reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
This was announced Wednesday by Ghanaian Minister of Tourism
Mike Gizo in the capital Accra.
</P>
<P>
The fair which seeks to bring together players and
facilitators in the industry will run on the theme "Vision 2020,
Ghana the tourism gateway to Africa".
</P>
<P>
It is aimed primarily at portraying and promoting Ghana's
culture as the major tourist attraction to the foreigner in the
context of Vision 2020, the national development strategy.
</P>
<P>
"We must endeavor to give it a truly international character
which transcends the borders of the sub-region and the African
region at large," said Gizo.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, mobilization of resources necessary
to carry out specific tasks on schedule and marketing of events
must all be professionally handled by competent and dynamic
organizations and fully monitored.
</P>
<P>
He also announced that Ghana will also host the 1999 Africa
Travel Association Congress to be held in Accra from May 3 to 8.
</P>
<P>
"The principal challenge to us now is how fully prepared we
are to cope with the influx in terms of infrastructure and
tourist demand for services and thereby demonstrate also our
ability to handle an anticipated larger turnout for Emancipation
Day."
</P>
<P>
He called on local investors to invest in the tourist industry
since it is the most viable place for making money.
</P>
<P>
Ghana is ranked among the top 20 tourism destinations in
Africa. The first Ghana International Tourism Fair organized by
the Ghana Tourist Board was held in Accra in 1986. 
</P>
</TEXT>
