<HEADLINE> China's Largest Emerald Auction (1) by Yu Zheng </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 15 (Xinhua) - China's Guardian Auctioneers
said today that they hope there will be a strong response to the
rare emeralds and other gems that will be in their October 28 sale
at Beijing's Kunlun Hotel.
</P>
<P>
A 157-carat rectangular emerald pendant is the star in the
jewellery sale. It is mounted in platinum and 18k gold, surrounded
by 35 diamonds which weigh 7.3 carats in total. It is expected to
bring as much as 2 million yuan (241,000 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
A translucent ink-blue sapphire, weighing 10.46 carats, is
projected to bring from 900,000 to 1 million yuan. Also on sale is
a jadeite pendant, flanked by a ruby and small diamonds, with a
bottom price of 600,000 yuan, and artworks, ancient china, coins,
and stamps.
</P>
<P>
Gao Yuan, the oil painting and sculpture specialist at
Guardian, which is China's leading auction house, is hoping for
bids of more than 1.5 million yuan for an oil painting by the
Taiwanese Liao Chi-chun entitled Landscape, which is expected to
be one of the major paintings.
</P>
</TEXT>
