<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Joins Two Patent Treaties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 15 (Xinhua) -- In a major decision, India
agreed to abide by the Paris convention for the protection of
industrial property and the patent cooperation treaty, a financial
daily reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Financial Express said both treaties, considered as main
records regarding international protection of intellectual
property, would be binding on India as of December 7.
</P>
<P>
The Paris convention lays down the basic principles governing
protection of patents, trademarks and industrial designs while the
patent cooperation treaty makes it possible to fill out a single
application for a patent that will be valid in several countries,
reducing costs and paperwork.
</P>
<P>
The decision was welcomed by patent lawyers, India's trading
partners and the United Nations alike Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
India has claimed biopiracy in a case involving a patent
granted to a company in the United States for rice similar to
India's famous Basmati grain.
</P>
<P>
A controversy broke out recently between India and Britain over
patent of a nearly extinct Indian cattle breed called "Vechur
cow".
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Roslin Institute of Scotland, which
produced the world's first cloned sheep "dolly", has applied for
the patent rights to the genetic material of this rare cow, which
India said draws its name from Vechur, a village in its
southwestern state of Kerala. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981015.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
