<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Shenzhen Bao'an, Legendary, Successful Issue (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Believe it or not. Local
researchers have found that China's first stock had no legal
basis. But nobody would say it was illegal, because there was
absolutely no law governing this field at the time the stock was
issued.
</P>
<P>
It was 1982, just two years after Shenzhen was severed from
Bao'an County in south China's Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
The money-tight county government of Bao'an, which borders a
capitalist Hong Kong, was pondering the idea of learning something
about fund-raising from its rich neighbor.
</P>
<P>
Hu Yaobang, then general secretary of the Communist Party of
China (CPC), agreed with the county leaders.
</P>
<P>
"I propose to raise the point among the people," Hu said,
"that on the one hand, the government lacks funds for development,
and on the other hand, the people have the money to invest. Why
not bring the two together?"
</P>
<P>
In November 1982, the country government established an
investment firm, the Bao'an County Joint Investment Company, with
capital of 200,000 yuan.
</P>
<P>
In July 1983, the county government allowed the company to sell
shares nationwide. On July 8, the company followed Hong Kong's
model of joint-stock firms and set up a shareholders congress
and board of directors.
</P>
<P>
The new-born publicly held company had its certificates of
shareholding rights printed at a local printing house in
Guangzhou, the provincial capital, by using samples from Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
On July 25, the company published an ad in a local newspaper
inviting investors, though the stock issue had received no
approval from the central government, and the government itself
had little knowledge about stocks, something deemed by many as the
very essence of capitalism.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981015.0253 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jingye Cradle of Top Swimmers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 15 (Xinhua) -- You may call it the national
team, but half of its members come from one place -- Shanghai
Jingye High School.
</P>
<P>
The 24-member Chinese swimming team, who are competing in the
International Schoolsports Federation (ISF) World Gymnasiade
here, have 12 swimmers from the Jingye, who made a big splash
after winning four out of eight gold medals in the first day's
competitions.
</P>
<P>
This is the fifth time that Jingye has been commissioned by
the State Education Ministry to organize a national High Shcool
Students Swimming Delegation to take part in the ISF World
Gymnasiade.
</P>
<P>
Since 1990, Jingye has been the training base for the Chinese
student swimmers preparing for the ISF World Gymnysiade and the
World High School Students Swimming contest. The delegations
have won a total of 20 gold medals, 12 silvers and eight bronzes.
</P>
<P>
Jingye has a history of 250 years while its student swimming
team was founded more than 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The school gets its name from the old Chinese idiom "Jing Ye
Le Qun", which means respecting work and enjoying company. The
idiom has served as the school's motto.
</P>
<P>
Although this oldest high school in Shanghai has been famous
for its academic accomplishments since its establishment in 1784,
the school has always attached an importance to physical exercise
and sports. The school has become distinguished with swimming
since the early 1960s.
</P>
<P>
"The school set up its swimming team then and never stopped
training," said Qian Guoguang, head coach of the Jingye swimming
team. "We are pround that swimming becomes a traditional sport of
our school."
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai Education Bureau named Jingye as an experimental
school for nuturing a high-level student swimming team in 1986.
Since then, Jingye has increased its efforts to develop the sport
and improve the team's records.
</P>
<P>
The team selects student athletes from all districts and
counties of the city, most of whom have started training since
childhood.
</P>
<P>
The team has a special coaching group which involves
professional coaches from the Shanghai Sports Education College
and the Shanghai's swimming team. The school asked all teachers
help student athletes make up missed classes.
</P>
<P>
"All of our young athletes are fond of swimming and they hold
a clear goal when they enter the school: to improve their
swimming skills while completing the high school education," Qian
said.
</P>
<P>
"The school throws all its weight behind the team wherever
possible. In this way, our swimming team grows up with satisfying
performances."
</P>
<P>
In five National Juniors Swimming Contests held from 1996 to
1998, team members have won a total of 43 gold medals, 17 silvers
and 11 bronzes. Over 20 students have been chosen for the
national and Shanghai swimming teams.
</P>
<P>
"As well as focusing on young champions, our school is also
dedicated to promoting the sport of swimming," Qian said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981015.0254 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Shenzhen Bao'an, Legendary, Successful Issue (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Soon, this first stock issued on the Chinese mainland since
1949 attracted investors from over 20 inland provinces and
municipalities as well as from Hong Kong and Macao.
</P>
<P>
The first issue raised more than 13 million yuan, including two
million yuan in shares held by the State, 1.6 million yuan shares
bought by companies, and 9.4 million yuan shares purchased by
individual investors.
</P>
<P>
On June 25, 1991 Shenzhen Bao'an caused a stir when it was
listed on the Shenzhen Stock Exchange with the code number
No.009. The stock pocketed 225 million yuan from the sale, and it
became the largest listed company in the country, then accounting
for 43 percent of the total volume of shares on the exchange.
</P>
<P>
In the following years, Shenzhen Bao'an continued to draw great
attention from Chinese investors.
</P>
<P>
The company is the country's first issuer of convertible bonds and
medium- and long-term certificates of share-purchasing rights.
</P>
<P>
In 1993, the Bao'an Group stunned the country by buying 19.8
percent of the Yanzhong company's shares on the Shanghai Stock
Exchange, which was the country's first successful take-over of a
publicly held firm through the purchase of stock.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the group has a controlling interest in three local
joint-stock firms, while holding shares in 30 listed companies. It
is also the second largest stockholder in six other listed
companies.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, the legendary company boasted total
assets of 5.64 billion yuan, compared with 200,000 yuan 15 years
ago. It has also paid 336 million yuan in pre-tax profits to the
government.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981015.0255 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand's Mortgage Rates at 28-Year Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Banks in New Zealand have
dropped floating mortgage rates to their lowest in 28 years,
providing thousands of home owners with a timely cash bonus before
Christmas, a local newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Dominion said all the main lenders slashed their floating
rates by one percent to 6.95 percent Wednesday, the first time
variable rates have fallen below seven percent since December
1970, according to Reserve Bank (central bank) records.
</P>
<P>
The floating mortgage rate cuts, which take effect for present
borrowers next month, will reduce repayments on a 100,000 NZ
dollar (54,000 U.S. dollar), 20-year mortgage by 61 NZ dollars (33
U.S. dollars) a month.
</P>
<P>
"The sharp decline in mortgage rates this year is part of the
Reserve Bank's medicine for the ailing economy. The bank has eased
monetary conditions in an attempt to stimulate economic growth,"
the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Just half a year ago, local floating mortgage rates reached
11.25 percent.
</P>
<P>
But though lower mortgage bills are a tonic for borrowers,
savers have less to cheer about. Local deposit rates have also
dropped by about four percent in the past three months, almost
halving the interest investors earn. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
