<HEADLINE> Undersea Volcano Project Ends in New Zealand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, October 15 (Xinhua) -- A joint New Zealand and
German scientific research project studying underwater volcanoes
north of New Zealand wound up in Wellington Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Evening Post, a Wellington-based newspaper, said that the
German research vessel Sonne berthed in Wellington Thursday after
a five-week, 2.5 million NZ dollar (1.35 million U.S. dollar)
expedition which used a submersible to video and collect samples
from the seabed.
</P>
<P>
Joint chief scientist Dr. Ian Wright was quoted as saying that
it was hoped the project would aid understanding of the make-up
and operation of undersea volcanoes.
</P>
<P>
Scientists explored a series of undersea volcanoes and carried
out rock sampling along the South Pacific "Ring of Fire" between
Tonga and New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
The submersible completed three dives to depths of 190 meters
and took the first gas and water samples of volcanic seafloor
vents. It was discovered that vent sites coincided with active
seafloor fault lines, the paper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
