<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Tamil Rebels Halt Court Proceedings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Threats by the Liberation
Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) have resulted in the indefinite
suspension of the five courts of law in Jaffna city, according to
reports reaching here from Sri Lanka's north.
</P>
<P>
Members of the judiciary, lawyers and officials attached to the
courts Tuesday unanimously decided to keep away from official
duties as their lives were under threat, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
As a result, work at the Jaffna, Mallakam, Point Pedro,
Chavakachcheri and Kayts courts have come to a complete
standstill.
</P>
<P>
Warning letters signed by "Thoovayan" describing himself as the
"Organizer of the Tamil Eelam Administrative Services" have been
received by members of the judiciary instructing them to cease
official duties from that day, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile all members of the 17 local bodies in the Jaffna
Peninsula in the north of Sri Lanka have also been threatened with
death by the LTTE calling on them to resign.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE has followed up earlier death threats by killing two
mayors of Jaffna, Sarojini Yogeswarana and Ponniah Sivapalan, and
the chairman of the Karaveddi Area Council, Kangasabapathy
Rajathurai.
</P>
<P>
The members of 17 local bodies were elected as representatives
democratically by the people of the peninsula in the polls held on
January 29 this year. But the LTTE rejected the elections.
</P>
<P>
The Jaffna Peninsula had been the stronghold of the LTTE rebels
before it was lost to the government forces in May 1996. The LTTE
rebels have been fighting the government since 1983 for a separate
state in the north and east of the island country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
