<HEADLINE> Malaysia Expects One Percent Economic Growth in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia has projected an
economic growth of 1.0 percent next year against the forecast 4.8
percent negative growth for this year.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that our economy will grow by 1.0 percent (next
year) although for this year we will have a negative growth of 4.8
percent. This means we will have a turnaround of 5.8 percent,"
Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The government would adopt a deficit budget for 1999, Mahathir,
who is the first finance minister, told reporters after he
explained the nation's financial situation and the strategy for
the 1999 budget at the Parliament Pre-Council meeting here.
</P>
<P>
"It is certain that the 1999 budget will be influenced by the
unhealthy economic situation and we will have a deficit budget for
next year," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said the government was planning to improve the
financial position of the country and intensify the economic
recovery measures through monetary and fiscal measures.
</P>
<P>
"The budgetary measures are designed to stimulate the economy.
So some tax measures will be introduced but mainly it is in the
fiscal policies that are going to contribute towards stimulating
economic growth," he said.
</P>
<P>
The 1999 budget is expected to be presented by Mahathir in
Parliament on October 23. 
</P>
</TEXT>
