<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most Chinese Teenagers Disapprove of Extramarital Sex </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 15 (Xinhua) -- A recent survey reveals that
though Chinese adults have become more tolerant of extramarital
sex, most teenagers are still against such behavior.
</P>
<P>
About 8,000 people including quite a number of students have
expressed their attitudes towards marriage and sexual relations
generally through an Internet survey conducted by the Horizon
polling company.
</P>
<P>
Adopting concubines and calling on prostitutes are considered
the worst sexual activities by people surveyed, but they seem to
be more tolerant of extramarital affairs, cohabitation and sex
before marriage.
</P>
<P>
A smaller proportion of people below the age of 20 are tolerant
of these activities than their elders, according to the survey,
and some even believe that infidelity should be against the law.
</P>
<P>
The survey shows that three-fifths of the teenagers agreed that
people who destroy others people's marriages by having an affair
should be punished either financially or by other means, while 70
percent of people aged between 37 and 45 do not think there should
be any punishment for such activities.
</P>
<P>
About two-thirds of the teenagers surveyed believe there can be
pure friendship between men and women, a much larger proportion
than that of people in other age groups, but very few teenagers
said they would accept "Platonic love," or love between men and
women without any sexual contact, according to the survey.
</P>
<P>
Experts say these results demonstrate that most teenagers are
still following traditional concepts of marriage and sex, and this
may ease the minds of those who think that Chinese youngsters are
being influenced by some negative aspects of modern society.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981015.0265 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka Launches Project to Fight "Hidden Drought" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 15 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi Ministry of
Agriculture has taken up a 3-year project to address the problem
of "hidden drought" faced by 2.8 million hectares of rain-fed
rice-growing fields in post-monsoon season every year.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed by Agricultural Secretary A.M.M. Shawkat Ali
Wednesday, The Independent newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The project, which will cost 1.15 billion taka (24.5 million
U.S. dollars), involves extending input support to farmers for
supplementary irrigation to overcome the problem.
</P>
<P>
The Bangladesh Meteorological Department has been asked to
develop further its agro-meteorological forecasts with a view to
guiding farmers about what they should do when they face the
"hidden drought".
</P>
<P>
The Space Research and Remote Sensing Organization has been
asked to conduct a research on the effects of El Nino and La Nina
weather phenomena on agriculture, and the research work in this
regard is expected to start soon.
</P>
<P>
About 30 percent of rain-fed rice yields is affected by the
"hidden drought" every year on average, and this kind of rice
accounts for about half of the annual rice output, according to
the agricultural secretary.
</P>
<P>
The 2.8 million hectares of rain-fed rice fields that face the
"hidden drought" are located in the northwestern and southwestern
parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the 2.18 billion taka (46.4 million dollars)
supplementary irrigation project taken up for the current year is
being scaled down because there has so far been no water stress
because of the lingering floods.
</P>
<P>
The project has been taken on the basis of the 1987 experience
of a severe post-monsoon drought that was considered as an effect
of El Nino, periodic warming of the Pacific waters that affect the
global weather. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
