<HEADLINE> Asian Games Facilities Get Pre-game Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Thailand kicked off three days
of sports events Thursday to test the facilities of the 13th
Asian Games scheduled for December 6-20.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from some 10 Thai sports associations will
compete in the pre-games in three major sports complexes in
Bangkok, Pattaya and Nakhon Sawan Province.
</P>
<P>
The games aim to test the sports facilities, none of which are
yet complete, in addition to the telecommunications, security and
traffic control provisions.
</P>
<P>
Competitors will take part in athletics, swimming, boxing,
gymnastics, tennis, shooting, cycling, canoeing, rowing,
widsurfing and soccer.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Sports Authority of Thailand (SAT) has begun
drug tests on national athletes.
</P>
<P>
"The team will test 50 athletes from 10 sports that are known
to lure athletes to use dope," Dr Chaturaporn Na Nakorn, head of
the Sports Science Center of Thailand, said.
</P>
<P>
The testing is intented as a preventive measure to keep some
800 Thai athletes away from doping, said Chaturaporn. It will
also serve as a test run for procedures to be used during the
games.
</P>
<P>
The SAT specifically requested that 1994 Olympic boxing gold
medallist Somluck Khamsing be tested, Chaturaporn said.
</P>
<P>
No suspicions have been raised about Somluck. But ensuring
that he is drug-free now would avoid any possible embarrassment
at the games.
</P>
<P>
The inspection team will drop by training centers without
notifying athletes ahead of time, he added.
</P>
<P>
Test result will be submitted to the Olympic Committee of
Thailand, which makes the final decision on which athletes will
represent the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
