<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zhejiang Deepens Sea-Level-Change Research </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, October 15 (Xinhua) -- The sea level along the coast
of east China's Zhejiang Province has been rising steadily in
recent years, prompting oceanographers to deepen their research
into this change in a bid to prevent the province from possible
disaster.
</P>
<P>
Data collected from twelve sea-wave sample sites indicates the
sea level has risen more than 20 centimeters in the last four
decades, scientists said.
</P>
<P>
A rapid rise in the sea level could increase the incidence of
typhoons and lead to serious port and dike damage. Zhejiang
Province has the country's longest coastal line and bountiful
ocean resources, almost two-thirds of the province's production
is concentrated in the coastal areas.
</P>
<P>
If the sea level rises by 30 centimeters, the province could
suffer economic losses of more than one billion yuan (about 120
million U.S. dollars), according to experts.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
