<HEADLINE> New Zealand to Enroll More Students From China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, October 15 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand Thursday decided
to increase the quota for students from the People's Republic of
China from the current 1,000 to 4,000 places each year.
</P>
<P>
Observers here are of the view that the increase of the quota
is purely for earning money and hunting talents.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand Minister of Immigration Tuariki John Delamere,
while announcing the decision, said this increase is expected to
provide a net benefit of about 30 million NZ dollars (16.2 million
U.S. dollars) in New Zealand's international student sales and
benefit a wide range of education providers in secondary, tertiary
and English language training institutions in the country.
</P>
<P>
According to him, one student in New Zealand for 12 months will
spend approximately 20,000 NZ dollars (10,800 U.S. dollars) in
tuition fees and living expenses.
</P>
<P>
"The increase in the quota is also a real opportunity for
students from the People's Republic of China to develop a pathway
to residence by studying in New Zealand," Delamere added.
</P>
<P>
In the statement, he also announced the decision to allow
foreign students to work for up to 15 hours a week during
term-time to replace the current stipulation of only allowing them
to work during the Christmas vacation.
</P>
<P>
"Working part-time is an important factor for foreign students
choosing where to study," he explained.
</P>
<P>
At present, there are 7,500 foreign students studying in New
Zealand.
</P>
<P>
"We do want to be certain that the benefits to the economy will
outweigh any costs, so we have asked Work and Income NZ to monitor
any impact of foreign students on the labor market and report to
the government on this," Delamere said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
