<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Takes Steps to Curb Crime, Terrorism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 15 (Xinhua) -- The Indian government decided
Wednesday to set up a special task force to evolve and implement a
plan of action to tackle inter-state crime and terrorism in the
country.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made during a marathon meeting of chief
ministers of eight northern states and Union Home Minister L. K.
Advani, the Hindu daily reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting agreed to monitor and audit external funding to
non-governmental organizations working in various areas of the
country, a move clearly aimed at checking the possibility of
funding by foreign agencies to carry out subversive activities.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also suggested that central government make
stringent laws for driving license and passports.
</P>
<P>
Advani informed the chief ministers of the magnitude and extent
of damage caused by terrorism in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Hindu said that the Indian government had spent 460 billion
rupees (about 11.5 billion U.S. dollars) on army and para-military
forces deployed on internal security duty and other security
related expenses mounted to 1850 billion rupees (about 4.625
billion U.S. dollars), mainly account of compensation to victims,
border fencing and raising of counter-terrorist forces.
</P>
<P>
As many as 34,252 people have been killed and public and
private property worth over 20 billion rupees (500 million U.S.
dollars) has been damaged by terrorist activities, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
In his address to the meeting, Advani urged chief ministers of
the northern states to take effective measures for early disposal
of court cases.
</P>
<P>
It is significant that the meeting was held just one day before
the resumption of talks between India and Pakistan in Islamabad,
during which India will focus on trans-border terrorist activities
especially in Kashmir. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
