<HEADLINE> About 60 Denver-Based Cult Members Disappear </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 14 (Xinhua) -- As many as 60 members of a
cult, whose leader prophesied Denver would be destroyed,
disappeared more than two weeks ago, a cult monitoring group said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A news report from Denver said those who disappeared were
members of Concerned Christians. They abandoned their homes and
jobs to follow their charismatic leader Monte Kim Miller, 44, said
Hal Mansfield, director of the Religious Movement Resource Center.
</P>
<P>
Family members have been calling. They are worried and have not
heard from their missing relatives. They said the members were
fleeing Denver because Miller prophesied the city would be
``ground zero'' for an apocalyptic disaster last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Miller, who founded Concerned Christians, is suspected of
leading the group to either Jerusalem or Mexico.
</P>
<P>
Miller's empty home in southeast Denver is for sale. He and his
wife, Marcia, declared bankruptcy a year ago, owing more than
600,000 U.S. dollars, reports said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
