<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Adopts Measures to Protect Female Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, October 15 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan government has
announced sweeping measures to ensure the safety and welfare of
100,000 women employed in the two Free Trade Zones, according to
the official Daily News reports Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The government's main aim is improving the living conditions of
women employed in the Free Trade Zone of Katunayaka nearby Colombo
International Airport and Biyagama in the Western province, the
paper noted.
</P>
<P>
The changes will include the improvement in accommodation,
counseling services, health services, transport, street lighting,
police patrols and recreational facilities.
</P>
<P>
The reports said that one of the pressing problems faced by
these women was boarding facilities where as much as 80 women were
crammed into a single house. Low interest housing scheme will be
introduced to ease this problem.
</P>
<P>
Thirty graduates will be recruited and trained to advise women
employees experiencing personal and work related problems.
</P>
<P>
Government dispensaries adequately staffed by doctors, nurses
and public health inspectors will be opened in these zones.
Awareness programs on nutrition will be conducted and fish stalls
will be opened near the Zones, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Transport facilities in the zone will be strengthened and two
fully equipped sports complexes will be opened. 
</P>
</TEXT>
