<HEADLINE> Free Visits to Scenic Spots for Teachers in Zhejiang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Visiting scenic spots and
museums without buying tickets -- what a sweet dream for
travellers! Now more than 100,000 teachers in east China's
Zhejiang Province will enjoy this privilege.
</P>
<P>
The Provincial People's Congress recently passed a regulation
which offers free visits for teachers to parks and museums.
</P>
<P>
Teachers who have taught in the province for at least 30 years
and have received honorary certificates from the provincial
government will be able to visit any scenic spot or museum in
Zhejiang free of charge.
</P>
<P>
Zhejiang has scenic spots covering an area of 3,500 square
kilometers, ranking first in China. It has more than 100 museums
including the China Silk Museum, the China Tea Museum and the
Hemudu Site Museum.
</P>
<P>
"To have a view of Zhejiang's wonderful sights is my
long-cherished wish," said Xie Guangtian, head of the Hangzhou
Teachers College. Xie's family is regarded as "the home of
teachers," since three of the six teachers of his family have
received certificates.
</P>
<P>
"Free visits also show a trend toward holding teachers in
great esteem and attaching great importance to education," said
Xie.
</P>
<P>
More than 100,000 teachers in Zhejiang have at least 30 year's
teaching experience, and to date about 50,000 of them have been
given certificates.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
