<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Currency Still Competitive: Bank Governor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Bank of Thailand Governor
Chatumongol Sonakul has said that Thailand's export
competitiveness is still acceptable despite the fact the baht
value is strengthening.
</P>
<P>
"The baht, although making strong gains recently, remains
competitively priced against other currencies," the governor said
in remarks published by Thursday's Nation newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the competitiveness level is still in a range
suggested earlier by the International Monetary Fund (IMF)
regarding the devaluation of the Thai currency.
</P>
<P>
Calculation of export competitiveness is based on a study
comparing exports of 22 countries. Inflation, exchange rate and
export goods of each country are taken into account to gauge the
competitiveness against each other. The study does not exclude
Japan, which competes with Thailand in trade.
</P>
<P>
So far, the baht has continued to escalate against the
greenback on the back of the Japanese yen's rally. Baht ended on
Wednesday at 38.10 to the U.S. dollar from Tuesday's finish of
38.25.
</P>
<P>
The real effective exchange rate reached the highest level at
37.06 percent in late January as the baht hovered around 57 to the
dollar. But the baht had then risen against the greenback, leading
the country's export competitiveness to hit the lowest level at
12.46 percent as of September 30.
</P>
<P>
Chatumongol said the central bank will allow the dollar/baht
exchange rates to move in line with the market mechanism.
</P>
<P>
"We don't want to force the baht to weaken (to boost exports),
but the most important thing is to improve efficiency in various
sectors such as production, exports, agriculture and industrial,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
"That will certainly raise the country's export
competitiveness in the long run," he said.
</P>
<P>
Chatumongol said the bank may intervene to prevent rapid
changes in the value of the baht, given that the central bank does
not want it to dramatically change in the short-term.
</P>
<P>
He said the central bank continues to monitor the movement of
the baht in order to ensure that it remains at a competitive
level. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981015.0297 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Highlights of Beijing-based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
 "People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- The Third Plenary Session of the 15th Central Committee of
the Communist Party of China (CPC) was held in Beijing between
October 12 and 14 to reach a decision on certain
major issues concerning agriculture and rural work.
</P>
<P>
CPC General Secretary Jiang Zemin spoke at the session on
agricultural development and rural issues.
</P>
