<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Biotechnology Provides New Opportunities for Agriculture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Rapid advances in molecular
genetics, computing and information technology will dramatically
transform global agriculture in the 21st century and provide new
opportunities, particularly for developing countries.
</P>
<P>
An independent panel of international experts made the
prediction in its assessment report on the work of the
Consultative Group on International Agricultural Research.
</P>
<P>
The panel consists of experts from the United States, Japan,
Germany, South Africa, Britain and India.
</P>
<P>
The report said that 840 million people, mostly women and
children, were hungry today, and that the world's population would
rise by three billion by the year 2025.
</P>
<P>
Therefore global efforts should be made to harness
biotechnology to meet the needs of people and the environment.
</P>
<P>
The world was at cusp of a new scientific revolution in the
biological science. Breakthroughs included food crops with higher
yields and nutrition content, plants resistant to drought and
pests, livestock immune to disease, and sustainable fisheries.
</P>
<P>
The experts predicted that key contributions of biotechnology
could include:
</P>
<P>
-- higher food production without expanding farmland into
wilderness, rain forest or marginal lands that support
biodiversity and vital ecosystem services.
</P>
<P>
-- reducing post-harvest loss of food and improving the quality of
fresh and processed foods, thus boosting the "realized nutritional
yield" per acre.
</P>
<P>
-- displacing resource-and energy-intensive input, such as
fuel, fertilizers, or pesticides, thus reducing unintended impacts
on the environment and freeing those resources for other purposes
or conserved for the future.
</P>
<P>
-- encouraging the reduction of environmentally damaging
agricultural practices and adoption of more sustainable methods,
such as conservation tillage, precision agriculture, and
integrated crop management.
</P>
<P>
The private sector was investing enormous sums in biotechnology
research, nine billion U.S. dollars in 1997 in the United States
alone, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981015.0304 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
