<HEADLINE> CFA Suspends Coaches from Team Activities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 15 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese Football
Association (CFA) on Wednesday handed out the severest punishment
since the professional league was launched in the year 1994,
suspending two second division coaches from any team activities
for "play passive games".
</P>
<P>
Chen Yiming, coach of Chongqing Hongyan, and Wang Hongli,
manager at Liaoning Tianrun, were immediately revoked of coaching
licence because they "had inescapable responsibility for the
consequences" of the 21st round second division league matches
last weekend which "had extremely nasty implications", CFA
vice-president Nanyong said.
</P>
<P>
Hongyan, the third-placed side but already out of the
promotion race, was thumped by relegation-treatened Yunnan Hongta
4-0 while Tianrun, who had secured their top flight spot with two
games remaining, went down 4-2 to Chengdu Wuniu, the side they
stuffed a total of 17 goals in their three encounters this year.
</P>
<P>
The two clubs were each fined 50,000 RMB.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Tianrun club sacked Wang immediately after the
CFA announcement.
</P>
<P>
CFA made the decision among rampant media accusations that
match-fixing scandals have gripped and ripped the Chinese soccer
and the sport in the country is on the brink of being out of
control.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese soccer governing body did not exactly say the two
matches had been rigged in their Wednesday's announcement.
</P>
<P>
"The two clubs played passively and slacked off in the crucial
moment of the league, which violated the National Soccer
Competition Discipline Regulations and is against the fundamental
sporting spirits of fairplay," Nan said at the routine soccer
briefing yesterday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The second division league will start its last round of
matches on October 17. 
</P>
</TEXT>
