<HEADLINE> More Armed Group Members surrender in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, October 15 (Xinhua) -- A total of 42 members of an
anti-government armed group laid down their arms to the government
early this month, official newspaper The New Light of Myanmar
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The armed group members, which are the remnants of the Mong Tai
Army (MTA) armed group, "exchanged arms for peace" with the
government at the regional battalion in Namsam Township, Shan
State, on October 4.
</P>
<P>
Since January 1996, former drug warlord Khun Sa and his MTA
have unconditionally surrendered to the Myanmar government in
succession, bringing the number of the surrendered to 15,000 by
the end of May this year.
</P>
<P>
A total of 28 members of anti-government armed groups, most of
them are ethnic, laid down their arms and surrendered to the
government during last two months.
</P>
<P>
In April, Phado Aung San, former central committee member of
the ethnic Kayin National Union (KNU), which has been reportedly
operating on the Myanmar-Thai border in armed opposition against
the Myanmar government, crossed over to the government side with
more than 200 of his men in Hpa-an, the country's Kayin State, as
part of KNU's surrender.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, a total of 17 anti-government ethnic armed groups in
the country have made peace with the government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
