<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam to Launch Anti-AIDS Awareness Month </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam's National AIDS Committee
plans to launch a month-long awareness campaign on AIDS prevention
beginning on November 1st in light of the increasing rate of
HIV/AIDS infection in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
According to an official report Thursday, 10,336 HIV/AIDS
carriers had been identified in 60 of Vietnam's 61 provinces and
cities by October 10.
</P>
<P>
Of the infected, 1,893 have developed full-blown AIDS and 1,008
have died, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Ho Chi Minh City and the northern border province of Quang Ninh
have the highest numbers of HIV/AIDS cases in the country.
</P>
<P>
Only the northern border province of Ha Giang remains free from
the fatal disease.
</P>
<P>
The disease is spreading quickly in northern Vietnam,
especially among youths and working-age people.
</P>
<P>
Tests conducted on new army recruits in 1998 found 1.7 percent
to be infected with HIV compared with 1.3 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The rate of HIV carriers among prostitutes picked up at random
for tests has also increased from 4 percent last year to 7.3
percent this year.
</P>
<P>
Increasing drug abuse among young people is one of the reasons
behind the spread of the disease.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam will set up an HIV/AIDS behavioral surveillance system
early next year in addition to the current two HIV/AIDS-related
surveillance systems, according to Chung A, vice president of the
national committee.
</P>
<P>
Surveillance activities will be carried out in 20 provinces and
cities with high rates of HIV/AIDS infection with the aim to
define the mode of HIV transmission in Vietnam and to seek the
solutions.
</P>
<P>
The current two are the HIV/AIDS epidemiological surveillance
system and the monitoring and managing system of
sexually-transmitted patients. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981015.0316 </DOCNO>
