<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Impoverished Chinese Moved from Mountainous Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, October 15 (Xinhua) -- About 20,000 farmers living in
remote mountainous parts of Shanxi Province, north China, have
been relocated over the past few years, and another 150,000 people
will be moved to better places in the next five years, according
to a provincial poverty-relief plan.
</P>
<P>
Most of the province's 200,000 impoverished people are
scattered about in 3,600 villages in mountainous areas with little
access and bad soil, where it is very difficult for then to get
out of poverty.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government began the relocation drive in 1993,
and has since 1996 allocated 10 million yuan (about 1.2 million
U.S. dollars) annually in special funds for it.
</P>
<P>
This year, the provincial government will provide 150 million
yuan for the fund and 75 million yuan in loans for the cause. Most
of the funds will be used for production, housing, traffic, and
water conservation.
</P>
<P>
Seven counties with about 20,000 people are included in this
year's relocation program. The whole drive is expected to end by
the year 2002.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
