<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Officials Foil Attempt to Smuggle Snakes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian security officials
at Soekarno-Hatta International Airport here have foiled an
attempt to smuggle eight snakes to Moscow, the Jakarta Post
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The suspected smuggled, a Russian named Vladimir, was about to
board Aeroflot Flight 566 last Thursday evening when the airport
security noticed moving items in his bag through the X-ray
monitoring screen, head of the airport's animal quarantine center
Lukas A. Tonga said.
</P>
<P>
After a brief check, quarantine officials found the Russian's
specially designed bag was filled with snakes, including three
hazardous Papuan Taipans, which were unique to Irian Jaya
province.
</P>
<P>
"All of the snakes are very expensive. The dreadful taipans,
for example, cost 300 U.S. dollars here in Indonesia," said Wawan
Sutian, one of the quarantine's veterinarian.
</P>
<P>
He speculated that Vladimir was going to sell the snakes'
poison as it could be converted into valuable antivenin.
</P>
<P>
"The price of the antivenin ranges between 250 U.S. dollars and
1,000 U.S. dollars per ampoule, depending upon the level of the
poison," he said.
</P>
<P>
Similar to last month's finding, the airport's officials said
they failed to arrest the suspect as the Russian was already
boarding, the report said.
</P>
<P>
On September 29, airport officials also foiled a similar
attempt to take out of the country a collection of 67 reptiles,
including pythons, monitors and turtles, which were about to be
smuggled to Singapore.
</P>
<P>
The alleged owner of the bag Leong Kok Tieng managed to fly
without being able to be touched by the airport authorities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
