<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Government Calls for New CONI </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Italy's caretaker Sports Minister
Walter Veltroni on Wednesday called for a new Italian Olympic
Committee (CONI) after saying the government had found evidence
that CONI dope tests breached International Olympic Committee (I
OC) criteria.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to CONI vice-president Bruno Grandi, Veltroni
slammed the independent body for the way it ran sport in Italy
and ordered it to completely reform itself.
</P>
<P>
Veltroni wrote to Grandi after examining the findings of a
three-man government commission set up to investigate test
practices at CONI labs.
</P>
<P>
The investigation opened on September 14 following persistent
allegations in the Italian media that there were malpractice in
CONI's doping tests.
</P>
<P>
Since the commission was set up, CONI president Mario Pescante
has resigned, the head of the organisation's anti-doping panel
has stepped down, CONI's Rome laboratory has been shut and five
of its employees have been sacked.
</P>
<P>
Veltroni said the CONI of the future had to be "leaner and l
ess bureaucratic" and suggested a deadline of January 1, 1999, by
which reforms should be implemented. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
