<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Pak Economy Falling Deeper into Mire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 15 (Xinhua) -- The first quarter of 1998-99
fiscal year (July 1 to June 30 ) has ended on a rather dismal note
as the U.S.-led economic sanctions exert negative influence on
Pakistan's fragile economy.
</P>
<P>
All major economic indicators paint a vague picture and show
that Pakistan's economy, beset with years of structural problems,
is indeed in troubled water, altering the prospects of any
economic development in the near future.
</P>
<P>
The revenue collection during the first three months of the
current fiscal year has declined by 15 percent from an estimated
target of 67.70 billion rupees (46 rupees equals one U.S. dollar)
to about 58 billion rupees.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the government's bank borrowing for
budgetary purposes has burst the ceiling for the year, reaching an
astonishing 45 billion rupees in three months against the
estimated target of 43 billion rupees for the whole financial
year.
</P>
<P>
Panicked by the early trend seen in the revenue collection, the
government is reported to have decided to scale down the
projection of revenue collection for the current fiscal year from
354.6 billion rupees as envisaged in the budget for 1998-99 to 325
billion rupees.
</P>
<P>
The declining trend in revenue collection reflects the almost
total stagnation in the vital industrial sector and negative
production of investment related items like cement and steel. And
the consumption of oil make it more than obvious that in the
coming months this trend in revenue collection will become much
more marked.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that Pakistan's current economic crisis, with a
mountain of accumulated outstanding debt, is aggravated by the
economic sanctions in the wake of its nuclear detonation at the
end of May and freezing of foreign currency accounts. It is
undoubtedly the most serious one since Pakistan's inception in
1947.
</P>
<P>
The slowdown of the economy was initially started due to mainly
to the stagnancy of the agriculture sector after repeated failures
of the cotton crop. However, the crisis has been deepened by
contraction of the industrial sector and decline in the foreign
trade.
</P>
<P>
The export sector has made the matter doubly worrisome. The new
fiscal year has begun with a decline of as much as 20 percent in
exports in the three months, falling from 1.7 billion dollars to
1.4 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The imports, on the other hand, also continue to decline
keeping the trade deficit well in control. But that is no
consolation because the imports decline has affected the revenue
collection by the customs and it also indicates a declining trend
in investments which threatens to make the economy worse in the
coming months.
</P>
<P>
The workers' remittances are also showing declining trend. In
the first quarter of current fiscal year, the amount of
remittances is paltry 350 million dollars, a fall of as much as 40
percent against the comparable period in the last fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, foreign private investment during July, the first
month of current fiscal year, was estimated at only 22.7 million
dollars against 108 million dollars during the same month of last
fiscal year, registering a decrease of nearly 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
Textile exports, which play a pivotal role in the country's
export sector, have also decreased by 168.44 million dollars in
the first quarter of 1998-99, depicting an unabated recession.
</P>
<P>
The economic barometer suggests that Pakistan's economy is
facing serious problems, and it is extremely hard for an early
revival in the present setting.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here believe that limited capital, the non
availability of foreign exchange, the stagnant industrial sector
marked with weakening exports and lower investment will make the
economy of this south Asian nation all the more difficult in the
coming months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
