<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, October 15 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. President Bill Clinton will hold preliminary
talks with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and
Palestinian President Yasser Arafat at the White House on Thursday
to start the Middle East summit.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's meeting with the two leaders will be followed by a
Rose Garden appearance by all three at which Clinton will outline
the objectives of the summit, said White House spokesman Joe
Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu and Arafat will then leave for the Wye Plantation on
Maryland's Eastern Shore with U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright to begin the summit. (US-Mideast-Clinton)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- The Russian State Duma, the lower house of
parliament, Wednesday passed a statement on the situation in the
Balkans, which welcomes "the progress on a peaceful resolution to
the conflict in Kosovo."
</P>
<P>
According to the Interfax news agency, the document endorsed by
307 votes with six votes against said that the State Duma
unconditionally denounces any forms of aggression against the
Union Republic of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
It declared that in the event of unleashing military operations
by NATO member states against that country, considerable damage
will be caused to their relations with Russia, which will flare up
tension in Europe and the whole world. (Russia-Duma-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SHANGHAI -- Tang Shubei, executive vice-president of the
Association for Relations Across the Taiwan Strait (ARATS), said
here Wednesday that the two sides across the Taiwan Straits should
first have mutual trust under the one-China principle.
</P>
<P>
China's sovereignty and territorial integrity cannot be
separated, although the two sides have not yet got united, he
pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Both Wang Daohan, president of the ARATS, and Koo Chen-fu,
chairman of the Taiwan Straits Exchange Foundation (SEF), talked
about sincerity and mutual trust during their meeting today in
Shanghai, Tang said at a press conference. (China-Official-One
China Principle)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The 53rd General Assembly (GA) session
Wednesday convened a plenary meeting to discuss the necessity of
ending the economic, commercial and financial embargo imposed by
the United States on Cuba.
</P>
<P>
The meeting considered a report by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan, who submitted the report on September 3 at the request of a
GA resolution, adopted on November 5, 1997, which demanded an end
to the U.S. embargo against Cuba.
</P>
<P>
In the report, Annan listed replies he received from
governments on the issue, and most of the governments called for
an immediate end to such an embargo under the principle of the
U.N. Charter. (UN-US-Embargo-Cuba) 
</P>
</TEXT>
