<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NBA Studying Luxury Tax Proposal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 14 (Xinhua) -- NBA is studying carefully
the union's new luxury tax proposal Wednesday to see if it will
reduce the players' salary growth.
</P>
<P>
"We are going to examine every element of this tax to see
whether under some circumstance, at the right levels and in the
right amounts, a tax could work," commissioner David Stern said.
</P>
<P>
If the owners accept the idea and work out a counterproposal
Friday, it means the sides have found a way to negociate the core
issue in the lockout.
</P>
<P>
The lockout is now over 100 days, and the league canceled the
first two weeks of the season Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Both sides are awaiting a ruling from arbitrator John Feerick
on the union's grievance over whether more than 200 players with
guaranteed contracts should be paid during the lockout.
</P>
<P>
The players made their tax proposal Tuesday, indicating to
owners that they are willing to give ground to get the season
started. The tax would theoretically be a deterrent against
owners signing their own free agents to overly lucrative
long-term contracts.
</P>
<P>
But the owners said the tax proposal was far from a
breakthrough, yet they seemed surprised nonetheless that the
union was offering a way to control superstar salaries.
</P>
<P>
Under the union's offer, a 50 percent tax would be levied on
the amount of any annual salary over 18 million, with the tax
money to be redistributed to low-revenue teams.
</P>
<P>
Stern indicated that the owners might accept a luxury tax
proposal if it included a fall-back provision that included a
hard cap. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
