<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Build Grain Warehouse with Huge Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 15 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government has
decided to put 15 billion yuan (1.8 billion US dollars) into
building grain warehouses this year, an investment in a single
year 30 times as much as in previous years to deal with the
country's acute shortage of grain storage capacity.
</P>
<P>
It is part of 100 billion yuan that was raised in the latest
treasury bond issue aimed at boosting infrastructure investment
and will be used for warehouses to keep 25 billion kilograms of
grain in state reserves, according to the State Development
Planning Commission.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the facilities will be completed before the
harvest next summer, the commission said, adding that 45 of them
are under construction.
</P>
<P>
Every year, only about 500 million yuan is used for grain
warehouses for state reserves, far less than what is needed.
</P>
<P>
There are only 15 special warehouses for state grain reserves,
which can hold a mere 0.02 percent of the total reserves. The rest
is stored in rented facilities.
</P>
<P>
Local warehouses are small and many are located in remote
areas, which affects macro-economic controls of the central
government, said a commission official.
</P>
<P>
China's grain market reforms call for the strict separation of
central and local government grain reserves, so more warehouses
are badly needed, he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981015.0355 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Big Names Fail to Shine at Euro Soccer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 14 (Xinhua) -- World soccer big names failed
to impress at the European Soccer Championships qualifying
matches on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
World champions France, who were expected to score a hatful
against their neighbouring part-timers Andorra, managed only a
2-0 win at the Stade de France, their first match back in the
stadium where they defeated Brazil to lift the World Cup in July.
</P>
<P>
They were forced to wait until the 53rd minute before Vincent
Candela opened the scoring in their group four match, and even
though Youri Djorkaeff added a second eight minutes later, the
moral victory was Andorra's if not the points, which moved France
up to second behind Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
European champions Germany, who started the defence of their
European title with a shock 1-0 group three defeat in Turkey on
Saturday, were given another scare when they went behind after
only eight minutes to Moldova -- before re-asserting the natural
order of things with a 3-1 win.
</P>
<P>
Just as on Saturday there was another big shock in Turkey --
but this time it was the hosts who went crashing, losing 3-1 to
Finland.
</P>
<P>
The Finns, who have never qualified for a European
championship or World Cup, currently top the standings with six
points, ahead of Turkey on goal difference -- but Germany, on
three points, have a match in hand.
</P>
<P>
England, another big name who have made an indifferent start
to the qualifiers. again failed to impress despite winning 3-0 in
Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
They remained third in group five on four points behind
Poland, who did not play, and Sweden, who won a tough match in
Bulgaria 1-0.
</P>
<P>
Sweden, who beat England 2-1 in their first match five weeks
ago, won with a 62nd minute goal from Henrik Larsson for a
victory that gave them a maximum return of six points from their
opening games.
</P>
<P>
Spain, another traditional force struggling to find form, also
had to come from behind to beat Israel, winning 2-1 in Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
Spain remain third in group six behind Austria, who won 4-1 in
San Marino, and the Israelis, who have both played one match more.
</P>
<P>
But there was no respite for Russia, who slumped to their
third successive defeat in group four, losing 1-0 to Iceland in
Reykjavik and finishing a thoroughly miserable night with only 10
men after Alexei Smertin was sent off 16 minutes from time.
</P>
<P>
Iceland's winner came two minutes from time from Runar
Kristinsson.
</P>
<P>
Russia had previously lost to Ukraine and France and already
look out of contention.
</P>
<P>
There was a thrilling group eight match in Zagreb where
Croatia beat Macedonia 3-2 thanks in part to two goals from
Zvonimir Boban after 45 and 70 minutes.
</P>
<P>
Macedonia had started the day in top place in the group, but
fell back to third with Croatia moving up to second after winning
two of their three opening games.
</P>
<P>
And there was another good game in Cardiff, where Wales, who
have been in the international doldrums for years, chalked up
their second win in four days with a 3-2 comeback victory over
Belarus.
</P>
<P>
That win lifted Wales level on points with group leaders
Italy, who have one match in hand.
</P>
<P>
In the same group Ole Tobiasen scored in the last minute as
Denmark, the 1992 European champions, forced a 1-1 draw with
Switzerland in Zurich.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's 22 matches completed a "double-header" round of
qualifiers following the 20 played on Saturday but there is still
an unfamiliar look to most of the groups with Latvia, Ukraine,
and Ireland setting the pace in their tables.
</P>
<P>
Latvia remain on top of group two despite going down 1-0 to
Slovenia.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine maintained their 100 percent record and first place in
group four with a 2-0 win over Armenia, while Ireland stayed top
of group eight and were the biggest winners of the night by
crushing Malta 5-0.
</P>
<P>
The Czech Republic stay top of the group after crushing
Estonia 4-1.
</P>
<P>
Scotland, who are second and won for the second time in four
days after beating Estonia on Saturday, were jeered by the
Aberdeen crowd who felt let down by their team's performance in
their 2-1 win over the Faroes Islands.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile there was a memorable night for Liechtenstein.
</P>
<P>
After losing 19 of their 20 previous competitive matches,they
won a competitive game for the first time ever -- beating
Azerbaijan 2-1 in Vaduz.
</P>
<P>
Liechtenstein, who lost nine and drew one of their 10 Euro'96
qualifiers and lost all 10 of their France '98 World Cup
qualifers, finally broke their duck with a 47th minute penalty
from Mario Frick and a second two minutes later from Martin
Telser.
</P>
<P>
Azerbaijan replied with a Kurban Kurbanov goal after 59
minutes, but that was not enough to spoil the celebrations of the
1,900 home crowd. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
