<DOCNO> XIE19981015.0361 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gamma Bursts May Come from Supernovas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Some of the powerful gamma ray
bursts may come from the explosion of dying stars called
supernovas, astronomers suggested Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Researchers at the California Institute of Technology in
Pasadena, United States, said they have observed an unusual
supernova, which occurred at about the same time, and in
approximately the same direction, as a burst of gamma rays.
</P>
<P>
Writing in the scientific journal Nature, the researchers said
the supernova was accompanied by a relativistic shock wave, which
they suggested produced the burst of gamma rays.
</P>
<P>
The supernova may have generated the gamma ray burst by
ejecting a stream of material at close to the speed of light, the
researchers said.
</P>
<P>
The sources of gamma ray bursts, which produces high-energy
powerful light, have puzzled astronomers for more than twenty
years. Until now scientists had thought that supernovas and gamma
ray bursts were unrelated.
</P>
<P>
The supernova connected with the gamma ray burst occurred
relatively close to the earth, a phenomenon so unusual to the
researchers that they argued this unusual supernova established a
distinctly different second class of gamma-ray burst.
</P>
<P>
The American researchers' conclusion was echoed in a separate
report in Nature. Scientists form the University of Amsterdam, the
Netherlands, suggested that the very unusual supernova may have
been the birth of a black hole.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981015.0362 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rudolph Charged with 1996 Olympics Bombing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 14 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Federal authorities on
Wednesday charged Eric Robert Rudolph, one of the FBI's 10
most-wanted fugitives, with bombings including one blasted in
the Centennial Park in Atlanta during the 1996 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
Attorney General Janet Reno said the criminal complaint
charging Rudolph with the Olympic blast and the 1997 bombings of a
gay bar and an abortion clinic was being filed with a federal
court.
</P>
<P>
Reno said that Rudolph is on the run. But she said, "We are
going to keep searching until we find him and we're not going to
rest until we bring him to justice."
</P>
<P>
Louis Freeh, Director of the Federal Bureau of Investigation
(FBI), said Rudolph "now is charged with six bombings," including
three in Atlanta and the January 29 bombing of a Birmingham,
Alabama, abortion clinic.
</P>
<P>
Rudolph was placed on the FBI's Most Wanted List last May, and
a one million U.S. dollars reward was offered based on earlier
charges that he bombed a Birmingham abortion clinic.
</P>
<P>
Rudolph was publicly linked to the Atlanta attacks last month
when it was learned a Tennessee gun dealer identified Rudolph as
the man who bought a special order of 50 pounds of smokeless
powder four years ago. Law enforcement official determined that
powder has been connected to the 1996 bombing at Centennial
Olympic Park.
</P>
<P>
The Olympic bombing killed one person and wounded more than 100
others. An off-duty policeman working as a guard was killed and a
nurse was injured in the Birmingham bombing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
