<HEADLINE> IDB Okays Loan for Agriculture Sector in Uruguay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The Inter-American
Development Bank (IDB) Wednesday announced the approval of a 32.4
million U.S. dollar loan to Uruguay to improve agricultural
technology.
</P>
<P>
The project will benefit small and medium-size producers and
improve the sanitary quality verification process for animal
products.
</P>
<P>
The project will contribute to the technological transformation
of the chain of agricultural production by investing in 11
strategic technological projects as well as in applied research
projects submitted directly by potential beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
The resources will be also used in technology transfer in the
areas of technology validation, professional training, and
dissemination of technologies.
</P>
<P>
The total cost of the project is some 50.3 million dollars.
Local counterpart funds total 17.9 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981015.0364 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Least Developed Countries Vulnerable to Price Falls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The inclement weather
and the commodity prices falls are likely to put a brake on the
recent economic recovery in the 48 least developed countries
(LDCs), the United Nations warned on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The LDCs, mostly in Africa, have a combined population of 600
million and an average per capita GDP of about 230 U.S. dollars.
They recorded another solid performance in 1997, the latest year
that the U.N. has been able to comply data.
</P>
<P>
LDCs gross domestic product averaged 4.8 percent against 3.2
percent for the world economy and 5.4 percent for developing
countries as a whole, down from the 5.5 percent they chalked in
1996, the U.N. Conference on Trade and Development (UNCTAD) said
in its latest report on LDCs.
</P>
<P>
Looking ahead, UNCTAD said devastating floods in Bangladesh and
above-average rainfall in Bhutan and Nepal this year and hurricane
damage in Haiti foreshadow further difficulties in 1999.
</P>
<P>
"What makes the LDCs especially vulnerable to the vagaries of
the weather and world commodity prices is their lack of export
diversification", UNCTAD said.
</P>
<P>
Over the past decade, most LDCs' exports have been limited to
two or three products, almost all of which were sold in raw or
semi-processed form.
</P>
<P>
Of the 28 LDCs for which there are comparable export data, only
five reduced their commodity dependence during the decade.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, their integration into world trade has declined,
compared with that of other developing countries, UNCTAD noted.
</P>
<P>
Output in 1996 represented less than one percent of world GDP
and their export share was only around 0.4 percent. Among the 48
LDCs, only 29 are World Trade Organization members.
</P>
<P>
The LDCs received only 1.5 percent of foreign direct investment
flows into developing countries and their share of worldwide flows
was only 0.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Official development assistance (ODA) from OECD (Organization
for Economic Cooperation and Development) countries dropped to
0.05 percent of their GDP in 1996, down from 0.06 percent
previously.
</P>
<P>
The LDCs faced a grim debt picture with a combined external
debt of 134 billion dollars in 1996, equivalent to 90 percent of
their total GDP.
</P>
<P>
Many LDCs have been unable to meet debt-serving obligations and
have had to request rescheduling of official debt, UNCTAD said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981015.0365 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IDB Assists Waste Management in Barbados </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The Inter-American
Development Wednesday announced the approval of a 13 million U.S.
dollar loan to the Barbados to assist in the development of
efficient waste management system.
</P>
<P>
The resources will help finance a waste disposal system that
will include an engineered sanitary landfill, a solid waste
transfer station and transfer equipment, a bulky waste landfill,
and yard waste composting facility.
</P>
<P>
An education component of the program will promote waste
minimization activities and environmental enhancements.
</P>
<P>
The total cost of the project is some 21 million dollars. Local
counterpart funds total 8 million dollars. 
</P>
