<HEADLINE> Canada Records Surplus, Cautious on Tax Cuts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Canadian Finance Minister Paul
Martin said Wednesday that the Canadian government has got a
3.5-billion-dollar (2.3 billion U.S. dollars) budget surplus, but
it is still not the time for big tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
"This is an historic milestone. And it is an achievement that
belongs not to the government but to Canadians themselves," Martin
told the House of Commons Finance Committee in his annual economic
and fiscal update.
</P>
<P>
The surplus has been applied directly to the national debt,
which were 579.7 billion dollars at the end of the 1997-98 fiscal
year.
</P>
<P>
Yet, despite the improvement in the country's finances, Martin
said it is still too early to cut taxes. "We must be realistic
about the resources at our disposal," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Safeguarding our financial health at home is the sine qua non
of riding out the global storm we are now in," he noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
