<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FAO Promotes Women's Role on World Food Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Marking this year's World Food
Day on October 16, a world food body will use global telecast to
encourage the participation of women in food production, and raise
money to help them become more productive.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference at the Near East head office of the Food
and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations (FAO) in Cairo
Wednesday, Atif Y. Bukhari, the FAO representative for the Near
East, announced the inauguration of the TeleFood '98 campaign in
the Near East.
</P>
<P>
TeleFood global telecast, an annual project initiated by FAO in
1997 in support of its campaign to end hunger around the world,
will highlight women's decisive role in household and national
food security during this year's World Food Day celebrations
events from Thursday to Sunday, according to the official.
</P>
<P>
Under the theme "Women Feed the World" of TeleFood 98,
television and radio programs will transmit to the world pictures
and information highlighting women's contribution to the battle
against poverty and hunger, and urging solidarity to reach the
goal of "Food for All."
</P>
<P>
On a global scale, women produce more than half of all the food
that is grown. In sub-Saharan Africa and the Caribbean, they
produce up to 80 percent of basic foodstuffs. In Asia, they
provide from 50 to 90 percent of the labor for rice cultivation.
</P>
<P>
Despite their contributions to food security, women tend to be
invisible actors in development and their role is poorly
understood and often underestimated, Bukhari told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"The fight against hunger is not an issue of charity: it is an
issue of justice... We have to act to help poor farmers,
especially women, gain access to the tools and knowledge to feed
their families and community. TeleFood offers us an opportunity to
express our solidarity and commitment to eradicate hunger," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The majority of the Arab countries' television stations will
broadcast programs since October 15, to raise the public awareness
to the tragedies of 800 million people who suffer from chronic
hunger and the fact that more than 10 children under the age of
five die of hunger or malnutrition every minute. Donations will be
collected to finance more projects for ending poverty.
</P>
<P>
"Give women the money, the education and whatever help they
need to produce, and see what they can. I think that's what the
TeleFood 98 is all about," Assel el-Dessouky, the assistant to
information officer at the Near East office, told Xinhua after the
press conference.
</P>
<P>
Last year, 500 million people in more than 60 countries
participated in the first global TeleFood campaign, which featured
performances and statements of solidarity from international
singers, actors, and athletes.
</P>
<P>
Viewers learned face to face about the affliction of hunger and
contributed more than 2 million U.S. dollars to help poor farmers
produce food where it is most needed.
</P>
<P>
Bukhari said the Near East countries have benefited
considerably from these donations, getting a total of 125,540
dollars, which enabled FAO to establish 20 projects in seven
countries, including the famine-stricken Sudan where the
percentage of employed women working in agriculture is 82 percent.
</P>
<P>
"Donations from last year's first TeleFood are not huge, but
they will definitely grow in the future. And after all, TeleFood
is more about awareness than money," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
