<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yugoslav Govt Endorses Milosevic-Holbrooke Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The Yugoslav government on
Wednesday fully endorsed the accord reached by Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic and U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke, the Yugoslav
Information Secretariat said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The accord, reached on Tuesday after nine days intensive talks,
"provides for resolving all issues in Serbia's southern province
of Kosovo in a peaceful manner, respecting the territorial
integrity and sovereignty of the Republic of Serbia and the
Federal Republic of Yugoslavia, and averts the threats of military
intervention against the country," Yugoslav news agency Tanjug
quoted the statement as saying.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Yugoslavia will allow a 2,000-strong
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) force
into Kosovo to ensure it complies with U.N. demands for the
withdrawal of Serbian troops and the return of refugees driven out
of home during the seven-month conflict in the province.
</P>
<P>
"The Yugoslav government fully endorses the decisions and
stances defined by Serbian government and Serbian President Milan
Milutinovic in order to implement the accord," said the statement
which was issued after the government held a session chaired by
Prime Minister Momir Bulatovic.
</P>
<P>
The government of Serbia, which makes up the Federal Republic
of Yugoslavia with Montenegro, endorsed the Milosevic-Holbrooke
deal on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Tanjug said the Yugoslav government has finalized the text of
its agreement with OSCE on its Verification Mission in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav government had also empowered Foreign Minister
Zivadin Jovanovic to sign this agreement with OSCE Chairman,
Bronislaw Geremek, who is expected to fly into Belgrade on Friday
to sign the agreement.
</P>
<P>
As part of the process of verification and implementation of
the Security Council Resolution 1199, "Yugoslavia will allow a
non-combat airplane to observe the situation in Kosovo with the
aim of peaceful verification," the statement said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
