<HEADLINE> EU Envoy Stresses Comprehensive Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, October 14 (Xinhua) -- European Union (EU) envoy said
Wednesday that there will be no just peace in the Middle East
unless the peace drive on Syrian- and Lebanese-Israeli tracks are
also revived.
</P>
<P>
Miguel Angel Moratinos, the EU special envoy to the Middle
East, made the remarks after talks with Syria Foreign Minister
Farouq al-Sharaa on the latest developments in the Mideast peace
process.
</P>
<P>
His words came just one-day ahead of the three-way summit near
Washington among U.S. President Bill Clinton, Palestinian National
Authority President Yasser Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Moratinos said it is high time to stress that all the tracks in
the peace process should be stimulated.
</P>
<P>
Arafat and Netanyahu will arrive in Washington Thursday to try
to wrap up a deal on further Israeli troops redeployment in the
West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Moratinos said that he has briefed Sharaa on the outcome of his
recent talks with Palestinians, Israeli and U.S. officials and the
EU's role in the Syrian-Israeli peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian-Israeli talks have been stalled since early 1996 and
Syria has refused to resume talks with Israel unless it agrees to
return the Golan Heights, which Israel captured from Syria in the
1967 Middle East war.
</P>
<P>
Moratinos also said that he has discussed with Sharaa the
on-going tensions between Syria and Turkey and the EU's efforts to
defuse the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Syria has been criticizing the U.S. for conniving at Israel's
intransigence.
</P>
<P>
Statistics showed that since the signing of the Oslo Accords in
1993, Israel has been building settlements in occupied Arab land
while demolishing Palestinian homes.
</P>
<P>
Syria said the events manifested that the Israeli leaders are
using the appeasement policy of the U.S. to gain more benefits,
prolong its occupation, accelerate settlement building under the
pretext of security. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
