<HEADLINE> Nigerian Opposition Leader Returns From Exile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian opposition leader and
Nobel literature laureate Wole Soyinka Wednesday returned home
from four years of self exile.
</P>
<P>
Soyinka, who arrived at the Lagos International Airport
Wednesday evening aboard a Lufthansa flight, was met at the
airport by his friends and well-wishers, said local radio
reports.
</P>
<P>
Soyinka's return marks a major step taken by the country's
exiled opposition groups in response to Nigerian Head of State
General Abdulsalam Abubakar's repeated call on them to return and
join the on-going democratization program.
</P>
<P>
Several other opposition members had already returned to the
country from exile earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
He is expected to pay a condolence visit to the family of
Moshood Abiola, the alleged winner of the annulled June 12, 1993
presidential election who died last July on the eve of his
release from four years of detention.
</P>
<P>
Soyinka is also expected to deliver a speech in Lagos Friday
on the transition to civil rule program and the future of the
most populous African country.
</P>
<P>
The opposition leader escaped Nigeria in 1994 after he was
banned from traveling by the then government of late General Sani
Abacha.
</P>
<P>
Since his succession of Abacha in June, Nigeria's new leader
Abubakar has taken bold steps in promoting national
reconciliation and democratization.
</P>
<P>
He has released all political detainees and opened dialog with
opposition groups, and announced a new transition program that is
scheduled to usher in an elected civilian government by May 29,
1999.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar called on the country's self-exiled opposition
members to return and join what he called the "all-inclusive"
democratization process. To show his sincerity, the Nigerian
head of state ordered the withdrawal of all charges against them.
</P>
<P>
Soyinka indicated his willingness to return in September when
he met with Abubakar in New York where the latter was attending
the 53rd United Nations General Assembly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
