<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romanian Parliament Okays Access by NATO Aircraft over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The Romanian Parliament on
Wednesday passed the decision of the Supreme National Defense
Council (CSAT) to grant access over its airspace to NATO "in
emergency and unforeseen situations".
</P>
<P>
CSAT, on October 11, as an answer to the request by the NATO,
decided to allow the NATO aircrafts access the Romanian airspace
"in emergency and unforeseen situations", and also gave green
light to Romania' participation in peace-keeping and humanitarian
operations with a Humanitarian Support Multifunctional Mobile
Detachment, formed by a medical section, another section for
refugees housing and a third one for reconstructing crashed
dwellings.
</P>
<P>
Romanian political parties were divided in their reaction to
the decision. Many appreciated the non-participation decision in
NATO military operation in Yugoslavia and considered it to be in
line with international practice to offer Romania's airspace to
NATO in emergency.
</P>
<P>
But others emphasized that Romania should not provide any help
to NATO by noting that to open airspace is equal to providing
logistic assistance to it.
</P>
<P>
Defense Minister Victor Babiuc, one of the key members of CSAT,
Wednesday stressed in the Parliament sitting that the decision of
CSAT has "humanitarian" and not "military" goals. "Romania has
never intended to involve at a military level, just at a
humanitarian one," he said, explaining that the CSAT decision
singles out four ideas: peaceful playing down of the conflict,
allowing NATO aircrafts to fly over Romania's territory in
emergency and unforeseen situations, Romania' s staying back from a
military involvement in the conflict and a post-conflict
participation with a multifunctional mobile division for
humanitarian support.
</P>
<P>
Romania makes no act of aggression against Yugoslavia by this
decision, as long as the support towards NATO is of humanitarian
nature, the Defense Minister added, in response to some previous
statements of the oppositions.
</P>
<P>
President Emil Contantinescu hailed the Parliament soon after
the vote, appreciating this legislative institution's capacity to
overcome its political disputes and biases. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
